<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / International Company News: Anhueser-Busch in Japan deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS and EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Anheuser-Busch and Kirin, respectively the biggest beer makers in the US and
Japan, have reached a deal that will bring Anheuser-Busch's new iced beer to
Japan under the name of Kirin Ice Beer.
The move marks a strengthening of the relationship between the two companies
following their decision last year to create a joint venture called
Budweiser Japan.
Anheuser-Busch's ice-brewing process involves passing the beer through a
special ice chamber where ice crystals are formed and keeping it in
ultra-cold storage for several days.
Kirin Ice Beer will be brewed at Anheuser-Busch's Los Angeles brewery using
a recipe adjusted to Japanese tastes, and will be packed in cans made by
Anheuser-Busch's Metal Container subsidiary in Windsor, Colorado. It will be
launched at the end of May.
Anheuser-Busch and Kirin, which recently exchanged token equity stakes of
about Y500m (Dollars 4.6m) are planning further co-operation in beer
production and material procurement.
Kirin aims to lower its production costs by gradually shifting beer
production and beer can supply to Anheuser in the US. The two companies plan
to co-operate in procuring wheat and other materials, and in looking for new
business opportunities in Asia.
Other Japanese beer companies, faced with high production costs and
competition from cheaper imports, are expected to reach similar deals with
foreign beer makers.
</TEXT>
