<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / International Company News: Bavaria nets DM2.3bn from sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MUNICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Bavarian government is to pocket DM2.3bn (Dollars 1.3bn) in cash - about
double the figure expected - from the sale of its stake in the Bayernwerk
electricity utility to Viag, the energy-based conglomerate.
The cash settlement, announced yesterday, is in addition to a
previously-agreed 25.1 per cent stake in the enlarged Viag group, which will
become one of Germany's top 10 companies in terms of sales. Combined
turnover of the two businesses is about DM40bn.
The deal, billed as the biggest German privatisation project to date, was
unveiled yesterday in a flurry of electioneering propaganda and upbeat
forecasts from the buyer.
Mr Edmund Stoiber, a prominent member of the Christian Social Union party,
one of the three coalition partners in Bonn, pledged the cash proceeds would
be used to build universities and fund research and not 'to fill gaps in the
budget'.
The Bavarian government's 25.1 per cent stake in the new-look Viag would be
sold within the next five years, so no-one could accuse him of
re-nationalisation, he said.
The group needed a stable shareholder structure while it went about its
restructuring programme, Mr Stoiber added.
Viag predicted respectable profits for 1993 and an unchanged dividend of
DM9. It promised a shake-out of the group's industrial holdings, and an
increase in earnings per share of at least 10 per cent by 1995.
According to Mr Georg Obermeier, finance director, the company could have
raised the dividend for 1993, but had decided an increase was not
appropriate at a time of rising unemployment and depression.
The group had neither 'a shopping list nor a selling list', according to Mr
Alfred Pfeiffer, chairman. But executives said future core industrial
businesses - apart from energy, accounting for 20 per cent of sales in the
enlarged group and 55 per cent of profits - would be packaging, chemicals,
logistics and corporate telecommunications.
Five firms of independent auditors had valued Bayernwerk at DM8.9bn and Viag
at DM10.2bn, he said. These figures justified a financial consideration of
DM1.85bn in return for the government's 58.3 per cent stake in the utility,
but the quality of Bayernwerk was deemed to be worth another DM450m.
Under present arrangements Viag owns 38.8 per cent in Bayernwerk, which in
turn has 24.9 per cent of Viag.
</TEXT>
