<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / International Company News: Sumitomo Cement plans merger
with smaller rival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A government-inspired restructuring of Japan's overcrowded cement industry
took a step forward yesterday when the fourth and eighth largest producers
announced merger plans.
Sumitomo Cement and its smaller competitor Osaka Cement are to join forces
from October, to form Japan's second largest cement maker, with 18.3 per
cent of the market and combined annual sales of Y211.1bn (Dollars 1.9bn).
Their marriage is driven by the forces behind last November's merger of
Onoda Cement, Japan's largest producer, with Chichubu Cement, the number
six, to consolidate Onoda's market leadership, with nearly a quarter of the
country's annual cement demand.
Both mergers are designed to seek economies of scale in an overcrowded
market worsened by the collapse in construction orders during this
recession. 'The cement industry in our nation is facing sluggish demand and
harsh cost competition. So we have decided to merge in order to better grow
in such an international era,' said a joint statement.
Before announcing the deal, the pair consulted the Ministry of International
Trade and Industry which was informally encouraging alliances among Japan's
22 cement makers, said the ministry The final decision to merge was made by
the companies themselves, it emphasised. Sumitomo Cement made the first
move.
Between 2 per cent and 3 per cent of Japan's 90m tonne cement production
capacity was surplus to requirements, the ministry estimated: 'In the long
term, cement makers must restructure because the market is receding.'
Some private sector forecasters argue the cement industry needs more
slimming than suggested by the ministry. Less than 10 producers would
suffice to meet domestic demand, believes Nomura Research Institute.
Osaka Cement will be dissolved after the merger and its president, Mr
Tetsunosuke Hamada, will become chairman of the new group. He forecast large
savings on production, distribution, capital investment and research and
development.
The new group expects a Y5.2bn pre-tax profit in the year to March 1996, its
first full trading year, rising to Y7.5bn in the following year, said Mr
Shoichi Tatemoto, president of Sumitomo Cement, who will be president of the
new company. It will be named Sumitomo Osaka Cement.
</TEXT>
