<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Skirmishes in battle for Westland - War of
words over order prospects and GKN's reasons for bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The battle for control of Westland turned more hostile yesterday after the
helicopter manufacturer accused GKN of employing shallow arguments and
misleading information in its Pounds 496m takeover bid.
Mr Alan Jones, chairman of the Yeovil-based manufacturer, said the
engineering and industrial services group had tried to cast doubt on its
order prospects, while disguising its own motives for the takeover.
'GKN does not appear to understand the value of Westland's future business.
The real savings arising from the possible acquisition appear to be tax
benefits for GKN,' he said.
His criticism, contained in a letter to shareholders, prompted an angry
response from GKN, which has offered Westland investors 290p per ordinary
share.
Sir David Lees, GKN chairman, said: 'Mr Jones has totally failed to address
the real issue, that is the price. Why should we overpay for his optimism
about future orders?'
He also dismissed Westland's claim that there was no synergy between the
helicopter business and GKN's armoured vehicles division.
GKN believes the two operations could pool their logistical and marketing
operations. It has also pledged additional financial support for the
company.
GKN is in a strong position to win control of Westland - having boosted its
existing holding to 45 per cent.
Mr Jones, said: 'Collaboration with GKN would add no value to Westland's
businesses. Westland has the financial strength to achieve its objectives
and does not need the shelter of a larger group.'
Both companies have started an intensive lobbying campaign to win the
support of institutional shareholders.
M&amp;G and Schroders, the two largest, have indicated they regard the offer as
too low.
Westland shares closed down 2p at 327p, a 13 per cent premium to the offer
price.
</TEXT>
