<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Falling sales to British Gas cut Victaulic
to Pounds 11.8m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Falling sales to British Gas helped to depress 1993 pre-tax profits at
Victaulic, maker of pipeline products for the gas, water, and construction
industries.
Profits fell by 12.5 per cent from Pounds 13.5m to Pounds 11.8m. Total
turnover edged ahead from Pounds 101.2m to Pounds 101.4m, although the
latest figure included Pounds 900,000 from Action Hose Couplings, acquired
in August.
The group said that since 1991 its sales to the UK gas industry had fallen
by 47 per cent. Last year sales to British Gas declined by about Pounds 8.5m
to Pounds 22m.
Mr David Stewart, managing director, said yesterday that although it was now
clear that British Gas would keep its pipeline distribution system, it would
not be clear until autumn how much it would be able to charge independent
producers to use it. 'It is difficult for British Gas to review their
investment programme, and we expect no great recovery in sales to British
Gas this year', he said.
The group has reacted by pushing to open up new markets, and increased
export sales from Pounds 9m to Pounds 15m. Exports accounted for 23 per cent
of group turnover last year.
Lindapter, a specialist fixings maker acquired late in 1992, contributed
Pounds 4.5m to turnover, and Action Hose Couplings a further Pounds 1m.
Net cash at the end of the year was up from Pounds 6.2m to Pounds 14.3m, and
the group is looking for further acquisitions in order to diversify from the
UK water and gas sectors.
Earnings per share eased from 20.3p to 18.4p. The group is proposing to lift
the final dividend from 5.3p to 5.5p, making the total pay-out 8p (7.8p). Mr
Stewart said the dividend rise was justifiable, given the strong balance
sheet, high cover and cash generative nature of the group.
</TEXT>
