<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Enterprise Oil hits Pounds 95m despite
falling prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Enterprise Oil, the largest UK exploration and production company, yesterday
reported an 8.9 per cent rise in 1993 net profits to Pounds 94.7m despite
the sharp slide in crude oil prices.
Record production of 158,914 barrels of oil equivalent a day (including
natural gas) boosted turnover to Pounds 546.1m, compared with Pounds 524.4m
last time.
The company also benefited from a sharp fall in tax from Pounds 57.9m to
Pounds 5.1m. That was because of changes in the petroleum revenue tax regime
in the UK and lower Norwegian taxes.
Earnings per share fell by 1.5p to 17p but a final dividend of 6.5p holds
the total at 16p. The enhanced scrip dividend alternative to the interim
dividend was taken up by 98 per cent of shareholders, saving the company
Pounds 44.3m in cash. It also reduced advance corporation tax liabilities by
Pounds 12.9m.
Mr Graham Hearne, chairman and chief executive, said Enterprise was better
placed than most exploration and production companies to weather low oil
prices because of its 'rising production and cash flows.' These were boosted
last month by the start-up of the Pounds 1.1bn Nelson field, the first field
of which Enterprise is the operator.
Analysts generally welcomed the results and Enterprise shares closed at
421p, up a penny. But there were warnings that future performance could
suffer if oil prices stay low.
Mr David Basham, at brokers Kleinwort Benson, noted that the 1993 results
were boosted by a high sterling oil price in the first half of the year of
Pounds 12.39 a barrel. This fell to an average of Pounds 11.58 for the whole
year, and is down to Pounds 9.40 for the first two months of 1994.
The company is responding by cutting costs and curtailing exploration.
Capital expenditure last year fell to Pounds 329.4m (Pounds 450.4m), while
spending on exploration and appraisal was down to Pounds 67m (Pounds 89.9m).
But the company added 60.3m barrels to its reserves, equivalent to 104 per
cent of total production last year.
COMMENT
The fact that Enterprise managed to maintain its dividend in the face of
real oil prices at the lowest level in 20 years showed its financial
strength. But even the strongest independent must tremble at the prospect
that prices will continue to hover around Dollars 13-Dollars 14 a barrel.
For an exploration and production company there are only a few ways to find
relief from low prices. In Enterprise's case diversification appears to have
been ruled out. Cutting costs helps, but the quickest way is to curtail
exploration, and the critical test for such companies remains their ability
to replace reserves over time. The remaining alternative is one which must
be looking increasingly attractive - the acquisition of low-cost assets with
future potential at knockdown prices.
</TEXT>
