<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Restructure costs cut Logica 22% to Pounds
3.2m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Logica, the computing services company, reported pre-tax profits 22 per cent
lower at Pounds 3.21m for the first half of 1993 after restructuring charges
of Pounds 2.1m.
Turnover was flat at Pounds 106.5m (Pounds 104.2m).
Earnings per share were 3.3p (3.7p) and the interim dividend is raised by 12
per cent to 1.4p (1.25p). The shares gained 4p to 310p.
The results suggest that Logica is coming to terms with the geographic and
managerial difficulties which have depressed profitability although growth
remains difficult and there are some problem areas.
There was no net growth in the UK and sales in continental Europe slipped 3
per cent. Sales in North America rose 10 per cent; the company made a loss
of Pounds 700,000 there in the first half compared with Pounds 1.4m last
time.
The problem lies with expenditures needed to support and develop a funds
transfer software package. Speedwing Logica, a joint venture with British
Airways, is performing below expectations.
Mr Martin Read, chief executive, said that operating profits of Pounds 5.3m
illustrated the underlying strength of the business.
He believes that the restructuring expenses would be recovered in the second
half and expected to see an improvement in performance.
There have been some 100 redundancies, chiefly in administration, but the
company this year took on 170 graduates. Net cash stands at Pounds 12.7m and
Mr Read said it was likely Logica would be making strategic acquisitions
this year.
</TEXT>
