FT  11 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Applied Distribution valued at Pounds 40.9m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Applied Distribution were priced yesterday at 135p, valuing the
contract distribution group, which was formed five years ago under a Pounds
16.5m management buy-out from Geest, at Pounds 40.9m.
The placing of 17.25m shares, representing 57 per cent of the enlarged
capital, was completed yesterday by NatWest Wood Mackenzie, broker to the
issue. The sponsor is Baring Brothers.
Some 11.35m new shares are being issued, valued at Pounds 15.3m, and the
balance consists of 5.9m shares being sold by existing shareholders.
Part of the Pounds 14.5m net proceeds will be used to repay bank and other
borrowings totalling about Pounds 11m. The rest will be used for working
capital and investment.
Since the buy-out, the group has achieved compound annual growth in turnover
of about 20 per cent and operating profits have grown at a compound average
annual rate of 7 per cent.
Last month the group reported operating profits of Pounds 3.6m (Pounds 3.4m)
on turnover of Pounds 26.4 (Pounds 21.4m) for 1993. Pre-tax profits
increased by 27 per cent to Pounds 2.23m.
Applied Distribution has benefited from the growing trend among UK retailers
and manufacturers to switch from in-house warehousing and distribution
arrangements to third party contracts.
Customers, including J Sainsbury, Somerfield/Gateway and Esso, are served
from five national depots.
Dealings in the new shares are expected to begin on March 17.
