<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Smith &amp; Nephew up at Pounds 171m - Rapidly
changing markets provide more acquisition opportunities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Smith &amp; Nephew, the surgical implants and bandages group, recorded a 10 per
cent increase in 1993 pre-tax profits to Pounds 170.6m, against Pounds
154.6m, despite the impact of healthcare reforms in the US.
Excluding exceptional items and beneficial exchange rate movements profits
rose by 8 per cent. Profits included a net gain of Pounds 7.3m (Pounds
13.3m) on disposals.
Turnover was Pounds 948.7m (Pounds 857.7m) including Pounds 17.5m (Pounds
48.7m) from discontinued items. Underlying sales from continuing operations
rose 7 per cent.
Mr John Robinson, chief executive, said: 'We are very pleased with these
results in a healthcare market that is changing rapidly around the world.'
He added that some of the changes were benefiting Smith &amp; Nephew and were
creating many more acquisition opportunities. The company has brought in
consultants to identify targets which would strengthen its product range or
geographical cover.
The company has not made a significant purchase since the Dollars 236m
(Pounds 162m) acquisition of Ioptex, the US eye lens maker in 1988 and,
helped by a series of disposals, now has a strong balance sheet. Gearing
fell from 12 per cent to 9 per cent over the year with shareholders' funds
rising to Pounds 452m (Pounds 405m).
US sales, 45 per cent of the total, suffered from a slowdown in
non-emergency surgery which hit demand for its artificial hip and knee
joints. Sales of such 'elective' surgery products rose by just 1 per cent.
But other products, including wound management and bone fracture pins,
continued to grow strongly leaving total US sales up 7 per cent.
On the continent strong sales in northern Europe, including the difficult
German market, offset weakness in Spain and France. Sales by its Japanese
subsidiary jumped by more than 50 per cent to Pounds 13m and Mr Robinson
predicted 'growth of 50 per cent or more for the next few years'.
Earnings per share rose only 0.4p to 10.6p, after the tax rate increased
from 29 per cent to 33 per cent. A final dividend of 3.02p is proposed for a
total of 4.91p (4.62p).
COMMENT
For a decade until the mid- 1980s Smith &amp; Nephew turned in annual earnings
growth of 20 per cent. Since 1989 that has sunk to a little more than 2 per
cent. In the depths of the recession such dullness had its appeal, now it
looks, well, dull. Nor will acquisitions necessarily return the sparkle. In
its last large deal in 1988 the company paid Dollars 236m for a business
which is now breaking even on sales of Dollars 30m. Prospects for the core
businesses look healthy enough, particularly in south east Asia, though
sales slowed in the second half. Earnings growth will be blunted by a rising
tax charge again this year but on forecasts of Pounds 175m the multiple is
just 13.5.
Safe, if unexciting.
</TEXT>
