<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Grasping the challenge of a new culture -
Barclays intends to eliminate its defensiveness to outsiders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Surrounded by office furniture that he does not like, in a bank that he says
can sometimes be 'stuffy, pompous and snobbish', the chief executive of
Barclays warms to his theme. 'I think banks have been misreporting profits
for years, and what happened in the late 1980s was grotesquely imprudent.'
Mr Martin Taylor pauses a split second to reflect, before continuing
defiantly with his rapid flow of words. 'You can quote me on that, although
the auditors will probably sue me,' he says, looking pleased at the
prospect. A new broom has arrived with a flourish at the UK's largest bank.
Mr Taylor, who yesterday set out his thoughts at the clearer's results
conferences with the media and analysts, left no doubt that he intends to
eliminate its caution and defensiveness when dealing with outsiders. He even
broke into French when replying to a journalist from a Parisian newspaper.
Harder analysis, and better communication of ideas lie at the heart of Mr
Taylor's salvo. There were few clear answers to the problems he set out, but
he reiterated constantly that the bank had to understand its own policies
better, and then make sure that the outside world understood them as well.
He also has a few brisk thoughts about flaws in the bank's structure. One is
that it has no strong group identity, but is dominated by the high street
bank. 'I think my colleagues from BZW (the investment bank) when they come
for group meetings feel they are coming to the clearing bank,' he says.
The group is not organised simply enough to allow him to 'get closer to'
each business. 'I think at the moment we are very inappropriately organised.
The problem is that what people are supposed to be doing and what they
actually do is not the same thing.'
Changing the culture is a longer-term task, although Mr Taylor insists that
it is his central challenge. 'That is what management is about: changing the
way that people behave over a long period of time. Surgery is not always
needed. You may sometimes just want a properly-balanced diet.'
Barclays has been accused of being less meritocratic than other banks,
because some senior managers are still drawn from the families whose banks
formed it in the last century. Mr Taylor says this is a myth, but that it is
still 'encrusted' with a bureaucratic management structure.
'There are traditions that are already being abandoned, the stuffy, pompous
and snobbish things. The banking side of this business is far too status
conscious for my taste,' he says. But unifying the bank's 'old-fashioned
military' traditions with the more free-wheeling BZW will be a hard task.
Apart from changing its structure, the most concrete idea that Mr Taylor
discussed was Barclays' move towards taking a small general provision
against each loan. He hopes this would encourage managers to price loans
better.
Mr Taylor argues that default provisions would link the pricing of loans
with credit risk. 'There is a habit here I was not aware of before I came
into backing of thinking of the two things with absolutely different parts
of the mind. To me they are two sides of the same coin,' he says.
This ties in with a scepticism about the value of taking on loans to support
the cost base. 'One thing that I have learned from my industrial background
is that marginal business is not always profitable, and sometimes the
marginal business in the book is not just the last 5 per cent,' he says.
Instead of raising new capital to expand lending, Mr Taylor thinks he can
recycle existing capital attached to poor assets. 'I think the bank has a
lot of capital poorly employed, and there is value to be added over the next
10 years by working it more intelligently.'
Mr Taylor says this would be a more precise process than simply shifting
capital among categories of lending such as to large companies. 'If you
actually go through the book and say where are we getting good returns, and
where not, you can make a very considerable value difference' he says.
Indeed, Mr Taylor is preoccupied by the issue of how much capital the bank
should hold - as well as what it should do with it. He emphasised that it
needed to cover its dividend twice over the economic cycle in order to live
on its own resources, and not be driven into rights issues.
The bank has already achieved a target of 6 per cent ratio of core capital
to risk-weighted assets set last year by Mr Andrew Buxton, its chairman. Mr
Taylor says he is re-examining this target. 'Six per cent might well be
right, but if it is right, you have to understand why it is.'
Mr Taylor says he will explain his conclusion carefully to avoid any
misunderstanding. Otherwise, 'They may say 'Ah, they want to have a cushion
because there is some disaster around the corner' or 'Oh, gosh, they are
looking for an adventure and they are building up firepower',' he says.
Part of his challenge is not only to identify the things that are wrong with
Barclays, but the traditions that are valuable. He talks admiringly of the
ability of Marks and Spencer, the UK retailer, to retain the best of its
traditions without becoming bogged down by the past.
'They hang on to the golden thread going back through time that does not
change. I am sure that in banking there are also golden threads running back
through time,' he says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
