<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Franklin Resources dealings today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dealings in the shares of Franklin Resources, the California-based fund
management group, are due to start on the London Stock Exchange today.
Franklin, one of the largest five US investment groups, bought the
London-listed Templeton fund management group in August 1992 for Dollars
786m. Franklin had Dollars 114.2bn (Pounds 78.2bn) of funds under management
at December 31 1993, in 146 funds under the Franklin and Templeton names, as
well as managed accounts. The London listing adds to existing listings on
the New York and Pacific exchanges.
Franklin's speciality is fixed-interest securities, which accounted for
about 84 per cent of its assets at the time of the acquisition, while 80 per
cent of Templeton's assets were in equities. Areas of overlap have been
reduced since the takeover, to allow each side of the group to focus on its
area of expertise.
Mr Charles Johnson, president of Franklin, said that some areas of operation
were still being integrated. Templeton is best known in the UK for its
emerging markets investment trust, but the group also manages a range of
unit trusts. Templeton is currently launching a new Latin American
investment trust, and has appointed Mr Nicholas Brady, the former secretary
to the US Treasury, as chairman of the trust.
As yet there are no Franklin-branded retail investment funds in the UK, as
investors here tend to buy more equity than fixed-interest funds.
</TEXT>
