<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Pentland declines sharply to Pounds 21.6m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lower interest rates hit annual pre-tax profits at the cash-rich Pentland
Group, owner of the Speedo and Berghaus clothing brands, which yesterday
announced a 22 per cent decline to Pounds 28.3m before exceptional items.
After exceptional items, pre-tax profits fell from Pounds 83.6m to Pounds
21.6m. The previous year had been boosted by the Pounds 47.3m gain on the
sale of the group's stake in Adidas, the sports shoe group.
Interest gains fell by Pounds 10m to Pounds 16.1m, resulting from the
decline in interest rates over the past year and a reduction in net cash
balances from Pounds 337.3m to Pounds 185.3m.
The cash decline arose in part from the payment of a special 12p dividend in
April, reflecting the profit from the Adidas sale.
Mr Frank Farrant, finance director, said Pentland was taking its time
finding the right acquisition following its disappointment over Adidas in
1992.
The group pulled out of its agreed Pounds 215m bid in October that year
after preliminary investigations. 'It is easy to acquire something which is
earnings enhancing in the first year,' Mr Farrant said, 'but we have got to
have something with growth potential.'
In the absence of 'the big one', Mr Farrant said, Pentland expected to spend
up to Pounds 75m on smaller acquisitions this year. Some Pounds 60m had been
spent in 1993, including assumed debt.
Acquisitions such as the electrical cablemaker, Woods Wire, and the outdoor
clothing company, Berghaus, helped to fuel the 45 per cent increase in sales
to Pounds 471.8m for the year to December 31. Stripping out purchases, sales
were 13 per cent higher at Pounds 366m. Operating profits in continuing
businesses were 10 per cent lower, however, at Pounds 8.8m.
This was because of heavy losses in the US footwear business and at Pony,
the sports shoe operation.
The group also withdrew from trade finance, which incurred losses of Pounds
2.8m at the operating level. Pentland took an exceptional charge of Pounds
6.7m to wind up the division.
Total operating profits for the group were Pounds 9.2m, including Pounds
3.2m from acquisitions.
The dividend was increased by 12 per cent with a proposed final of 1.64p
making a total of 2.8p. The Pounds 54.3m in dividend pay-outs and a Pounds
58m write off of goodwill on acquisitions, depressed shareholders' funds by
a net Pounds 93m to Pounds 310.1m. Earnings per share fell from 15.79p to
2.74p.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Pentland Group.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3149 Footwear, Ex Rubber, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
