<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Volvo pays the cost of failed merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The cost to Volvo of rupturing plans to merge with France's Renault became
clear yesterday as the Swedish group - the country's biggest manufacturer -
announced a pre-tax loss in 1993 of SKr2.64bn (Pounds 222m), the second
successive year of losses.
The result was a sharp improvement on the 1992 pre-tax deficit of SKr4.8bn.
But the company would have been comfortably back in profit had it not been
for charges totalling SKr5.2bn associated with the unwinding of the
three-year-old strategic alliance with Renault.
This unwinding followed Volvo's decision last December to scrap plans for a
full merger of its car and truck operations with the state-owned French
group.
Volvo was at pains to stress that it had staged a strong recovery at the
operating level in 1993, with unit sales of cars and trucks rising for the
first time in years.
The group surged to an operating profit of SKr1.55bn from a loss in 1992 of
SKr2.25bn, boosted by last year's sharp fall in the value of the Swedish
krona, rationalisation programmes that have eliminated 14,000 jobs in four
years, low product development costs and a change in the accounting of some
tool costs.
However, investors, who have long discounted Volvo's turnround, were
unimpressed by the results and an unchanged dividend of SKr7.75 per share.
Volvo's most-traded B share fell SKr7.00 to close at SKr683.
Mr Soren Gyll, chief executive, said 1994 had started well, although he
declined to comment on prospects for the whole year. He also refused to
comment until a shareholders' meeting in April on what moves the group might
make to seek a new long-term partner in carmaking.
Group sales in 1993 reached SKr111.15bn compared with SKr83bn in 1992, but
were up only 8 per cent adjusted for exchange rate changes. Unit car sales
were 311,800, up from 303,800, thanks mainly to a 9 per cent increase in the
US, Volvo's biggest market. The car group returned to an operating profit of
SKr502m (SKr1.83bn loss).
Unit truck sales rose to 51,300 from 48,100, with the truck group reporting
an operating profit of SKr765m after a loss of SKr641.
</TEXT>
