<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / ABB takes Dollars 596m charge to restructure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Asea Brown Boveri, Europe's largest electrical engineering group, yesterday
announced a 7 per cent rise in pre-tax profits after financial items to
Dollars 1.19bn (Pounds 793m) for 1993, on turnover 4 per cent higher at
Dollars 28.3bn.
The improvement was better than expected, but comes before a net
non-recurring charge of Dollars 596m, mainly for restructuring in the second
half of the year. This left net profits at Dollars 68m, down from Dollars
505m.
Mr Percy Barnevik, president and chief executive, said that after a period
of consolidation, 'the key message to our managers is to go for growth'.
Mr Barnevik said profits in dollar terms reflected a year of turbulence in
currency markets. Expressed in local currencies, profits rose an average 25
per cent, despite a recessionary environment.
Productivity increased by an average 6 per cent and net cash improved by
about Dollars 250m, mainly because of a reduction in stocks. ABB's operating
margin rose from 6.1 per cent to 7.7 per cent. Research and development
spending, at Dollars 2.27bn last year, was some 20-25 per cent higher than
in 1990.
The best performer continued to be power plants, where operating earnings
rose 66 per cent to Dollars 739m.
Profits fell from Dollars 642m to Dollars 520m in power transmission and
distribution because of poor demand while industrial and building systems
lifted profits from Dollars 606m to Dollars 649m. The restructured
transportation division bounced back to profits of Dollars 84m from a
Dollars 40m loss.
</TEXT>
