<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Review of tax departments threatens thousands of jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A sweeping reorganisation of the Treasury's two main tax collecting
departments is being considered by the government in a move which could put
thousands of civil servants' jobs on the line.
Ministers are examining the integration of a number of the functions of the
Inland Revenue and HM Customs &amp; Excise in a bid to cut costs as part of a
wide-ranging review of expenditure. They are also considering any overlap
between the two departments and the Contributions Agency of the Department
of Social Security.
One senior Revenue official said yesterday: 'We don't rule anything in and
we don't rule anything out.' A senior Customs official said: 'Absolutely
anything will be considered.' The exercise - known as the Fundamental
Expenditure Review - is being conducted as part of the government's
long-term spending review co-ordinated by Mr Michael Portillo, chief
Treasury secretary.
Outline details were announced at the time of the Budget last November and
the instructions from ministers to the heads of the Revenue and Customs were
to consider 'radical' proposals.
Interim findings from working groups within the two agencies will be
submitted to ministers over the summer, although any fundamental changes may
take several years to implement.
The examination will include consideration of whether there is needless
duplication in the separate tax investigation roles performed by the
agencies when they are visiting companies.
At Customs, civil servants are examining topics including the way in which
value added tax and excise duties are administered, the operation of its
anti-smuggling activities, and how trade statistics are run.
Opponents of a merger of the central functions of the two departments argue
that it would run contrary to the substantial efforts to decentralise and
delegate power in Customs and the Revenue.
The Treasury wants to show it is not exempt from its own spending
strictures, in order to strengthen its hand in negotiations with other
departments.
</TEXT>
