<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / The Lex Column: Rolls-Royce
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The entire aerospace industry is whistling to keep its spirits up in the
long dark night of recession, so it is hardly surprising that Rolls-Royce is
having a hard time. Rolls' tale of stalled civil engines and military orders
in a tail spin has a grim familiarity about it. There is also a sense of
deja vu about its expectation that spares orders must pick up eventually. At
least the management is now realistically cautioning that civil aircraft are
not about to take off. Rolls has also cut its cost base according to its
business, and there was a commendable improvement in stock turn and lowering
of working capital over the past year.
Still, for all Rolls' self-help, others are cutting just as hard, and
savings may simply be lost to the market in lower prices. Shareholders may
also wonder why the rights issue was needed given that average daily
borrowings were less than Pounds 100m last year. Perhaps a combination of
Trent engine development costs, corrosive restructuring provisions, and the
need to help finance industrial power projects demanded a strengthened
balance sheet. If so, extension of the logic suggests that the company might
do better as part of a much larger whole. Certainly the low returns to
shareholders since flotation argues that there is a need for alternative
methods to finance the needs of such long-term capital intensive industries.
</TEXT>
