<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / The Lex Column: Taylor tinkers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Martin Taylor, Barclays new chief executive, deserves a round of applause
for setting his sights firmly against rights issues. The old tendency to
distribute too much by way of dividends and then go cap in hand to
shareholders when more capital is needed is discredited. The corollary is
that dividend cover must be high enough to permit a decent level of retained
earnings. At first sight Mr Taylor's suggestion that dividends should be at
least twice covered looks pretty tough. Barclays has not managed that since
1988, and its latest dividend is only 1.3 times covered. Look again, though,
and the target may actually be rather lax.
With only minimal effort Barclays should be able to pay large dividend
increases as bad-debt provisions come down. Provisions could fall by half
and still be around 1 per cent of weighted risk assets. But Barclays would
have another Pounds 950m of profits which equates to almost 40p of earnings.
Its 15.15p dividend could then double before the target was breached. The
assumption that Mr Taylor was implicitly promising large dividend increases
helped push the shares higher yesterday.
The worry is whether Barclays would be retaining enough earnings to finance
growth over the longer term. Barclays may think this does not matter while
inflation stays low. It could also improve the mix of its business rather
than expand its balance sheet. That might bring higher operating profits for
a while, but it is a tough challenge when all banks are scrambling for
high-return, low-risk business. Poor prospects for operating revenue have
hurt Lloyds' share price despite its eye-catching returns. It has
underperformed the sector by 40 per cent over the past couple of years.
Barclays must hope that BZW's dynamism will help it escape a similar fate.
</TEXT>
