<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Fimbra chief loses key role in watchdog regime: PIA head to
run admissions process
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Godfrey Jillings, chief executive of Fimbra, the self-regulatory
organisation for independent financial advisers, is no longer to manage the
process of deciding who should be authorised by the new watchdog for retail
financial services.
Instead, Ms Colette Bowe, chief executive of the Personal Investment
Authority, will run the admissions process herself. 'This is the most
important aspect of our work at this time, and I've decided to take personal
charge of it,' Ms Bowe said yesterday.
She made the decision last week, after the first meeting of the group
intended to run the PIA's admissions procedure.
Mr Jillings' role in the process had been seen as reassuring independent
financial advisers, many of whom will be among the new body's smaller
members, that their interests would not be ignored.
Many financial advisers have been among the PIA's critics. Mr Jillings'
removal is likely to fuel the campaign already being run by the National
Federation of Independent Financial Advisers against the impending demise of
Fimbra.
'Godfrey is the hero of the IFAs,' one regulator said yesterday. Mr Jillings
himself was unavailable for comment.
The change in the management of the process comes just three weeks or so
after Mr Jillings' role in the admissions project was announced. Work on
admissions will still be carried out by staff drawn from Fimbra and Lautro,
the self-regulatory organisation for the life insurance industry, but
trained to standards set by the PIA.
The admissions process will be central in setting the tone of the new
regulator, which is intended to bring about a 'step change' in investor
protection.
The PIA has already warned that firms and individuals approved by existing
regulators are not guaranteed acceptance in the new regime.
Both Ms Bowe and Mr Joe Palmer, the PIA chairman, faced deeply sceptical
questioning from MPs about the admissions arrangements, when they gave
evidence to the cross-party treasury committee at the House of Commons last
week.
MPs expressed grave doubts that applications to join the new regulator could
be properly handled, given the likely numbers of candidates and the time
available.
The PIA expects to have about 6,000 potential members. Application forms are
due to be returned by early April.
Lautro imposes record Pounds 225,000 penalty, Page 7
</TEXT>
