FT  11 MAR 94 / Observer: Holed up in the bunkers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Diane Graham, owner of a US engineering company, has caused a minor
explosion in the male-dominated recesses of the US golfing establishment.
She has dared question one of the great traditions of golf clubs -
restricted teeing-off times for lady golfers.
Lawyers have been briefed to fight at least a dozen lawsuits which challenge
a practice common at some exclusive golf clubs. The argument for restricting
the ladies' rights to tee off when they want is based on a belief that women
play more slowly. Off the record, old boy, they also occupy the greens for
too long during the so-called 'power hours' when big business does its
deals.
Diane Graham, of Halbrook Country Club, is not amused. 'If you went out to
the club and saw a sign that said blacks and Jewish people can't play until
2 in the afternoon, people would be outraged.' She obviously hasn't tried
out the bunkers in some of the darker corners of Britain's home counties.
