<PROFILE>_AN-ECKD9ADRFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Leading Article: French disgrace
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The French government has caved in to pressure from Air France's unions. Its
agreement to provide FFr20bn or more in fresh capital for a company which
lost FFr7.5bn last year cannot be understood from a commercial perspective.
A rational private investor would provide such sums only if there was a plan
to stop the financial haemorrhaging fast. The flag-carrier's softly-softly
approach does not constitute such a plan.
The explanation for the hand-out is political. Mr Edouard Balladur is
reaping the bitter rewards for appeasing the unions last November, when they
brought France's airports to a halt in protest at an earlier restructuring
plan. He followed a similar approach in dealing with rioting French
fishermen.
But it is not just French taxpayers who will pay the price of aid to Air
France. The subsidies distort competition in the European Union's newly
liberalised aviation market. The question is whether the European Commission
will also cave in to political pressure and approve the hand-outs.
The Commission's overall intention is clear: it would like to stop state
aid. Brussels is battling against strong political interests at a time when
its authority is weak. Although Britain, the Netherlands and Denmark are
expected to urge it to be tough, other countries which plan to bail out
their own financially stricken airlines could side with France.
Moreover, the Commission may find itself impaled on its own doctrine that
subsidies can be provided on a 'one time, last time' basis. In Air France's
case, this is something of a misnomer. It has already received FFr7.3bn in
four tranches since 1991 and the new hand-outs will be provided in three
tranches. According to some calculations, that makes seven dollops of aid,
not one.
But Brussels may not see it that way. It mistakenly viewed the first set of
tranches as normal financial transactions rather than subsidies and so,
under the doctrine, Air France still has one last chance. It may be that the
French government has decided to make the most of this last chance by
agreeing to such a large capital injection.
While it is probably unrealistic to expect the Commission to block all aid
to Air France, it should reject the current plan. The carrier should be
required to make deeper cuts, if necessary softening the blow with generous
redundancy payments. Some way must also be found to limit the damage to Air
France's rivals, for example by preventing the carrier from dumping
subsidised seats on highly contested routes.
The Commission may not have the stomach for a fight. But a failure to tackle
the issue forcefully would badly undermine its overall state aid policy.
While a hard line would provoke a war of words, in the end Mr Balladur might
thank Brussels. The faster Air France is returned to viability, the sooner
he can press ahead with plans to privatise the carrier.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Air France.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4512 Air Transportation, Scheduled.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    PEOP  Labour.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
