<PROFILE>_AN-ECKD9ADQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Leading Article: The attack on Heathrow
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Irish Republican Army's attack on Heathrow airport was not its bloodiest
since the Anglo-Irish Downing Street declaration in December, but it was
certainly its boldest. Heathrow ranks alongside the City of London, itself
devasted by an IRA bomb last year, as a prime and heavily defended target.
The assault does not prove that the republican movement will never respond
favourably to the carefully crafted words of the declaration, but it appears
to confirm that it is unlikely to do so soon. For the IRA, the war goes on.
The British government thus finds itself under increasing pressure to
abandon the terms of a declaration seen by its opponents as an act of
appeasement calculated only to encourage terrorists to increase the
deadliness of their bargaining tactics.
Mr John Major was wise to rule out any such course of action yesterday. The
declaration may or may not be capable of ending Ulster's troubles one day,
but it has already yielded benefits which should not be lightly set aside.
It has accelerated the convergence of view between London and Dublin that
coercion has no part to play in shaping Ireland's future. It has provided a
basis upon which all but the most extreme of the north's constitutional
parties have felt, at least briefly, able to imagine political progress.
Against this background, it is encouraging that a series of recent opinion
polls north and south of the border has shown a large majority in favour of
a settlement based upon the Downing Street principles.
The unpleasant truth facing Mr Major and Mr Albert Reynolds, his Irish
counterpart, is that in spite of these advances, peace may not be in sight.
The IRA's political position is weaker than it was in December, but it is by
no means defeated.
A future thus offers itself of yet more agonisingly slow progress,
punctuated by atrocities which create a sense of reeling backwards. The
agenda for progress should include further efforts, in consultation with the
province's constitutional parties, to devolve government functions from
Westminster to Belfast. A more harmonious political relationship between
London and Dublin should also yield more effective security co-operation
between north and south.
The agenda also needs to involve deepening the political consensus about
Ulster's future at Westminster. The only false political step made by the
government this week has been its handling of an approach from the
leadership of the Labour party to try to forge agreement upon the future of
the Prevention of Terrorism Act. The party political crowing of Mr Michael
Howard, the home secretary, during the debate on this act, which was itself
interrupted by the news from Heathrow, lacked statesmanship.
The political tide is moving, however slowly, against the IRA. This is not a
time either for cheap shots, or for lurches in approach.
</TEXT>
