<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Arts: The Maid of Orleans - Opera
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN ALLISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The enterprising Royal Northern College of Music in Manchester launched its
spring opera season on Tuesday with a Tchaikovsky rarity, The Maid of
Orleans.
It is a brave project, boldly realised, with no expense spared. Since the
strange decision was made to give the opera in Russian, even surtitles were
specially provided. There could have been no question of borrowing them: no
Western company has ventured the opera in recent years.
At present, Tchaikovsky's historical drama survives only in the Bolshoy's
repertory - ironic, since in writing it, the composer was making a conscious
bid for popularity. His attempt to copy the conventions of French grand
opera won acclaim at the St Petersburg premiere in 1881, but the
assassination shortly afterwards of Alexander II led to the curtailment of
the theatre season, and The Maid of Orleans was not revived again in Russia
during Tchaikovsky's lifetime.
Its neglect is not hard to fathom. But even if, as many believe, The Maid is
Tchaikovsky's dullest opera, this performance showed it to be more than a
mere curiosity, and worthy of the occasional revival. The music is not
vintage Tchaikovsky - some episodes bear his distinctive stamp, but too
often he falls back on overblown gesture - yet the real weaknesses are
dramatic: the opera's chief source, Schiller's tragedy, is diluted by
interpolations and the simplified, sentimentalised treatment of Jeanne d'Arc
herself.
The production by Stefan Janski, the RNCM's director of opera studies, is
solid and straightforward, probably the best way of tackling such a
sprawling piece. Most of the public scenes are splendid, and only the royal
entertainments in Act Two seemed tedious (and the anachronistic acrobats
tasteless). Charles Cusick Smith's versatile sets allow for Jeanne's
striking angelic visions, and colourful costumes complete the spectacle.
In Russia, The Maid of Orleans is reserved as a vehicle for star mezzos, and
without Jane Irwin's vocal strengths, the RNCM could not have contemplated
staging it. Her performance in the taxing title role was as affecting as the
superficial characterisation allows; her rich, lustrous tone which extends
to a powerful top makes her a mezzo to watch.
With the exception of the tenor roles, the opera was strongly cast, and
three other singers stood out: Martin Snell (Thibault), Ashley Holland
(Dunois), and the Ukrainian soprano Nataliya Kompaniyets (Agnes), who
brought Slavonic authenticity to Tchaikovsky's music.
Paul McGrath welded his vast forces - large orchestra, off-stage band,
organ, and an excellent chorus - with flair.
Sponsor: The Royal Bank of Scotland. Further performances: March 12,16,22,
and 25 (061-273 4504).
</TEXT>
<XX>
