<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Arts: Not quite cricket - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MALCOLM RUTHERFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sometimes a note of translation may be in order. The word 'yaar', as in
Wicked Yaar, Garry Lyons's sprightly new play at the Cottesloe, is roughly
the Punjabi equivalent of the English 'mate', as in 'matey' rather than
'mating'. It is thus a term of affection. 'Wicked' in modern English is a
term of approbation.
The play is about the difficulty of bringing English and Asians together.
Wicked Yaar is a mix of Asian fairy tale, Yorkshire comedy and racial
prejudice. There is also an injection of cricket, on the assumption that
this is the game that brings all good people together. On the whole, the
cricket comes out on top.
Malik Mir, played by Ravik Aujla like an aspiring Pakistani all-rounder,
wants to be the first Asian to be picked by his county. The trouble is that
the local English youth are more interested in being bovver boys (and girls)
for Leeds United. They declare the short cut to the cricket ground a no-go
area for blacks and attempt to intimidate Malik.
Then the spirits come to the rescue. Malik finds a medallion which, when
rubbed, brings a genie to his side who sees off the thugs, helps the family
finances by cheating the inland revenue through computer hacking, and
improves the cricket. The reason why Malik scores a match-winning 20 off
three balls in the final of the schools trophy is that he has hit the third
for only two, but the invisible genie flings it on for six overthrows.
Directed by John Turner, the cricket scenes are very engagingly done. Even
here there is a twist in the plot. The captain of the rival team is a smart
white girl who knows that, however good she is, she can never play for the
county 'because it's a man's club'. Malik consoles her with the line that at
least England win at the women's game. A decent Asian boy and a decent
English girl unite in their dislike of bigotry: fairy tale stuff all round.
There are other pleasures. The amiable genie, or ghul, takes to chewing gum
as if it were nectar and regards the local ASDA supermarket as a veritable
palace of delights. There is a lot of rap, especially in the cricket
commentary, and some prolonged bhangra dancing. The design by Nigel
Prabhavalkar is excellent.
Whether it all hangs together is probably a subjective judgment. The piece
runs out of ideas towards the end: it struck me as feeble to conclude that
it was all a dream, and while there may be a case for reverse
discrimination, the treatment of white working class youth in Wicked Yaar
carries it beyond the plausible. Can it really be that all poor inner-city
whites are so awful and all Asian immigrants so virtuous? Perhaps a little
too much preaching.
In repertory, Cottesloe Theatre, (071) 928 2252, then touring.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
