<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Arts: Crisis in the Commonwealth - The Institute, cultural
showcase for the nations of the former British Empire, seems set to go the
way of the Empire itself
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Monday is Commonwealth Day but at the concrete pavilion of the Commonwealth
Institute in Kensington, celebrations will be muted. Commonwealth
secretary-general, Chief Emeka Anyaoku, will host a reception for a host of
sporting celebrities, but their hearts will not be in it.
For the Institute, set up in 1958 as the cultural showcase for the nations
of the former British Empire, seems set to go the way of the Empire itself.
The arts and educational centre, which houses 12,000 artifacts from more
than 50 nations, is to lose its entire Pounds 2.7 million subsidy from the
Foreign and Commonwealth Office.
'The news came nine days after our development report was published, which
we were feeling very pleased with, so the effect was devastating,' says
Stephen Cox, director-general of the Institute. 'It's been a very miserable
time.'
Cox has prepared an 11th-hour proposal for the venue's survival and made
half his staff of 90 redundant, including his deputy, in an attempt to wring
a reprieve from the foreign secretary, Douglas Hurd. If the FCO comes up
with Pounds 1m a year, says Cox, he will earn the rest: 'We have got, and
are developing very rapidly, a good conference and events centre here which
is beginning to make money in quite substantial amounts'.
The Institute has always had its detractors, who question the value of wood
carvings and masks of dubious historic or aesthetic interest or permanent
exhibits depicting New Zealand cheesemaking. 'The building itself is
unforgiveably ugly and inside, it is designed to confuse,' says the art
critic Brian Sewell. 'The temporary exhibitions have been unmitigated drivel
for the last 20 years. The work is often by really wretched people who
wouldn't have even got into art school in this country. The artifacts are
just tourist trade rubbish. It is a slave of and monument to political
correctitude.'
Supporters, however, point to the record of the institute's main gallery,
which has housed exhibitions by significant artists including the Guyanese
painter, the late Aubrey Williams, and to a series of much-praised readings
by Caribbean poets. Last year, more than 50,000 British schoolchildren
visited and Cox asserts that behind the music, dance, paintings and tableaux
of 'life in many lands' the Institute has a serious role: 'Britain is a
multi-cultural society and the context and reason for that is predominantly
a Commonwealth one. If we fail to ensure that context is maintained so that
people understand it, then I think we are left with the problems of the East
End of London and the British National Party washing over us. The
Commonwealth is essentially an organisation working towards eliminating
racial prejudice.'
He is seeking private sector partners for a Pounds 5m proposal to transform
the interior of the building to become a tourism draw with an underlying
ecological message. On the ground level would go World of Wonders, a
dramatic virtual reality presentation of natural phenomena like tropical
storms, volcanic eruptions and Arctic chill; on the second level would be a
computer-driven information complex on the 50 Commonwealth states; and on
the third a temporary exhibition area.
Under-funding over the years means the listed building - designed by the
architects of the Royal Festival Hall - has been badly neglected and Cox
acknowledges that a rethink of the displays is long overdue. 'One thing I've
never doubted is that the Commonwealth and the Institute have an important
job to do.' Generally, he says, 'we have attracted very little criticism
though we're working in some sensitive areas - the projection of
international understanding, of Commonwealth values, the development of the
multi-cultural society in Britain. These areas can become very difficult.'
But surely, with ex-dominions like Canada and Australia now globally equal
with Britain, and at least one of them going briskly towards renouncing the
monarchy, the association of these former Empire states is an anachronism.
Not to Cox. 'The Commonwealth is the only multilateral organisation,other
than the UN, covering a quarter of the world's land surface and a quarter of
the world's population. It's the only other organisation which combines rich
and poor, developed and developing, the Pacific, Atlantic and Indian
Oceans.'
Australia may be going republican, but it is pro-Commonwealth; Hong Kong may
leave, but South Africa would like to rejoin. And London is the headquarters
of the Commonwealth, with the Institute its vital cultural showcase.
Brian Sewell, however, remains unconvinced. 'It has been the most fatuous
exercise since it began. And as the Commonwealth nations are pulling away,
what is the point of keeping the Commonwealth Institute open?'
</TEXT>
