<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Starting remarkably early at 6.30 (though admittedly it goes on until 10.30)
Radio 3 relays a live concert performance of Lulu, from the Royal Festival
Hall, London. This last opera of Berg's was unfinished at his death and
completed by Friedrich Cerha. Lulu is a femme fatale who eventually comes to
London as a prostitute and is killed by Jack The Ripper. Andrew Davis
conducts the BBC Symphony Orchestra, Patricia Wise is Lulu, and Wolfgang
Schone plays the two roles of Doctor Schon and Jack The Ripper.
BBC2 mounts a 50-minute documentary which agonises over the way that people
have traditionally told jokes about mothers-in-law. Should we expect
companion prog rammes about Irishmen, Newfoundlanders, and golfers? Take My
Mother-In-Law starts at 9.30.
Three old movies start at around midnight, the best being Elia Kazan's 1951
version of the Tennessee Williams play, A Streetcar Named Desire. Marlon
Brando gives his famous 'method' performance as the boorish Stanley who
rapes his sister-in-law (12.15 BBC2).
</TEXT>
