FT  11 MAR 94 / Technology (Worth Watching): Notebooks for number-crunchers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Notebook computers have rapidly become part of the accoutrements of business
travel, writes Louise Kehoe. Yet for users involved in heavy-duty number
crunching, the standard notebook PC is inadequate. Two offerings may provide
solutions.
IBM has introduced a portable version of the Unix workstation. The N40 is
based on the PowerPC microprocessor jointly developed by IBM, Apple Computer
and Motorola. Priced at Dollars 12,000, the N40 incorporates an active
matrix colour display.
Taking a different tack, Compaq Computer has introduced a family of
notebooks based on Intel's latest 486 DX2 and DX4 microprocessors. Compaq
has eliminated the cumbersome AC adapter and cables by building the adapter
into the computer, which still weighs less than 7lb. Prices range from
Dollars 3,300 to Dollars 6,500. Compaq: US, 713 370 0670. IBM: US, 914 945
3884.
