<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Sizewell computer queried
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Scientists advising local authorities over the safety of the proposed
Sizewell C nuclear power station in Suffolk are not convinced of the
reliability of an important computer system.
The prototype system is designed to monitor all reactor functions and give
early warning of any fault.
The scientists, led by Professor Tony Goddard of Imperial College, London,
are recommending that an assurance is obtained from the Nuclear
Installations Inspectorate that the system will not be approved until
reliability tests are validated.
The system, developed by Westinghouse of the US, is already being installed
in Sizewell B, Britain's first pressurised water reactor nuclear power
station, although the inspectorate has yet to give it final clearance.
Inspectors have indicated that they may be able to issue a licence within
the next few months.
However, they are still awaiting further submissions from Nuclear Electric,
the state-owned generator which is building the Pounds 2.03bn B station. and
wants to proceed with a Pounds 3.5bn twin-reactor C plant.
Members of the British Computer Society have previously expressed concern
about the complexity of the computer system.
Prof Goddard's team is also recommending that local councils seek
clarification from Nuclear Electric on the amount of spent uranium fuel to
be stored at Sizewell.
</TEXT>
