<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Insurers to crack down on bad debts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Insurers are to assess the creditworthiness of their customers in a move to
tackle a growing problem of bad debts.
About a dozen companies are supporting the development of a credit database
which will be used to assess the ability of an individual or commercial
buyer to maintain instalment payments on policies.
As many as one-in-five customers pays for insurance by monthly or quarterly
instalments and bad debts have risen, partly as a result of steep increases
in premiums. It is also believed that some of these defaults involve fraud.
Default rates on instalment policies are running at nearly double the rate
for other forms of credit offered by banks and building societies which
already use credit information groups.
'The problem is all too apparent,' said Mr George Stratford, chief
accountant at Cornhill Insurance. 'The high payout on claims . . . has long
been exacerbated by a high level of late payments on personal policies.'
Cornhill, which has used credit information for the past six years and is
one of the companies which launched the initiative, noticed a trend 2 1/2
years ago for motor policyholders to pay their initial instalment and then
default, said Mr Stratford. 'With a large proportion of personal lines (home
and motor) business moving from insurer to insurer in search of best rates,
discussions with fellow insurance companies revealed that we were not alone
with this problem,' he said.
Infolink, part of the UK's largest independent credit information
organisation, is providing technical services for the scheme.
Mr Kevin Still, head of insurance services at Infolink, said: 'There is also
an element of fraudulent activity whereby individuals obtain cover and pay
the initial payment, but have no intention to maintain their repayments.'
</TEXT>
