<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / 700,000 school places face axe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Patten yesterday stepped into a fierce row over the extent of excess
capacity in schools by saying that up to 700,000 surplus places could be
eliminated 'very quickly' at a saving of more than Pounds 200m.
The education secretary's claim - which comes as local elections loom - was
dismissed by the Labour-controlled Association of Metropolitan Authorities.
Mr Patten's figures were meaningless, it said, and seven councils that had
presented the Department for Education with plans to rationalise and remove
surplus places had been thwarted by delays in decisions.
Mr Graham Lane, the AMA's education spokesman, said Mr Patten had 'made a
lot of noise about the need to remove surplus places', but added: 'The
evidence shows that our members are doing their best whilst his own
department is dragging its feet.'
Mr Patten said that from next month, when the new Funding Agency for Schools
starts to operate, he would urge local authorities in England and Wales to
'squeeze surplus school places out of the system'. Any that failed to
respond would find the job done for them by the new agency. Questioned at a
Westminster press conference, Mr Patten said money being spent on 'roofs for
half-used buildings' should be earmarked instead for teachers, the national
curriculum and for books.
The government's aim was to 'concentrate management and teaching effort on
the children, not on the buildings'. He said that 'an awful lot of places'
could be removed by withdrawing parts of buildings from use.
But Mr Patten offered no assurance that the money saved would remain in the
education service and would not be clawed back by the Treasury. His remarks
prompted a call from Labour for surplus places to be used to 'make a start
on providing universal nursery education'.
Mrs Ann Taylor, shadow education secretary, said: 'Taking powers to produce
a hit-list of schools which are to face closure is not the most productive
way forward.'
The Audit Commission, which monitors local government spending, said it was
concerned by surplus places, but could not provide an authoritative figure.
It told councils to consider amalgamating schools' sixth forms into
sixth-form colleges.
However, Mr Patten is now encouraging schools that teach pupils aged 11 to
16 to open their own sixth forms.
</TEXT>
