<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Legal aid curb may hit privacy cases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Cases brought under the government's proposed law on privacy may be made
ineligible for legal aid. The law would create criminal offences covering
electronic eavesdropping and long-range photography on private property.
Ministers are considering the curb on aid as part of a renewed onslaught
against the legal aid budget, which is set to climb to Pounds 1.4bn in
1994-95 in spite of steps last year to restrict eligibility.
Mr Michael Portillo, chief Treasury secretary, is questioning the extent of
legal aid provision in several areas as part of the review of spending by
the Lord Chancellor's Department.
Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, said earlier this year that the government
was proposing to withdraw legal-aid funding for cases which could be
resolved without going to court.
Some ministers are worried that too heavy-handed a clampdown will increase
pressure for a contingency-fee system for lawyers (no win, no fee) to
safeguard access to the courts for the less well-off. They are concerned
that this might lead to an increase in legal actions.
