<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Lautro fines life insurer record Pounds 225,000
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A record Pounds 225,000 fine has been imposed by Lautro, the self-regulating
organisation for the life insurance industry, on Aegon life assurance for
serious structural failures in its compliance procedures.
The penalty is the first to be levied as a result of the second round of
routine inspection visits carried out by the regulator.
It reflects Lautro's statement last week that there could be 'little excuse'
for companies which still had seriously inadequate compliance procedures in
spite of the extensive amounts of regulatory guidance that had been issued.
The regulatory offences, admitted by Aegon, occurred between May 1990 and
March 1993 and related to weaknesses in the internal control systems.
As a result of the rule breaches, Aegon has had to review 2,000 files using
standards set by an independent firm of accountants and pay some Pounds
10,000 compensation to 65 investors.
The payments relate to complaints against the company which it had already
admitted but where Lautro believed it had undercompensated customers.
Five specific shortcomings listed by Lautro included failures in vetting
procedures for appointing some company representatives and 'tied' agents, in
checking selling practices, in properly investigating the high levels of
policies sold by some sales agents being surrendered early, and in dealing
with complaints promptly and properly.
Lautro also said that the compliance department had inadequate resources.
Mr Peter Baines, Aegon chief executive, said that since the second
inspection visit the company had increased its compliance department from
six to 11 staff and had appointed a new head of compliance.
He said that during 1991 and 1992 the company had expanded rapidly, and
admitted that he and colleagues had failed to keep up with the changes in
regulatory standards that Lautro was introducing.
Although the fine is a new record - about Pounds 45,000 higher than that
recently imposed on Legal &amp; General for widespread and systemic weaknesses
in compliance - it is likely to be superseded shortly as other cases from
the second round of inspection visits are determined.
Mr Baines estimated that beyond the fine itself the disciplinary action had
cost Aegon almost Pounds 500,000, taking account of its payment of Lautro's
costs of Pounds 20,000 as well as the cost of engaging outside advisers and
making systems changes. He expressed confidence that all the necessary
compensation payments had been made.
</TEXT>
