<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Little change due on law for women
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David Hunt, employment secretary, last night accepted that some changes
should be made to the Sex Discrimination Act to improve employment
opportunities for women. However he ruled out wholesale recasting of its
provisions.
While promising to have further discussions with the Equal Opportunities
Commission, he told the Commons: 'I do not think we should substantially
reshape the legislation.'
Mr Hunt rejected Labour charges that over the last 15 years the government
had exploited the increase in male unemployment by encouraging the use of
part-time women workers to drive down wage levels.
He said women often wanted to combine work with family commitments, and had
benefited greatly from the creation of more than 2m part-time jobs over the
past 10 years.
Ms Clare Short, who speaks for Labour on women's issues, said the
overwhelming majority of women were in low-paid jobs with little opportunity
for promotion, and no pension entitlement.
She said the expansion in the number of part-time women workers had followed
the destruction of more and more full-time jobs for men, and had resulted in
the 'dragging down of standards' for everyone.
Ms Short added: 'Women do not want rotten wages, no training and no pensions
 -that is why full-time rights for part-time workers are crucial'.
She called for urgent action to implement the recent House of Lords'
judgment that the UK's laws on part-time workers' rights over redundancy pay
and unfair dismissal were in breach of European law.
Ms Short said Labour's commitment to introduce a minimum wage would 'pay for
itself' through the increase in the income tax yield and the savings in the
social security budget resulting from reduced payments of family credit.
Mr Hunt condemned discrimination against women as 'not only inefficient but
clearly wrong' and maintained that there was great scope for a bi-partisan
policy.
He stressed that only 13 per cent of women with part-time jobs would prefer
to work full time.
</TEXT>
