<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Mexican bank chief is named
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Miguel Mancera is to be governor of Mexico's newly independent central
bank. Head of the existing non-independent central bank for the past 11
years, he had been favourite to take the post.
The Bank of Mexico, which becomes formally independent from April, will have
broad powers to set monetary policy, and will be prohibited from providing
credit rates to the government below market levels.
However, the finance ministry will have overall responsibility for exchange
rate policy.
Mr Mancera, an economist with a doctorate from Yale, will serve for three
years and nine months. He is widely respected in Mexico and abroad, and is
known for his aversion to inflation, commitment to pro-market economic
policy, and support of a stable currency.
However, some Mexican banks have criticised him for his cautious attitude to
financial liberalisation, in particular his opposition to rapid development
of a futures and options market in Mexico.
Four other economists appointed to the board of governors are all known for
their technical expertise and political independence. They are: Mr Guillermo
Prieto, Mr Ariel Buira, Mr Jesus Yacamen, and Mr Francisco Gil Diaz.
</TEXT>
