<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Clinton officials give Whitewater evidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Three White House officials yesterday gave evidence in secret to a federal
grand jury investigating the Whitewater affair. A stack of documents were
also turned over to the same panel, convened by Mr Robert Fiske, the
independent counsel probing Whitewater.
First to be called was Ms Margaret Williams, chief of staff to Mrs Hillary
Rodham Clinton, who said afterwards she was encouraged to be involved in a
process 'where the finding of fact is important, as opposed to innuendo and
rumour-mongering and gossip and sensationalism.'
She was followed by Ms Lisa Caputo, the first lady's press secretary, and Mr
Mark Gearan, White House director of communications. All are said to have
attended meetings with regulatory officials investigating Madison Guaranty,
the failed savings and loan institution at the centre of the Whitewater
affair, involving Mr and Mrs Clinton's 1980s financial dealings in Arkansas.
Seven more senior White House and Treasury officials have secured
postponement of testimony, most until next week. But one of them, Mr Roger
Altman, deputy Treasury secretary, confessed to the Wall Street Journal
yesterday to 'a piece of awful judgment' in arranging a meeting on February
2 with the White House to discuss the status of the Madison inquiry.
He was then acting head of the Resolution Trust Corporation, the agency
formed to clean up the nationwide savings and loan debacle of the 1980s. He
said he never told President or Mrs Clinton, or Mr Lloyd Bentsen, the
Treasury secretary, in advance about his initiative, and insisted the
session was purely informational.
Senator Bob Dole, the Republican leader, again alleging tampering with
official inquiries, said Mr Altman should resign, as should Mr Webster
Hubbell, associate attorney general and formerly a partner in Mrs Clinton's
Little Rock law firm.
The White House said resignation was not on the cards, but Mr Altman's star
in Washington has been much dimmed.
Also, 82 Republican congressmen yesterday demanded an investigation into an
old story: Mrs Clinton's participation in an investment partnership accused
of profiting by short-selling drugs stocks last year when she was attacking
pharmaceutical companies for overcharging.
Both Mr and Mrs Clinton sought to give the impression of business as usual
yesterday, the president speaking in New York and the first lady attending a
healthcare meeting on Capitol Hill. The threat of early congressional
hearings on Whitewater, which Mr Fiske said could interfere with his
inquiries, appeared to recede. Senator William Cohen, Maine Republican,
doubted they could be held before June.
The president could also take some encouragement from two polls published
yesterday which showed that, notwith standing a torrent of critical and now
nationwide media coverage, the public is still unpersuaded of the
seriousness of Whitewater.
</TEXT>
