<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / World Trade News: EU rejects US allegations of hypocrisy
over US-Japan trade dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission yesterday rejected US allegations of hypocrisy over
the US-Japan trade dispute, and denied it had erected barriers against US
products, writes Gillian Tett in Brussels. It said although the EU did not
endorse US strong-arm tactics in the trade row, it was 'just as concerned'
about the deficits the EU and US had with Japan.
The commission was responding to an attack on Wednesday night, by Mr Micky
Kantor, US trade representative, who accused Europe of standing on the
sidelines in the US-Japan dispute while continuing to impose barriers
against some US goods.
Sir Leon Brittan, EU trade commissioner, accepted that some problems
remained between the EU and US over trade barriers, but insisted progress
was being made to remove them. 'The EU also has a very long list of US trade
barriers, some of which have been in existence for decades,' said Sir Leon.
Examples included US tax rules on certain cars and regulations which
stipulated levels of American tobacco in cigarettes, a spokesman added.
</TEXT>
