<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / World Trade News: Hungary confirms lead in freeing up
telecoms - Nicholas Denton reports on the award of local network concessions
to foreign-led partnerships
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hungary, in awarding concessions to foreign-led consortia to run local
telecoms networks in 15 out of the country's 54 districts, has confirmed its
innovative policy in telecommunications. Budapest privatised its national
operator and adopted digital mobile networks before most east European
countries.
In December it sold 30 per cent of Matav, the national telecommunications
company, to Deutsche Telecom of Germany and Ameritech of the US for Dollars
875m in eastern Europe's largest privatisation. The local tender further
dilutes state control over the telecoms sector.
The government granted concessions in four districts to UTS, a partnership
of French telecoms equipment manufacturer Alcatel and US Telecom East, a
group of US local telecommunications companies. UTS plans to invest Dollars
275m over a decade to build up the number of lines in its regions by the
government requirement of 15.5 per cent a year.
Two local areas centered on Szeged, Hungary's second-largest city, go to
Compagnie Generale des Eaux, the diversified French public utilities group.
Other foreign-led consortia have won in another nine regions, with the
remaining 39 staying with Matav, the national operator.
The authorities have indicated that they are prepared to grant licences for
local telephone companies to operate cable television in parallel. Hungary
would be the first country after the UK where the regulators have relaxed
the barrier between the two, increasingly converging, businesses.
Budapest's is a policy of letting 'a hundred flowers bloom', says Mr Henri
Piganeau, Hungarian project director for CGE.
However, the entry of independents will do little in the short-run for
competition. The concessions give the winners exclusive local rights for
eight years and do not impinge on Matav's monopoly of trunk and
international traffic. Independent operators will take over less than 20 per
cent of existing lines, with the majority remaining with Matav.
Rivalry with cable television providers will be muted. The
telecommunications ministry said that it would grant dual service licences
on a case-by-case basis and would take into account the interests of
existing cable operators.
Nevertheless, CGE for one plans to run fibre-optic cable as close as
possible to houses in the expectation of a permit to offer television. The
company estimates that cable television services have the potential to add a
fifth to the value of the business.
When the local monopolies expire, CGE's Mr Piganeau forecasts, strong local
operators will begin to raid border areas of neighbouring regions. 'It
provides the seeds of future competition,' he says.
In the meantime, the independents should be able to lead Matav by example,
according to Mr Piganeau. Their performance will provide a benchmark by
which to measure the national operator's performance.
On balance, analysts say Hungary's liberalisation has probably gone as far
as it could without undermining Matav or making the environment so risky as
to deter new entrants into the market.
'Hungary is really leading the way on this one,' says Mr James Roberson of
United Telecom Services.
Hungary is an unlikely telecommunications pioneer. The telephone network,
with just 7 lines per 100 inhabitants, was the most sparse in the Soviet
bloc even though its communist neighbours hardly set exacting standards.
But in some races there are advantages to coming from behind: in the drive
to develop modern telecommunications, eastern Europe - and particularly
Hungary - is demonstrating that backwardness has its compensations.
The growing strain on state finances, far from limiting development, has
pushed Budapest to liberalise and attract private finance. The auction of
local concessions raised a useful Ft8.2bn (Pounds 54m) for the government
and attracted commitments from foreign consortia to invest Ft20bn in the
first three years.
Low line-density, still only 15 per 100 compared with a west European
average of 43, provided the political impetus to invite in independent local
operators. Long waiting lists for phones have made Matav one of Hungary's
most unpopular companies and fuelled demands by many communities for more
responsive local operators.
Local authorities criticise Matav for putting the trunk network and
businesses above provision of new lines for ordinary households. 'That's
what happens when you have King Kong calling all the shots,' says Mr
Roberson.
The inadequacy of communist telecommunications regulation freed regulators
to tear up past laws and fashion the 1993 telecoms act around modern
technology and the new possibilities of competition.
All in all, Hungary has offered a classic example of what telecoms analysts
call the 'leapfrog' - the ability of countries with backward networks to
jump over a whole stage of telecoms development. Hungary's neighbours, which
start even further back, have a similar opportunity.
The independents certainly hope so. UTS says it is looking at other east
European countries and CGE believes its operations in south-eastern Hungary
could provide a springboard for expansion into neighbouring Romania and even
Serbia.
</TEXT>
