<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / US warns Japan on surplus: 'Great nations keep their
commitments,' says Christopher
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan was warned yesterday to live up to its commitment to reduce its
current account surplus significantly or risk losing international
credibility.
'Great nations keep their commitments,' Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary
of state, said in Tokyo. The US had kept its part of the bargain, made in
bilateral framework negotiations, to take steps to reduce its deficit. Japan
had voluntarily agreed to lower its surplus, but 'no one would agree with
the contention that Japan has met its commitment,' Mr Christopher said.
While in other respects, the US's single most important bilateral
relationship was healthy, it continued to be troubled by the trade
situation. 'Compliance with the framework agreement should be the basis for
going forward,' Mr Christopher said.
Although there were no breakthroughs in his talks yesterday with Mr Morihiro
Hosokawa and Mr Tsutomu Hata, Japan's prime and foreign ministers, Mr
Christopher said he had sensed a greater recognition that the status quo was
unsatisfactory to the US.
Japanese officials had assured him that Japan would draw up by the end of
the month steps to fulfil its framework agreements.
Mr Christopher further defended the US government's decision to revive the
Super 301 provision in the 1988 US trade act giving it the right to
retaliate against unfair trade practices.
The US decision has come under attack from several quarters, including the
European Union, as going against the trend of 'multilateralising' trade
issues.
Yesterday Mr Gerard Longuet, French trade and industry minister, joined
growing international criticism of Washington's decision to revive Super 301
saying as an 'unjustified attack' on Japan.
Super 301 was a tool to open Japan's markets not only to the US, but to all
countries, Mr Christopher said. Neither the US nor Japan wanted a trade war
and Super 301 was useful in encouraging the parties to have the kind of
dialogue that rendered retaliation unnecessary.
Mr Christopher said that while other countries might not agree with the
measures employed by the US in opening up Japan's markets, 'the world looks
to the US for leadership' and 'will be very glad to reap the benefits of
what the US is doing. Whatever their position,' he said, 'the rest of the
world will applaud if we can achieve those results.'
