<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Brazil cuts import duties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRASLIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Brazil has cut import duties on a wide range of household products following
criticism that the government's economic restructuring programme has led to
big price rises. Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso, finance minister, said lower
tariffs would curtail price rises because imports could now compete with
locally-made goods.
Inflation is thought to have risen this month as companies raise prices
following introduction of a new accounting unit, the unit of real value
(URV), designed to form the basis of a new currency. Companies also feared a
government price freeze as in previous restructuring attempts.
The media has highlighted examples of prices doubling, adding to political
pressure on Mr Cardoso to act and avert calls for stronger measures, such as
the government setting key prices.
Products targeted in the duty changes include toiletries, paint and
medicines. They are almost all made by companies with near-monopoly or
oligopoly control over the local market. Import duties on such goods are cut
from 20 per cent to 2 per cent.
Meanwhile, Brazil is increasingly optimistic it has persuaded the IMF to
grant a standby accord as part of the country's Dollars 52bn (Pounds 35bn)
private bank debt rescheduling plan.
IMF approval is a prerequisite for the US treasury to issue zero coupon
bonds as guarantees for part of the rescheduling. Mr Cardoso is likely to
visit Washington for talks with Mr Michael Camdessus, chairman of the IMF,
in time for the Fund to issue a letter of intent next week.
Brazil's congress has approved, in the first of two scheduled votes, the
reduction of the president's term of office from five to four years.
The new rule will apply to the country's next president, due to take office
next year following elections in October.
</TEXT>
