<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Kazakh president's allies 'win big majority'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE LEVINE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ALMA ATA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Kazakh government yesterday released figures showing that allies of the
president, Mr Nursultan Nazarbayev, won a large majority in Monday's
parliamentary elections, and denied western claims the polls were unfair.
Diplomats said Mr Nazarbayev controlled at least two-thirds of the new
177-member parliament and his opponents probably had fewer than 30 seats, or
less than 15 per cent. The results raised new concerns about ethnic tension,
as Kazakh candidates won 56 per cent of the seats, against 27 per cent for
ethnic Russians.
The Kazakhs comprise 43 per cent of the republic's population and the
Russians 36 per cent. 'It looks like Nazarbayev got a landslide,' one
diplomat said.
The elections have been condemned as unfair by observers from the Council on
Security and Co-operation in Europe. The delegation said the polls favoured
supporters of Mr Nazarbayev by, among other factors, an apparent systematic
effort to disqualify independent candidates. The elections were Kazakhstan's
first since it gained independence in the Soviet break-up two years ago.
The election results showed allies of Mr Nazarbayev belonging to political
parties will comprise a 95-seat bloc of parliament, or 53 per cent. His
supporters are also believed to make up a majority of the 60 successful
candidates who ran with no party affiliation.
Kazakhstan's foreign minister, Mr Tuligen Suleymenov, said the CSCE
delegation had been 'ill-informed'. Mr Karatay Turisov, the republic's
electoral commission chairman, released a point-by-point denial of their
conclusions.
'It would be naive to believe we have the same democratic principles as
western countries,' he said. 'It's impossible to change the psychology of
people in a two-month campaign after 70 years of communism.'
</TEXT>
