<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Li urges economic consolidation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIJING
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Premier Li Peng yesterday told China's annual parliamentary session that
political stability and further consolidating economic reforms were the main
priorities in the year ahead.
Mr Li's 'state of the republic' address placed heavy emphasis on combating
inflation, reducing unsustainable rates of economic growth and ensuring
public order in the face of a widening income gap between country and city.
'Economic development is the centre of all our work,' Mr Li told some 2,800
delegates to the National People's Congress which convenes once a year.
'Social stability, in turn, is an indispensable prerequisite for economic
development and smooth progress in reform.'
Mr Li's remarks reflect the leadership's increasing concern about an erosion
of the central government's authority and widespread disillusionment with
Communist rule.
'In some areas public order is poor, and not enough has been done to combat
social evils,' Mr Li added.
'The corrupt practices of a few government functionaries . . . have impaired
the close ties between the government and people.'
China's premier acknowledged 'mistakes' in the government's performance,
including a 'fairly sharp rise in prices'. He pledged additional efforts to
restrain price rises, but gave little indication of what steps might be
taken to curb cost-of-living increases.
He announced few new initiatives in his 90-minute address, but reminded
delegates that China in its present phase of explosive economic growth was
'presented with a rare historical opportunity'. Among his main points were:
China's GDP growth target for this year is 9 per cent. China forecast 8 per
cent growth in 1993, but the economy grew by 13 per cent last year and shows
little sign of slowing.
State enterprises in 'dire straits' would receive some assistance, but in
the end 'must rely on their own efforts to extricate themselves from their
predicament'. Attempts would be made to accelerate enterprise reform.
New capital spending would be restricted to construction projects already
under way with special emphasis on China's infrastructure requirements.
China should proceed gradually with banking reforms aimed at ensuring that
commercial banks are relieved of their policy-lending obligations. A
National Development Bank for infrastructure is to be established.
Mr Li won applause for remarks that amounted to a slap at Britain over Hong
Kong. 'No matter what happens, the Chinese government and people are
determined and able to resume the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong as
scheduled and to ensure long-term stability and prosperity there.
'British colonial rule in Hong Kong is coming to an end. No force can stop
that.'
</TEXT>
