<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / EU compensation 'unfair'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Compensation awards for similar types of personal injury typically vary by
600 per cent across Europe, according to a report by Davies Arnold Cooper, a
leading firm of City solicitors. A review of award levels in 13 EU countries
(including Scotland) and seven EFTA countries showed anomalies which were
'hugely unfair to European citizens and businesses', said Mr David McIntosh,
a senior partner at the firm. Irish courts generally made the biggest
awards, while courts in Greece, Portugal, Spain, Norway and Denmark were
less generous. Non-economic awards - for bereavement or pain and suffering -
varied from nothing to Pounds 250,000, with the higher rates awarded in
predominantly Catholic countries, the report said. Mr McIntosh urged
Brussels to launch a formal inquiry into the problem and urged the
introduction of Europe-wide guidelines on compensation levels.
</TEXT>
