<TEXT>
Mr Jacques Chirac, the Gaullist RPR's candidate for the French presidential
elections in 1995, was almost level with the prime minister, Mr Edouard
Balladur, in a poll on who is best placed to beat the likely Socialist
candidate, Mr Michel Rocard. The poll, published yesterday in the weekly
Valeurs Actuelles, said Mr Balladur could beat Mr Rocard by 56 per cent to
44 per cent, while Mr Chirac could win by 55 per cent to 45 per cent. Mr
Balladur, a longtime Chirac aide and RPR member, has not yet said whether he
will run. But several polls published on Wednesday suggested that Mr
Balladur had fallen from favour. A Gallup poll for L'Express, France's
leading news magazine, gave his approval rating as 47 per cent, compared
with around 60 per cent for most of 1993.
