<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / US funds for Czech N-plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US Export-Import Bank has given its final approval to Dollars 317m
(Pounds 217m) of loan guarantees for upgrading the controversial
Soviet-designed nuclear reactor at Temelin, in the Czech Republic. Temelin
is close to the Czech border with Austria, and the Austrian government has
fiercely contested the plans to bring the still uncompleted reactor into
service. Eximbank said its guarantees would help finance Dollars 334m of
improvements to be carried out by Westinghouse Electric to the
instrumentation, control and fuel systems of the Temelin reactor. Studies by
the US and by the International Atomic Energy Agency have indicated that the
Soviet VVER-1000 reactor can be operated as safely as western-designed light
water reactors, so long as control improvements are made. The control system
Westinghouse will install at Temelin is, according to US nuclear experts,
more advanced than that operating at the UK's Sizewell B reactor.
</TEXT>
