FT  11 MAR 94 / Bundesbank rate cut pledge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The explosion in German money supply in January is not a fundamental
obstacle to further cuts in German interest rates, senior Bundesbank
officials said yesterday - remarks apparently designed to calm the nerves of
unsteady financial markets. The Bundesbank would stick to its anti-inflation
course, said Mr Hans Tietmeyer, the central bank president, but this was not
inconsistent with further falls in money market and capital market interest
rates. Two other members of the Bundesbank council stressed that the 20.6
per cent increase in M3 broad money supply in January was an aberration and
that the central bank would continue with its exceedingly cautious programme
of interest rate cuts. The January M3 data, released last week, far exceeded
economists' most pessimistic predictions and deeply unsettled financial
markets despite the Bundesbank's explanation of the special factors that lay
behind the strong rise.
</TEXT>
