<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Lenin's namesake carries capitalist flag: Vladivostok is
heading for the free economy thanks to one Vladimir Ulianov
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Perched on Russia's craggy eastern coast, Vladivostok is a potentially
vibrant Pacific Rim city struggling to emerge from its dross Soviet shell.
Right-hand drive Japanese cars - a third of the price of inferior Russian
vehicles - abound. The best hotel in town, the Vlad Motor Inn, was shipped
over, fully built from western Canada and offers the same amenities as any
comfortable Canadian inn, from fluffy towels to Molson's beer.
But, as the ugly Soviet apartment blocks which mar Vladivostok's picturesque
natural setting suggest, the city's and Russia's communist past still
threatens to block its market development.
The home port of the rusting Pacific fleet and the site of defence
industries which employ much of the city's workforce, Vladivostok has a
powerful anti-reform constituency, which has found an ally in the region's
new governor.
Moreover, the xenophobia which was expressed here and elsewhere in Russia,
with strong support for the extreme right in the December elections, has an
added fillip in Vladivostok because of widespread local fears of
economically thriving China, just a three-hour drive away. Vladivostok's
biggest success story is its stock exchange, the most active in Russia.
Unlike most exchanges in the country, which trade in commodities or
privatisation vouchers, the Vladivostok exchange trades only in the shares
of privatised companies. It can do so because 230 of the 500 large-scale
enterprises in the Vladivostok area have already been transformed into joint
stock companies - a figure which makes the region Russia's leader in
large-scale privatisation.
Mr Viktor Sakharov, a bearded former marine biologist who is president of
the stock exchange, says the booming activity on the exchange, where Rbs100m
worth of shares are traded on average each week, is teaching the directors
of local large enterprises to look to the private sector rather than the
government for capital.
'Factory directors are beginning to understand that no-one will give them
money any more, that the days of cheap credits are over,' says Mr Sakharov,
who gives weekly economics lectures to the 'Red Barons' in the hope of
'pounding some market economics into their heads'. The managers are
learning. Mr Sakharov believes that that the only way to get capital
investment is through share offers. Foreigners are also starting to get in
on the action. Mr Sakharov estimates that British, Australian, South Korean
and Japanese investors have already purchased Dollars 3m (Pounds 2m) worth
of shares and says Dollars 24m is in the pipeline from the United States and
the UK.
The biggest obstacle to more foreign investment is physical. To buy shares
traded on the Vladivostok stock exchange investors must first make the
gruelling journey to this Pacific outpost.
A few hardy western businessmen live in Vladivostok and act as local agents
for UK, US and Asian companies.
Investing could become easier if Seji, the most active investment company
operating on the exchange, succeeds in its plan to open an office at the
Hong Kong stock exchange this spring.
Seji's trading operations are run by the ironically named Mr Vladimir
Ulianov. But although the thin, nervy businessman bears the name Russia's
first Bolshevik leader was known by until he assumed the more familiar nom
de guerre of Lenin, the present-day Mr Ulianov is the face of Russia's
fledgling, and embattled, capitalist revolution.
In 1991, Mr Ulianov and a small group of fellow officers serving in the
Pacific fleet decided that they had better prospects working in Russia's
nascent market economy than in its rusting navy.
Since then, it's been clear sailing. Seji now has working capital
approaching Rbs2bn and in November alone turned a profit of Rbs368m
speculating in the shares of just one company, Sesco, the Far Eastern
Shipping Company.
A typical project is Seji's plan to finance the production of light aircraft
at a local defence plant in which it holds a 10 per cent interest. Seji is
willing to raise the Rbs3bn which the cash-strapped factory requires to
produce helicopters and light aircraft, but only on the condition that it
has control over how the money is spent and where the profits from eventual
sales go.
Without tough controls, Mr Ulianov explains, any investment in a Russian
factory disappears in subsidies to loss-making divisions of the enterprise.
'Crudely put, our strategy is not to give any cash to the factory
directors,' Mr Ulianov says. 'The factory is only allowed to be the
assembler.'
This is the maxim of every successful Russian businessman, but it is a point
which has been lost on western aid donors and on the representatives of the
old Soviet elite at the top of the Russian government, including the prime
minister, Mr Victor Chernomyrdin, whose hand has been strengthened by the
result of the December elections.
If Mr Chernomyrdin has his way and the flow of soft credits to Russia's 'Red
Barons' is renewed, they will again be in a position to resist the tough
financial constraints imposed by private businessmen such as Mr Ulianov and
other investors in Vladivostok's exchange. Citing this sort of anti-reform
action in the aftermath of the elections, a worried Mr Sakharov said: 'We
knew our people were stupid, that they were an ignorant, lumpen proletariat,
but we had no idea that they were quite so stupid.'
</TEXT>
