<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Spanish MPs in voting row
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Spain's parliament was suspended for two hours yesterday amid angry
accusations from opposition deputies that ruling socialists had voted more
than once during a debate on labour reforms. The house was voting on
opposition amendments to the government's labour reforms, which sparked a
24-hour general strike earlier this year. The opposition Popular party lost
the amendments by just two votes, but said socialists had voted for absent
colleagues by secretly pushing the buttons which electronically register the
votes. Deputies stamped and hissed when it was revealed that six more votes
were counted in one ballot than in the next. The matter was referred to the
House Committee who will investigate the charges of vote-rigging. Reuter,
Madrid.
</TEXT>
