<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Lisbon minister puts boot in over tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER WISE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Portuguese government has dismissed the head of the tax department and
threatened to auction assets of a top football club as part of a crackdown
aimed at stemming a big shortfall in tax revenue.
The move by Mr Eduardo Catroga, finance minister, was praised as courageous
by tax consultants. But officials of FC Porto, the football club, said it
was an affront to their dignity - particularly the listing of the lavatory
of the referees' changing room as one of the assets to seize.
Mr Francisco Rodrigues Porto was dismissed as director general of taxes
after revenue in 1993 fell Es373bn (Pounds 1.43bn) below the government
forecast. The shortfall was the main cause of a doubling of the forecast
budget deficit last year to 8.2 per cent of gross domestic product.
However, Mr Vasco Valdes, the member of government directly responsible for
taxes last year, was promoted in a cabinet reshuffle in December.
Tax specialists said an increase in VAT on basic foods and restaurants had
led many small shopkeepers and cafe owners to resort to the black market.
The abolition of border collections of VAT on imports had further increased
tax evasion.
The computer system for processing tax collection was also woefully
inefficient, they said, because of government cost-cutting measures that had
frozen spending on hardware, software and personnel.
No other signal that Mr Catroga is determined to fight tax evasion could
have been stronger than his decision to tackle a leading football club.
'Football teams spend billions on foreign players they can't afford and
simply ignore the taxman,' said a tax consultant. 'Until now politicians,
fearful for their popularity, had just shrugged their shoulders.
FC Porto officials were so taken aback by the threat to seize assets to
secure part of an estimated Es1bn in tax and social security arrears that
they called an emergency meeting yesterday.
Analysts now wonder whether Mr Catroga's zeal to combat tax evasion will
lead him to tackle a case with more serious implications. The attorney
general is investigating 67 companies alleged to have to sold false invoices
to other companies to enable them to claim fictitious VAT and corporate tax
repayments. Police are reported to be investigating dozens of other
companies, many of whom are alleged to be contributors to political party
funds.
</TEXT>
