<DATE>940311
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Germany's coalition faces a mauling from the jobless in year
of the voter: As the SPD faces its most promising opportunity in 12 years to
beat Chancellor Kohl's coalition, Quentin Peel hears what politicians in the
first of 19 poll battles across the country are telling aerospace workers
fighting to save their jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
At the gates of the Deutsche Aerospace plant at Lemwerder, in the bleak
marshes of the Weser estuary in the north German state of Lower Saxony,
several hundred bitter and baffled workers gathered this week to demonstrate
their determination to save their jobs.
Since last October they have mounted a permanent vigil at the gates to
protest against the impending closure of the factory, where the Transall
military transport aircraft is built, and Airbus aircraft serviced.
The entire 1,200-strong skilled labour force is set to be sacked as part of
a restructuring programme in the German aerospace industry, battered by cuts
in military spending and the slump in demand for civilian aircraft such as
the Airbus.
Their guest of honour on the makeshift speaker's platform was Mr Rudolf
Scharping, leader of the opposition Social Democratic party (SPD), and the
man who hopes to win the next general election on October 16 to become
federal chancellor in Bonn.
The trouble was that he had little firm hope to offer the workers at
Lemwerder, for his own party stands for even more drastic cuts in the
country's defence budget than the present liberal-conservative coalition
headed by Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
'I have come here because I believe that politicians have the goddam duty to
go to the very places where decisions are being taken about jobs,' he said.
'It is all very well to fly off to the Far East, like Chancellor Kohl, and
lecture people about blooming landscapes. They should come and visit the
places in Germany where the jobs are under threat.'
It was a good line for the cameras, but it was not really what the
threatened workers had come to hear. They wanted promises that a future SPD
government in Bonn would provide the new orders to keep them in business.
Mr Scharping could only promise to 'create a stable framework' for business
to do its best. As for military spending, he admitted he wants further job
cuts in the Bundeswehr, down from the present 370,000 to just 300,000.
The opposition leader is treading an acutely cautious path in his long
campaign to overthrow the Kohl coalition, desperately anxious not to give
any hostages to fortune which may destroy his party's best chance of power
since it fell from grace in 1982.
'Jobs, jobs and jobs again,' is the campaign theme of the SPD at the start
of Germany's 1994 election marathon, which culminates in the general
election on October 16.
It is by far the greatest concern of the electorate, beyond law and order,
immigration, social welfare, housing or education. Mr Scharping is concerned
to show that his party not only cares, but that it has ideas about how to
create new jobs. Lemwerder was a tough place to start.
Mr Scharping was left in little doubt about what the failure of any rescue
plan for Lemwerder might mean.
'The anger of the people is aimed against the managers, for now,' said Mr
Erwin Nowak, chairman of the works council. 'But if Lemwerder is not saved,
then all the big parties will certainly feel it at the general election.'
This week the focus of Germany's entire political establishment is on the
first poll of no less than 19, among the 5.9m electors in the state of Lower
Saxony. It should give some clear indications about the spate of elections
to come.
The outcome of Sunday's vote is in little doubt: Mr Scharping's colleague
and erstwhile rival for the SPD leadership, Mr Gerhard Schroder, looks set
to be swept back to power as premier in the state parliament in Hanover.
His red-green coalition, between the SPD and the Green Party, has a big lead
in the opinion polls over Chancellor Kohl's Christian Democratic Union
(CDU).
Recent opinion polls give the SPD some 45 per cent support in the state,
against 35 for the CDU. In 1990, the SPD won power from the CDU with 44.2
per cent to 42.0, while the Greens, with 5.5 per cent, made up the
difference. The Free Democratic Party (FDP), Mr Kohl's partners in Bonn,
managed 6 per cent then, but this time they are in danger of falling below
the 5 per cent minimum needed to win any seats.
The Greens could do a little better this time - one poll gives them 8 per
cent support. If the FDP fails to make the grade, it means Mr Schroder has a
chance of an absolute majority.
The unknown in this election is how the extreme right-wing Republicans will
perform, as well as an assortment of other citizens' movements. In the
opinion polls, only 3 per cent say they will vote for the Republicans, but
there is still a big proportion - around one in three  - undecided.
Mr Schroder's success has been that, in spite of fears in the business
community when he formed his red-green government four years ago, he has
proved to be far more pragmatic than his left-wing credentials suggested. As
unemployment in the state has risen towards 11 per cent - the second highest
in west Germany - he has become ever more concerned to be friendly towards
industry, and distance himself from the stern environmentalism of his
coalition partners.
Indeed, he stunned the last SPD party conference in Wiesbaden by citing
Lemwerder as a case for giving defence industries a better deal. He was
denounced by his party colleagues, but the message to the Lower Saxony
electors was clear: for Gerhard Schroder, jobs come even before party
politics.
His success has left the CDU bewildered and trailing. 'He is a pure
pragmatist without principles, and erratic, too,' says Mr Christian Wulff,
his 34-year-old CDU challenger. 'We say red-green is unfriendly to business.
Look at Lemwerder: the red-green coalition has banned military research in
the state, so it has all gone to Bavaria. Now they wonder why companies like
Dasa close down in Lower Saxony entirely.'
Mr Wulff, who has been a staunch Christian Democrat since he was a
schoolboy, has chosen a campaign poster with a huge black-and-white close-up
of former Chancellor Konrad Adenauer in the background, and a modest little
colour photograph of himself in front.
His critics say he is deliberately trying to distance himself from Mr Kohl
by identifying with the CDU's great founding father.
Yet Mr Kohl is about the only real weapon he has. His style is a total
contrast to that of Mr Scharping. At a rally in the sports hall of Nienburg,
north of Hanover, last week, the chancellor was relaxed, fatherly,
deliberately cultivating his statesman's image.
He made the same speech he has been making for months, calmly ignoring his
unpopularity in the polls. I am the man who delivered unification, the safe
old face you can trust, he seems to say. I know all the actors on the world
stage, and they trust me. Germany is going through a turbulent time, and the
outside world is in turmoil. But I am unflappable and unmovable. Stick with
me.
It is a message which is just starting to get through to an electorate which
none the less is heartily fed up with the current administration in Bonn,
and says it wants a change. But it is a message which is certainly too late
to save Mr Wulff from defeat in Lower Saxony.
As far as Mr Schroder is concerned, he is already almost home and dry. But
Mr Scharping and Mr Kohl have their eyes fixed firmly on a much more distant
goal.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
German elections: a marathon which could change the political landscape
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
March 13
Lower Saxony parliament
Sunday's poll for the state's parliament is the first vote in Germany's
election marathon which involves six other state parliaments, elections
for local authorities in nine states, the electoral assembly
(convention) to choose the next federal president in May, the poll for
the European Parliament in June, and finally the general election on
October 16. Lower Saxony will send the first signals for a campaign
which could transform the political face of the country.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
March 20
Schleswig-Holstein local councils
These are the first in a series of local council elections which could
well see a big backlash against the traditional political parties in
favour of local citizens' movements. The local authorities are
responsible for most local services and have been forced by financial
stringency to cut back in many areas, and raise their charges. The main
round of elections coincide with the European poll on June 12, with
North Rhine-Westphalia, the most populous state, coming to the polls on
October 16.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
May 23
Presidential convention
The federal convention, or electoral college, in Berlin will elect a
federal president to succeed President Richard von Weizsacker. The real
contest is between Mr Roman Herzog, the president of the federal
constitutional court, for the Christian Democratic Union, and Mr
Johannes Rau, prime minister of North Rhine-Westphalia, for the Social
Democratic party. How the minority Free Democratic party votes will
almost certainly decide the issue.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
June 12
European parliament
These elections throughout Germany will provide the first national
indicator of popular political trends. The fear of the main parties is
that voters may be tempted to vote for extremist protest parties, like
the extreme right-wing, nationalist Republicans, because they do not
consider the poll as important as a national election. Additionally,
local council polls are being held in seven states. (See March 20 above)
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
June 26, Sept 11, 25, Oct 16
State parliaments
There are six elections, five in east Germany. Again, the greatest fear
is over a backlash against the traditional political parties of
centre-left and centre-right, because of unhappiness over the
consequences of unification and the resulting high unemployment. The
exception is in the west, in Bavaria, where the conservative Christian
Social Union is struggling to maintain its absolute majority in the
parliament.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Oct 16
National elections
The finishing line for the exhausted campaigners and the moment of
truth for Chancellor Helmut Kohl's conservative-liberal coalition. Can
he reverse what looks certain to be a string of negative results in the
state and local elections, and still hang onto power in Bonn? Or will
Mr Rudolf Scharping, the youthful SPD leader, persuade the cautious
voters that his party is 'capable of government' at national as well as
provincial level?
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
