<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Irish telecoms tariffs cut by competition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Fierce competition has broken out in the international sector of the Irish
telecommunications market, worth IPounds 200m (Pounds 192m) a year, since
the state-run telecommunications company Telecom Eireann opened up the
market last autumn.
The latest entrant is International Telecommunications Ltd (ITL), a private
Irish company, which began operations yesterday. It is offering business
customers reductions of 30 per cent on Telecom Eireann's tariffs for most
international calls. The company said it would not charge sign-up fees or
service charges, nor impose minimum traffic levels. Nor would customers be
obliged to use ITL's service exclusively.
Telecom Eireann says it will 'compete aggressively' for market share. Last
month it introduced a 30 per cent volume discount for customers with
international traffic of more than IPounds 2,000 a month. It also introduced
a new tariff structure last September, cutting the cost of international
calls by up to 40 per cent.
Mr Fergus McGovern, chief executive of Telecom Eireann, said yesterday the
new tariffs had resulted in 28 per cent a year growth in the company's
international traffic.
Around 30 per cent of the company's total call revenues of IPounds 600m come
from international traffic.
Under European Union competition directives, Telecom must relinquish its
monopoly of the Irish market by 2003, and since last autumn has had to allow
competitors access to its international business.
Around half of international calls made are to the UK. British Telecom,
which launched a service out of Ireland for business customers last
November, says Ireland is the second largest international direct dialling
route out of the UK.
Allied Irish Bank, one of the biggest customers of Telecom Eireann, is
shortly to put out a tender for its international call traffic.
Earlier this month, it was confirmed that Telecom Eireann is seeking 'a
strategic alliance' and that a proposal has been received from Cable and
Wireless, thought to be worth up to IPounds 500m, to set up a joint venture
to handle Telecom Eireann's international calls business.
</TEXT>
