<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Germans settle row over care for aged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
One of the longest-running political battles in Bonn, over the creation of a
new social security scheme to finance nursing care for the aged and
handicapped, was yesterday settled in a top-level cross-party compromise.
Almost 20 years after plans for the scheme were first proposed, the final
details were thrashed out in talks between leaders of the ruling coalition
and the opposition Social Democrats (SPD).
It means German workers and employers will have to pay an extra 1 per cent
in social security contributions from January 1, rising to 1.7 per cent in
later years, to finance the introduction of statutory nursing care
insurance.
The scheme will pay for the cost of care in old peoples' homes, and of
residential care in their own homes for the elderly and handicapped. The
costs have hitherto been paid by local authorities, but soaring numbers of
old people threatened to overwhelm their financial resources.
The annual cost of residential care is estimated initially at DM14.4bn,
(Pounds 5.60bn) with additional administrative costs of around DM1bn. Up to
2.1m old and handicapped people are estimated to be eligible for assistance.
Strong industry opposition to the deal was overwhelmed by the determination
of the political parties to be seen to be capable of making a decision in an
election year, when electors are threatening a backlash against the whole
political establishment.
The deal was done yesterday after several hours of negotiations between Mr
Rudolf Scharping, leader of the SPD, and Mr Wolfgang Schauble, parliamentary
leader of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), the main party in the ruling
coalition.
Mr Scharping reached the deal against the objections of many within his own
party, who claim that the compromise amounts to an infringement of wage
bargaining autonomy in German industry.
The key to the compromise was an agreement to offset the increased costs to
industry by the cancellation of one day's holiday per year, providing one
extra day's work. That is supposed to pay for the first phase of the scheme,
to finance nursing care at home.
There is no agreement on compensatory measures to offset the second phase,
the cost of care in residential homes. That will be subject to a report by
the government's independent economic advisers, the so-called 'five wise
men."
</TEXT>
