<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Northrop launches Pounds 1.39bn hostile offer for Grumman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A takeover battle erupted last night over US defence group Grumman, as
military aircraft manufacturer Northrop launched a Dollars 2.04bn (Pounds
1.39bn) hostile offer in response to an agreed Dollars 1.9bn bid unveiled by
Martin Marietta on Monday.
Northrop coupled its bid with an attack on Grumman's board for entering into
a takeover deal with Martin Marietta, even though Northrop and Grumman had
spent months in late 1993 and early 1994 discussing a friendly merger.
It described as 'improper and illegal' a so-called lock-up agreement under
which Grumman will pay Martin Marietta Dollars 50m if its offer for the
company is outbid, and said this did not serve shareholders' interests.
Northrop is bidding Dollars 60 a share in cash for Grumman, compared to
Dollars 55 a share in cash on offer from Martin Marietta. Grumman's
shares,which closed at Dollars 54 7/8 , down Dollars  1/8 in normal trading
yesterday, soared to Dollars 61 3/4 in after-hours dealing.
Northrop said it had arranged financing commitments of Dollars 2.8bn from
Chase Manhattan Bank and Chemical Bank. Martin Marietta's bid is being
financed by BankAmerica and JP Morgan.
The struggle for Grumman manifests the consolidation in the US defence
industry, which is rationalising in the face of a shrinking Pentagon budget.
Most deals in the sector have been friendly, though in 1992 Martin Marietta
and Northrop were on opposite sides of a Dollars 475m battle for LTV's
missiles and aircraft divisions. That tussle was won by Northrop and two
allies - Loral and Carlyle Group.
Northrop, based in Los Angeles, has sales of about Dollars 5bn and derives
roughly half its revenues from the B-2 stealth bomber programme, which is
being wound down. It also makes the F-18 fighter and fuselage sections for
Boeing 747 commercial jumbo jets. Maryland-based Martin Marietta, with 1993
sales of Dollars 9.3bn, has been expanding rapidly through takeovers.
Both companies argue that Grumman, which used to be known primarily as a
maker of warplanes, but has diversified in recent years into electronics and
data systems, would make an excellent strategic fit and immediately add to
their earnings per share. Some 40 per cent of Grumman's shares are owned by
an employee investment plan.
Mr Kent Kresa, chairman of Northrop, said that his company and Grumman had
conducted months of merger discussions because of the fit between the
businesses, and as late as February 25 Northrop had offered to make a bid of
'not less than Dollars 50 a share, if invited to do so.'
He complained that Grumman had signed a merger agreement with Martin
Marietta, without informing Northrop that it was in negotiations or inviting
the company's best bid.
