<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Forces join S Africa 'homeland' revolt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MMABATHO, BOPHUTHATSWANA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Confusion reigned in the South African black 'homeland' of Bophuthatswana
yesterday as hundreds of police and soldiers revolted against the government
along with thousands of looting protesters, celebrating what they believed
was the overthrow of President Lucas Mangope.
Early this morning, however, there were reports that soldiers loyal to
President Mangope had opened fire on protesters in the capital Mmabatho and
the town of Mafikeng as troops of the nominally-independent homeland tried
to restore order.
The president's whereabouts were not known, but there were persistent
reports he had fled by helicopter. It was unclear however whether he had
left the homeland or was attempting to regroup his forces from his home
village.
Armed right-wing whites sympathetic to Mr Mangope, who had vowed to keep the
homeland independent of a new black South Africa, were reported to be
gathering outside the towns, some driving into the capital on what appeared
to be military scouting missions.
The Afrikaner Resistance Movement, a neo-Nazi group that has vowed to fight
against black rule in South Africa, had said it would send its members to
Bophuthatswana to help stave off an African National Congress-led coup in
the run up to next month's general election. Mr Mangope is an adamant foe of
the ANC and had refused to let Bophuthatswana participate in the April 26-28
poll, which the ANC is expected to win easily. His demise would be a
substantial victory for the ANC.
South Africa's 'ambassador' in Mmabatho, Tjaart Van der Walt, said last
night Mr Mangope had told him he was going to his country residence outside
the city. South African officials said Mr Van der Walt had assured them Mr
Mangope would be able to regain control, although early this morning this
seemed highly uncertain.
The violent protests started four days ago when demonstrators demanded the
homeland be reincorporated into South Africa and take part in the country's
first all-race elections. With a population of slightly more than 2m it is
one of 10 black homelands created by Pretoria under its discredited
apartheid policy.
'We are free, at last]' shouted one demonstrator outside the campus of the
University of Bophuthatswana yesterday. Other protesters waving ANC flags
clambered on to police armoured vehicles to embrace those who only moments
before had shot volleys of teargas and rubber bullets into the campus.
Soldiers and police stood by as thousands of protesters looted and set light
to a large shopping complex in the capital Mmabatho, which demonstrators
said was owned by a company in which the president held shares. Gunfire
filled the streets of the capital and looting went on for several hours,
with demonstrators carrying out furniture, computer equipment, kitchenware,
televisions and clothing.
There were jubilant scenes as police laid down their arms and invited
'comrades' - young ANC students - to climb on to police and army vehicles,
including a water cannon which had been used against students. Police and
students went to the South African embassy to deliver a petition entitled
'police for peace', addressed to Mr Mangope and demanding that he stop using
the police as a political force.
People of 'Bop' turn backs on a loser, Page 4
