<HEADLINE>
FT  11 MAR 94 / Forces join S Africa 'homeland' revolt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MMABATHO, BOPHUTHATSWANA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Police and soldiers in the South African black 'homeland' of Bophuthatswana
revolted against the government yesterday, joining thousands of jubilant
protesters celebrating what they believed was the overthrow of President
Lucas Mangope.
'We are free, at last]' shouted one demonstrator outside the campus of the
University of Bophuthatswana. Other protesters waving African National
Congress flags clambered on to police armoured vehicles to embrace those who
only moments before had shot volleys of teargas and rubber bullets into the
campus.
The president's whereabouts were not known last night, but there were
persistent reports that he had fled. It was not clear whether the whole of
the homeland's police force and army had switched to the side of the
demonstrators.
Soldiers and police stood by last night as thousands of protesters looted
and set alight to a large shopping complex in the capital Mmabatho, which
the demonstrators said was owned by a company in which the president held
shares.
Looting went on for several hours, with demonstrators carrying out
furniture, computer equipment, kitchenware, televisions and clothing.
Gunfire filled the streets of the capital last night as protesters
celebrated their victory.
Earlier in the day there were jubilant scenes as police laid down their arms
and invited 'comrades' - young ANC students - to climb on to police and army
vehicles, including a water cannon which had been used against students.
Police and students went to the South African embassy in Mmabatho to deliver
a petition entitled 'police for peace', addressed to Mr Mangope and
demanding that he stop using the police as a political force. The petition
also included a number of economic demands.
There appeared to have been no attempts to take over government buildings,
the president's office or the homes of ministers last night, but the
whereabouts of ministers were unknown.
South African officials said they had been assured by their 'ambassador' in
Mmabatho that Mr Mangope would be able to regain control, although this
seemed unlikely last night.
There were, however, reports that members of the paramilitary Afrikaner
Resistance Movement had set off for Bophuthatswana from a nearby town, to
assist their right wing ally Mr Mangope.
If the president has indeed fallen, this would represent a blow to the
efforts of the right-wing Freedom Alliance to boycott April's all-race
elections, though the main partners in the alliance, Inkatha and the
Afrikaner Volksfront, yesterday reaffirmed their resistance.
Gen Constand Viljoen, Afrikaner Volksfront leader, said negotiations with
the ANC would be halted until the ANC recognised the sovereignty of
Bophuthatswana - a demand which may have been overtaken by last night's
events.
</TEXT>
