<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Bophuthatswana paralysed by poll strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MMABATHO, BOPHUTHATSWANA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Riot police fired at demonstrators in the South African black 'homeland' of
Bophuthatswana for the second day running yesterday as a civil service
strike paralysed the government of the increasingly embattled President
Lucas Mangope. At least 32 people were wounded, witnesses said. The homeland
government said a police officer was killed.
Mr Mangope, who yesterday closed the broadcasting service and sacked its
staff, rejected a request from the Independent Electoral Commission to allow
campaigning and polling for South Africa's April elections to take place in
the homeland. Bophuthatswana said earlier this week it would not participate
in these elections.
As teargas drifted toward the government offices from the nearby University
of Bophuthatswana, Mr Ephraim Keikalame, finance minister, admitted: 'It is
not possible to have an effective functioning government under these
circumstances.'
Almost the entire public service appeared to be on strike, but telephones
and electricity continued to function. The capital's main hospital complex
was deserted by staff. Outside the university, police armoured vehicles
roared up and down throughout the day, firing teargas canisters and rubber
bullets at students barricading the entrance gate.
'This is the kick of a dying horse,' said one student, weeping from the
effects of the gas, while another vowed: 'We want to make Bop ungovernable.'
Using rubbish bin lids as shields and brandishing sticks as spears, students
did the toyi-toyi dance, the hallmark of the African National Congress, as
they demanded that nominally independent Bophuthatswana, a creation of
apartheid, be reincorporated into South Africa. The rioting provoked a
threat of direct South African intervention, with the Transitional Executive
Council, the multi-party body overseeing government in the run-up to
elections, saying it would give Mr Mangope a week 'to change his attitude'.
Meanwhile there was uncertainty last night over whether various rightwing
South African parties would contest the April elections. Parties were due to
lodge candidate lists by yesterday afternoon, but many - including the
mainly-Zulu Inkatha Freedom party and the right wing Freedom Front - failed
to do so.
</TEXT>
