<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Brazil minister seeks poll pact
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRASLIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso, Brazil's finance minister, has been in
exploratory talks with the right-of-centre Liberal Front party (PFL), the
second-largest in Congress, with a view to building an alliance ahead of
October's presidential elections.
Both sides are reluctant to talk about the discussions, which are still at
an early stage.
Mr Cardoso, who is trying to push an ambitious economic restructuring
programme through Congress, is also measuring reaction to the proposed
alliance within his own party, the Social Democratic Movement (PSDB).
Linking with the PFL would provide Mr Cardoso with a viable political base
and support in the country's north-east, where he has looked weak in all
opinion polls. It would also provide a strong challenge to the present
presidential front-runner, Mr Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva of the left-wing
Workers party.
In the latest polls, Mr da Silva won 30 per cent backing compared with Mr
Cardoso's 11 per cent.
Mr Lus Eduardo Magalhaes, leader of the PFL in the lower house, said the
situation should become clearer by the end of this month, the deadline for
Mr Cardoso to resign under Brazilian law if he wants to run for president.
</TEXT>
