<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Saudi snub for Hussein
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES WHITTINGTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMMAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
King Hussein of Jordan's efforts to mend fences with Saudi Arabia, which
still begrudges Amman's pro-Iraqi stance during the 1990-1991 Gulf crisis,
were shattered yesterday when he failed to meet King Fahd during a short
visit to the Saudi kingdom, James Whittington writes from Amman.
Although the trip was presented from the Jordanian side as a minor
pilgrimage to perform the Umra at religious sites, officials in Amman had
been privately optimistic that a rapprochement between the two monarchs was
possible.
'We simply would not have made the trip if we thought King Fahd would not
see us,' conceded one senior official.
Diplomats described the trip as a 'serious snub' to King Hussein. 'It shows
clearly that the Saudis have not forgiven him for what they saw as an act of
betrayal during the Gulf war,' one said.
