<DATE>940310
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1994 - Office Automation
(24): Setting the pace - Implementation / Work flow is changing the way
Britannia Building Society operates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britannia Building Society is working on a strategy for office automation
which will put it at the heart of the society's operations, writes John
Kavanagh. The strategy will be based on document image processing and work
flow automation, which have already been used to redesign the handling of
mortgage arrears and property recovery.
Britannia, one of the top 10 building societies in the UK, was claimed by
its supplier, Olivetti, to have been the first organisation in the UK to
adopt document image processing. That was in 1986.
The society, based in Leek, Staffordshire, and with 200 branches, is thought
to have the biggest installation in Europe, with 180 workstations served by
a Filenet system. Olivetti introduced the system in the UK and still sells
it, although US supplier Filenet now has its own operation here.
For the first few years, Britannia used the system purely for storing and
accessing documents on screens instead of as paper files. Everything from
the mortgage application form onwards, but excluding property deeds, is
scanned in or entered as word processor files. All queries are dealt with
through the system: original documents are no longer kept.
Tax forms relating to investment accounts have been scanned in since they
were introduced in 1991. The society would have needed extra staff to handle
them manually but won agreement from the Inland Revenue that images would be
acceptable.
These paper storage and retrieval applications alone brought significant
savings but the society is now also increasingly exploiting the automated
work flow potential of the system.
Early last year, Britannia transformed the handling of arrears, building it
around work flow and on-line access to information. The changes made a
'significant impact', according to Mr Barry Foster, head of systems
development. Well over Pounds 10m in arrears was collected in 1993 and a
large percentage was seen as directly attributable to the new system.
'Previously we sent progressively serious letters, but we now work through
telephone contact,' Mr Foster says. 'The department has been reorganised
into teams, who work shifts so that they can call people at home in the
evenings.
'Every night our ICL mainframe works out which accounts have gone into
arrears and passes them to the Filenet system. All documents, such as
correspondence, relating to each case are scanned in and the system can also
retrieve accounts and other data from the mainframe, so staff have immediate
access to all information when they call. Filenet keeps track of cases if
they progress to litigation and recovery of the property.'
Having fully automated the post-mortgage processes, Britannia is now looking
at activities which lead up to a mortgage being accepted.
'We're piloting a PC-based sales system which will be the front-end to the
entire process and installed at the point of first contact with the customer
in the branches,' Barry Foster says.
'This means the whole process from customer contact to handling
applications, completion, sending the payment and passing the data over to
the administration system is being totally reviewed. The Filenet system will
play a part in the redesign.'
Other developments being considered include putting branches on-line to the
document retrieval system and providing similar document handling and work
flow facilities to insurance company Britannia Life.
'In all developments we have to be convinced of the benefits, because this
is an expensive technology,' Barry Foster says. 'In addition, we've been
installing more and more PCs instead of simple terminals as workstations to
the Filenet system. The terminal response times have not been good - 10
seconds or more - and PC response times are quicker, because the PC can
handle more of the processing. Response times have been the subject of more
discussions with Olivetti and Filenet than any other issue.'
The latest discussions are over the replacement of the ageing Filenet
central processor - 'we want some assurances before we make the move but
we're confident that there will be significant improvements,' Mr Foster
says. 'Despite the response times, the system is still far faster than
having to look for paper files.'
System performance upgrades and strategy review are the main preoccupations
of Barry Foster and his team at present. Their deliberations are likely to
have a considerable impact on the future of the society.
'The society is going through very considerable change at branch level and
in business redesign,' he says. 'Work flow will be an increasingly
significant part of the strategy.'
Filenet
Filenet for document image processing and Workflo software for work flow
automation, launched in 1985 and now on version 3.1, released in 1993.
Supplier: Filenet, a US company formed in 1982. Olivetti launched its
products in the UK in 1985 and Filenet set up a UK operation in 1991.
Filenet's 1993 turnover was up by 14 per cent at Dollars 158m; the company
has 900 staff world-wide, including 150 in Europe.
Price: A typical system, including central processor, an optical disc
jukebox and work flow software, costs around Pounds 100,000.
Number of users: There are 35 customers in the UK and 730 world-wide.
</TEXT>
