<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1994 - Office Automation
(22): Customer service enhanced - Electronic forms / Electronic mail has
long taken over from telexes and paper forms at Mercedes-Benz
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mercedes-Benz originally installed Verimation's Memo office automation
package to get rid of telexes. Today, the vehicle manufacturer not only uses
the package as its standard method of telecommunications, both internally
and to dealers, but also as a replacement for paper forms, writes John
Kavanagh.
Mercedes-Benz has 1,000 staff and 180 franchisees in the UK. It introduced
Memo in 1988 on its IBM mainframe computer at the UK headquarters in Milton
Keynes. The franchisees now have computer systems of their own and all but a
handful connect to the mainframe to use Memo. There are 2,000 electronic
mailbox users on the UK system.
'The initial aim was to cut the number of telexes and telephone calls,' says
Mr Andy Sheldon, who is responsible for supporting Memo users in the UK. 'We
were getting 500 free-format telexes a day from the UK franchisees, for
example, to order emergency parts needed on top of their standard stock
deliveries.
'The franchisees now complete a structured electronic form on their systems
and transmit it via Memo. Staff in the parts department check all orders on
their workstations and can accept, reject, correct or query them, sending
the queries back via electronic mail. All this has cut paper and time.
'Another major time-saving application went live last October. In the past,
if a part received by a dealer was damaged, a lot of paperwork was raised
and it took 15 days to process a claim. We've now introduced an electronic
form here, too. The warehouse people look at a claim on screen and decide on
the appropriate action. There is no paper involved at all.
'This has cut the time to handle damaged parts from 15 days to 1 1/2 days.
There have been staff-savings here: previously there was a significant data
entry function, but now the dealers do it themselves.'
The electronic forms are also used internally. Secretaries fill in weekly
absence reports for their departments through Memo. Staff going on trips
book travel and accommodation by sending an electronic form to the company's
travel agent, which is linked to the system.
The latest application is expected to have a big effect on customer service.
'From February, dealers can get immediate automatic decisions on goodwill
claims,' says Andy Sheldon. 'If a part fails just outside the warranty
period, the dealer can fill in an electronic form; this goes through Memo to
a system on our mainframe which looks up the customer details and various
tables to decide whether the part will be replaced free of charge.
Previously this involved phone calls or faxes: now there's a decision within
five seconds, while the customer is with the dealer.'
Other central applications also have links to the electronic mail system.
When new cars arrive at Harwich from Germany, the vehicle system is informed
and this generates a message to the appropriate dealers.
Mercedes-Benz does not use the bulletin board facility, which can hold
announcements for inspection by any user. Instead, it sends general messages
 -such as reports on stolen cars - to a central electronic mail box which
each dealer has in addition to its individual staff mailboxes.
'All the mailboxes are held on disc on our mainframe and there are about
100,000 messages stored at any time, so if we had the bulletin board we
would save disc space by only holding the general messages once,' Andy
Sheldon says. 'However, that means buying the software, so it's swings and
roundabouts.'
The diary facility is used extensively to arrange meetings and book rooms
and equipment. 'Very few people in my division have diaries,' Mr Sheldon
says.
The UK operation chose Memo because the group uses it as the worldwide
standard. Mercedes-Benz's international data communications network links 15
mainframe computer installations and serves 110,000 Memo users, making the
company Verimation's biggest customer. Most communication in the UK and with
Germany and other countries goes via electronic mail as a matter of course.
'We saved several hundred thousands pounds in the first year by cutting
phone and telex costs,' he adds, 'but we've had electronic mail for so long
now and it's become so ensconced that we don't even really think about the
savings any more.'
Memo electronic mail system
Memo also offers electronic forms, work flow management, bulletin board and
scheduling facilities, some as standard and others as extras. It was
launched in 1984. The latest version, 4.1, was released at the end of 1993.
Supplier: Verimation, formed by Volvo in Sweden in 1984 and in the UK in
1987. Now 25 per cent owned by Volvo and 75 per cent by Swedish software
company Sapia. Volvo owns Memo.
Turnover in 1992 was Pounds 12m. There are five staff in the UK and 280
worldwide.
Number of users: 1.9m at 900 worldwide sites, including 42 in the UK and 420
in the rest of Europe. Memo has 7.5 per cent of the mainframe electronic
mail market in the UK and 8.5 per cent worldwide. It has 4.5 per cent of the
total electronic mail market, world-wide.
Price: Depends on computer. Unlimited licence for an IBM MVS mainframe is
Pounds 34,500.
</TEXT>
