<DOCNO>FT941-4512</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-ECJDQAHWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940310
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1994 - Office Automation
(21): Who said the paperless office was just a dream? / Goodbye to
secretaries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There are two-dozen professional staff at IQ Software in the UK, but no
secretaries - and the company dreams of becoming paperless, too, reports
John Kavanagh.
IQ, which develops and sells information access software aimed especially at
managers and senior executives, bases the entire way it operates on computer
systems.
'We think in terms of automation and productivity, rather than
administration and secretaries,' says UK general manager Mr Geof Gibbons.
'If someone finds they've done the same admin job three times in the last
week, we start thinking of ways to automate it.'
The main office in Winchester and smaller operations in Manchester and
Colchester are supported by two main software packages, supplied through the
parent IQ Software company in the US to all its European subsidiaries. These
are Futurus Team Combo, an office automation product from Futurus, and Sales
Control from Sales and Marketing.
The UK company also has Sunaccounts from Systems Union, Microsoft Word for
word processing, Lotus 1-2-3 for spreadsheets and its own products for
management information access. The systems run on a Novell office network
supporting relatively cheap IBM-type personal computers, generally chosen on
price.
'We have an almost paperless office,' Geof Gibbons says. 'We run sales
control like a groupware system for everyone in the company. The marketing
people enter details of sales leads and allocate them to salesmen.
'A salesman phones and then gets the system to produce a standard follow-up
letter. The system records that the letter has been sent. The salesman can
ask the system to remind him to chase up the lead so many days later. He
might arrange a demonstration and generate another letter. The system again
records this fact but we don't keep paper copies in a file or anything silly
like that.
'The salesman will use the Futurus Team electronic mail system to get the
support people to check that product trials are going well. The support
people log their activity in the system. When the lead turns into a
customer, the accounts people are notified through the system and create
accounts records in Sunaccounts.'
The result is that all activities relating to a customer are logged
paperless on the system. In addition, all activities use - or are sparked
off by - information which is handled and recorded once only, he says.
'Sales people know which information and prices they've given. The support
team know of any problems and what was done about them. Marketing can check
the progress of a prospect. Training consultants know the amount of training
to be done.
'We also key-in summaries of any correspondence from customers, so that's
available on the system, too.'
The Futurus Team electronic mail facility is a natural part of every-day
life at IQ Software and is regarded as more productive than the telephone.
While we speak, Mr Gibbons keys in a question he cannot answer and sends it
to a technical specialist; the answer comes back towards the end of our
conversation.
'E-mail is the simplest way of communicating between people here in
Winchester, in the remote offices and at the US head office,' he says. 'You
don't tie-up valuable time in phone calls. Written messages tend to be more
succinct and thoughtful, because you've got to key them in. And you can add
to them and send them to any number of appropriate people at the same time.
We don't use a discussion database like Lotus Notes: instead we build a
dialogue from an initial e-mail message.
'For example, I might broadcast a question about a customer, a salesman
might add a comment about what he has done and say he's waiting for the
support team to do something and then the support person might add his
comment. This also gives us a log of the entire conversation.
'We do e-mail to some customers, via the public Compuserve network service.
This hasn't been taken up as much as we'd like by customers. There still
seems to be a lot of psychological barriers: even people who are well used
to using PCs prefer to talk on the phone. Even in our company, with all our
office automation, there's one guy who sends little paper notes in response
to e-mail messages. Fortunately, he's the only one.'
A separate simple electronic mail system in Futurus Team is used to pass on
telephone messages. Anyone answering the telephone for someone who is out
types a message into this system, so there are no scribbled notes on
people's desks. Geof Gibbons says this does not put staff off taking other
people's calls: in this company, communications and information technology
are a natural part of the way everyone works. IQ Software has looked at
voicemail systems, which record spoken messages, but feels they are still
too expensive for its needs.
Another electronic mail system enables people to communicate directly and
immediately on urgent matters. A user can send a message through a PC to a
colleague, who is notified by an audible beep and can key in a reply.
IQ Software finds this especially useful if someone takes a query on the
telephone and the person who knows the answer is also engaged: the two
colleagues can hold a conversation through their PCs while talking to
outsiders on the telephone.
Futurus Team's bulletin board facility is used by the US headquarters to
send product and other information over night. At the US end, the system
checks for any product documents which have been changed since the previous
day's connection and sends those across.
In Winchester, this facility is also used to keep track of training course
bookings and to maintain certain other information such as staff names and
addresses.
A diary system is also part of Futurus Team and is used to arrange meetings
and book resources such as a meeting room and a projector. If one person
arranges a meeting, the system notifies the others via electronic mail.
IQ Software has taken various measures to ensure that while information
technol ogy is fundamental to the way the company works it is not also an
Achilles' heel.
'All the discs are mirrored, so all data is written to two disc drives at
the same time,' says the company's support manager, Mr Neil Hutton, who also
looks after the internal systems.
'Everything is archived to tape every night. We have uninterruptible power
supplies in case of mains electricity problems.
'One benefit of using a Novell network is that any machine attached to it
can be the file server, so if the usual file processor goes down, we can
move the discs to another machine.
'We use standard 486 PCs, not quite the state of the art but perfectly
adequate for our needs.'
Geof Gibbons underlines the importance of having the systems constantly
available - 'we've been fully automated from day one and never had a
secretary. We started on a single machine and when there were two of us, we
bought another and got a network.
'The systems have absolutely proved themselves in terms of the productivity
of our people,' he concludes. 'We just couldn't work without our systems
now. It's as simple as that.'
Futurus Team Combo
This product is a work group or groupware system including electronic mail,
a bulletin board or conference facility, a diary and scheduling facility,
conversations via PCs, a simple database and a fax send-and-receive
facility.
Supplier: Futurus was formed in Atlanta, Georgia, in 1987 to develop the
Team system.
Number of users: various versions of Team are installed on 500,000 shared
processors world-wide, including 1,200 in the UK. Market research firm
International Data Corporation gave it 16 per cent of the groupware market
in 1992.
Price: Pounds 385 for five users, Pounds 3,120 for 50 users. There are
distributors in 40 countries. Futurus is ending its current UK distribution
arrangements and talking to other suppliers.
Hardware and operating systems: IBM-type personal computers running DOS or
DOS with Windows.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
