<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1994 - Office Automation
(18): Lotus notes
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This product is a work group or groupware system launched in 1990 and now on
version 3.0, released in 1993. The system is based on a document database
which allows team members to share documents and add comments. Other
facilities, some of which are illustrated in the Lawson Mardon and Unipart
case studies, range from work flow automation to setting reminder alarms for
forthcoming tasks or events.
Some companies have used Notes in unexpected ways to develop business
systems such as accounting. Other software companies are developing products
to offer add-on facilities.
Supplier: Lotus Development, formed in the US in 1982 and in the UK in 1983.
The company leapt to stardom with the 1-2-3 spreadsheet package. Turnover in
1993 was up nine per cent to Dollars 981.2m. Net profit was Dollars 75.4m,
compared with Dollars 57.2m in 1992, when there were acquisition and
restructuring costs. Lotus has 4,200 staff world-wide.
Number of users: Notes is used by more than 750,000 people in 3,200
companies world-wide and is clear leader in an ill-defined market.
Price: Pounds 375 for one user, Pounds 3,715 for 10 users, then discounts
increase. Sales and support: direct or through dealers or systems companies
(value-added resellers).
Hardware and operating systems: IBM-type personal computers running Windows
or OS/2, plus Apple Macintosh computers.
