<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1994 - Office Automation
(19): Experience is more valuable than documentation - Consultant's Critique
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN GRUMBALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The information that people write down tends to be that which is easy to
structure. It is often obvious. Anyone who has tried to write a procedures
manual for any job soon finds that it is easy to describe which forms are
filled in but much harder to describe how to acquire the information to do
so.
Lawson Mardon's use of Lotus Notes has the ability to capture experience.
The conversations that occur on the system provide a knowledge base that
would be hard to obtain in any other way.
Anyone joining the company can read how other people have handled particular
cases. In addition, they can pick the brains of more experienced staff
without having to interrupt them. The effect of interruptions on work flow
should not be under-estimated.
This unstructured collection of experiences can be periodically edited and
organised. It is usually essential to do so to save staff the effort of
trawling through the originals.
In many electronic mail systems, there is a frequently-asked questions file.
This encapsulates replies to the most common queries and forms a useful
starting point for any newcomer.
Another benefit from the system is the audit trail that Lotus Notes
provides. It tracks all the transactions including errors and subsequent
corrections. This forms an invaluable basis for quality programmes and
possible BS5750 certification.
I was pleased to see the mix of technologies used. Far too many systems
expect clerks to become database programmers.
While a database language carries power, it also requires different
disciplines from those in common use. The use of forms via Lotus Notes gives
users a metaphor they are familiar with.
Lessons from this study are:
There are enormous benefits in capturing experience and making it available
to newcomers.
Electronic mail messages become a valuable audit trail.
Most people are not programmers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P737  Computer and Data Processing Services.
    P357  Computer and Office Equipment.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
