<PROFILE>_AN-ECJDQAHRFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940310
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1994 - Business Briefing
(15): The groupware revolution - Era of the 'empowered team' - Groupware
could redeem the broken promises of 1980s office automation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ten years ago we were being promised the prospect of a paperless office. So
much for that: 10 years later various survey reports (supplied on paper)
show that 10,000 filing cabinets are delivered to UK offices every day, only
five per cent of business documents are held on computers and that people
spend four to six weeks a year looking for the other 95 per cent. Spending
on office automation increased seven-fold between 1980 and 1990, yet office
productivity rose by a meagre one per cent.
Enter groupware, an ill-defined set of software packages which will
nonetheless generate a market worth Dollars 2.5bn in products, consultancy
and training in Europe and the US this year, according to a 300-page report
on this market by research firm Ovum.
Groupware has evolved from electronic mail and from the 1980s attempts at
office automation to support office workers at all levels. Whereas early
office automation focused on word processing, groupware aims to help people
work together through communication with each other and through access to
shared information, whether they are processing invoices, involved in a
major engineering project or discussing corporate strategy.
Several related types of products have been identified as lining up under
the groupware banner. Communication with or through a shared system, for
example electronic mail, is fundamental to all applications. As the Ovum
report puts it: 'E-mail is the mother of groupware.'
The automatic storage and retrieval of document images by any number of
people at the same time is a desirable part of many applications: incoming
correspondence, forms, drawings and other documents which cannot be keyed in
through word processor systems are scanned in to be held on disc and called
to a screen in seconds rather than hunted down in a filing cabinet or on
someone's desk.
Work flow management software, a late 1980s development of document image
processing, usually refers to systems which manage document handling tasks
carried out by clerical staff. Case studies in this issue of Software At
Work show how work flow management can transform the way whole departments
work, bringing big increases in efficiency and making work more interesting.
Features variously described as information sharing, electronic conferencing
and task management also fall under the groupware heading. At the simplest
level there are bulletin board systems, which allow users to leave comments
and queries for inspection and response by others.
A development of this is the production of a document such as a corporate
strategy, possibly controlled by one or two people, to which others can add
their comments. Our Unipart case study (see page 14) shows how this can be
taken even further to become a key part in the management of big projects.
Other software in the broad category of groupware includes specialist
products such as shared diaries and meetings schedulers.
The Software At Work case studies reveal almost unbounded enthusiasm for
groupware among users who in some cases are pushing such products to their
limits, running widely differing applications from the same product.
Software packages starting at less than Pounds 400 are forming the basis for
the entire way some companies are organised and work.
'The enthusiasts are fervently committed to the idea that groupware offers
an entirely new and even revolutionary approach to IT support for
white-collar work,' says Ms Rose Lockwood, senior consultant at Ovum. 'At
the other extreme, sceptics believe groupware is little more than a
marketing strategy for a motley collection of products which are being
repositioned by software vendors.' But she adds, 'We believe the enthusiasts
are nearer the mark.'
The research firm, Business Intelligence, which is also producing a hefty
report on introducing and using groupware, says the combination of products
covers the four main tasks that people perform in offices: finding
information, using information, communicating with others and attending
meetings. Groupware in the form of e-mail and conferencing eliminates the
frustration and time wasting of trying to contact someone by telephone when
the person is out or not answering or engaged. Document image processing,
work flow management and conferencing enable people to discuss issues when
convenient to them individually and without attending meetings. As our case
studies show, groupware can cut the number of meetings and make those which
are actually held more productive. Communications and access to documents
improve the ability to use information. As Business Intelligence director Mr
Ian Meiklejohn puts it: 'Stand-alone PCs provide useful tools such as
spreadsheets and word processing packages, but a significant amount of
management work involves input from several sources. The ability to share
the document and work with it in a team is a considerable benefit over the
benefits delivered by stand-alone PCs.'
There are great hopes that while the office automation systems of the early
1980s failed to live up to their full promise, suppliers and users will get
it right with groupware. This confidence stems from two developments. First,
the technology is now relatively cheap, offers good performance and is
widely used by people of all levels. Personal computer systems are quite
attractive to users these days and high-capacity communications through the
emerging ISDN digital services means pictures, voice and video can be
transmitted from one screen to another.
Indeed, Mr John Williams, UK work flow marketing manager at Digital
Equipment, believes that 'there is probably enough technology on our desks
already to support everything we want to do.'
Ian Meiklejohn at Business Intelligence backs this view by pointing to
surveys which show that more personal computers will be attached to networks
this year than were installed in 1989. Research firm IDC says the number of
electronic mailboxes on public systems will grow from 4.9m in 1991 to a
massive 38m in 1996.
The conclusion is that many individual users are ready for groupware, both
psychologically and technically.
The second reason for the confidence in groupware is that it fits in with
the way businesses are re-organising themselves - 'it is clear that the
empowered team is becoming a much more important part of the corporation,'
says Ian Meiklejohn. He defines an empowered team as one which has the
authority to make decisions to achieve a given task - 'if empowered teams
are to work effectively they must have much better tools for sharing and
using information,' he says. 'Groupware provides that set of tools.'
This issue leads to a note of caution from Mr Meiklejohn and others -
'groupware could fail to deliver productivity improvements unless it is
accompanied by a critical approach to business re-engineering,' he adds.
'It's not that groupware makes business re-engineering possible, although it
certainly helps, but rather that unless business processes are rethought,
groupware may deliver no more than mini- and mainframe-based office
automation has done in the past.'
Rose Lockwood at Ovum agrees and adds that any expansion of local area
networks should now be done with groupware in mind: 'Many users have
implemented groupware in an ad hoc way, leaving most decisions about what
systems are developed and how they are administered up to end-users. This is
dangerous and likely to lead to the same kind of dysfunctions that have
dogged the desk-top world for a decade.'
The Ovum report, Groupware: Market Strategies: details on 071-255 2670.
Business Intelligence, producing The Groupware Report, is on 081-544 1830.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    XGZ  Europe.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7372 Prepackaged Software.
    P737  Computer and Data Processing Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MKTS  Market data.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XII
</PAGE>
