<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1994 - Financial Control
Systems (14): A global view of finance - Consolidation in financial services
/ Information on financial market changes is Knight-Ridder's main commodity,
but fluctuation was less welcome in-house, when it came to consolidating
international accounts. A multi-dimensional spreadsheet was the answer
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
For Allan Richardson, chief financial officer at Knight-Ridder
Financial/Europe, based in London's Fleet Street, the problem of controlling
five finance departments across the continent held few fears. He had already
dealt with the same issues in previous posts in multinational organisations,
and had clear ideas of what was needed.
'What you really want is something like a spreadsheet, which allows
accountants to look at what they want, wherever it is held, and in whatever
format suits them,' he says.
Knight-Ridder Europe is part of the Dollars 2.3bn US-owned multinational,
provider of financial information and services to the European commodities
and financial services market. Its own product is information: news,
reports, and analysis of foreign exchange fluctuations, and international
commodities pricing.
However, the mechanisms Knight-Ridder had in place to handle its own
financial reporting were, in Richardson's view, too reliant on spreadsheets.
These involved the writing of macros, (inbuilt programs written to suit
specific needs), frequent re-keying of data, and unwieldy models which made
global budgeting in particular very clumsy.
Mr Richardson's main objection to spreadsheets as a tool for control is that
the data is tied to the specific spreadsheet structure - 'if you change one,
you change the other. What we want is to change the spreadsheet without
affecting the underlying data,' he says.
No spreadsheet assessed by Knight-Ridder, including Excel and Lotus 123,
could get round this problem. Lotus Improv was a single-user,
single-currency tool, not sophisticated enough for Knight-Ridder's purposes.
Extracting data from the mainframe to a PC was too cumbersome, and didn't
meet the demand for dynamic data. The data had to be live, and real, not a
'frozen copy' of centrally-held information. This requirement led to an
evaluation of various executive information systems (EIS), including EPS,
Comshare, Express and Essbase.
The company decided that it needed a multi-user client-server system, which
would provide easy access through a graphical user interface, and access (by
name, such as 'sales') to any available data item. The eventual choice,
based on its ability to handle changes efficiently, was Essbase, running on
an HP3000 mainframe supporting a Novell network of 486 and 386 PCs. The
entire installation, excluding an 'extra,' the currency conversion package,
was around Pounds 40,000.
Essbase, from Arbor software, is described variously as a a
multi-dimensional analysis tool, a decision-support system, executive
information system, and spreadsheet. Its attraction was that it could be
addressed by end users through the familiar medium of their Lotus or
Microsoft spreadsheets.
'What Essbase does is to download transactional data, from invoicing,
general ledger or any other source and mix it with other data,' he says. 'It
allows me to first define the structure, then define the report and cut and
dice the data any way we wish to see it. Forecasting is a different job
again, but with this, rather than creating a new set of figures, we can have
actual, budget, and forecast: rather like playing 3D chess.'
Multi-dimensional analysis provides a familiar spreadsheet 'look and feel,'
to Knight-Ridder's 40 or so users across Europe, but is far more flexible
than spreadsheet modelling. This flexibility allows Richardson to extract
data to a level of detail that once would have demanded custom-built Cobol
programs.
He can examine the sales performance of a particular country, mapped against
target, allocate direct costs, and tell which products are making what
profit. All tailoring is being done in-house - 'you need one person who is
PC-literate and who understands accounting,' says Mr Richardson.
The main benefits have been timely information in a manageable format, using
dynamic data - 'rather than spending time writing macros, and putting data
in, it frees people's time to ask questions and look at what is actually
happening,' he comments. 'Interpretation becomes the key: it makes the job
more interesting.
Arbor Essbase
This product, the Essbase Multi-dimensional Analysis System, version 3, was
launched in October 1993. It enables workgroups of financial managers,
business analysts and product managers to simultaneously access and analyse
large amounts of corporate data consolidated from spreadsheets, relational
databases and legacy systems in a client-server environment.
Large users include Shell; Avis Europe; Prudential; and Guinness.
Supplier: Arbor Software Corp, based in Santa Clara, US, was founded in
1991, with a UK office founded in 1993.
Number of users: 80 customers worldwide, including multiple sites.
Price: in the region of Pounds 25,000 for five-user client/server system.
Sold direct and through VAR/consultants. Services available include:
training and consultancy to corporate end-users.
Hardware and operating systems: any server running Windows NT or OS/2.
Client machines can include PCs, Macs, running Windows 3.1 or Macintosh
System 7.
User views include: 'Fast, flexible, easy user-interface, good
locking/security features, familiar Lotus/Excel paradigm makes for a rapid
learning curve, easy to create structure, in-house maintenance. Rapid
response from supplier to requested enhancements. Ideal for 'information
hoarders.' '
Other views: 'Unforgiving to initial mistakes made in creating structure.'
Contacts: Nigel Geary, Arbor Software (UK), Atrium Court, Apex Plaza,
Reading, RG1 1AX, Tel 0743 566 749.
In the US: 0101 408 727 7166
Claire Gooding
</TEXT>
