<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1994 - Financial Control
Sytems (11): Window on the world - Integrated accounting in manufacturing /
For Henkel, the manufacturing group, linking existing 'islands of
automation' to create an integrated view brought the benefits of the new,
without losing the familiarity of old tools
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
One problem facing Henkel, the chemicals, cosmetics and household products
group, was a good one to have: that of integrating its operations as the
group expanded.
Brand names such as Aapri, Silkience and Pritt sticks are probably more
familiar names than that of their manufacturer, Henkel. But the German-based
group is large - Dollars 8bn turnover and 140 production units - with
interests in domestic and industrial chemical products, DIY products,
including wallpaper.
In the UK, finance director Norbert Frank explains the problem: 'Different
people need to look at different things: margins achieved within a period,
manufacturing performance, yield, wastage, and so on. We had many
applications on our System 38 - all good 'island' solutions, but not
integrated.'
He wanted closer financial control, with financial systems that would link
with sales and distribution, manufacturing, production planning, and human
resources. (See 'enterprise' in buzzwords, page 4).
A complete upgrade left the coast clear for new hardware - AS400 or a Unix
computer - and a fresh start, with GUI (graphical user interface) and
Windows.
Mr Frank was convinced that he had found a state-of-the art offering in the
new R3 package from SAP, whose mainframe accounting solution R/2 had long
been in use in the German parent company.
'It combines the Windows world with the applications software,' says Mr
Frank, 'and I have not seen any other package that does that.'
The main attraction of R3 was the ease of use, and its executive information
system or EIS-like facilities.
'The benefits are the transparency and accessibility of financial data. We
can now 'drill down,' looking at an individual account balance and then
right down to a single transaction or document, but at the same time, access
is easy at the highest level, using 'drop down' windows,' he says.
Another benefit was that users did not have to abandon their Excel
spreadsheets. Users can simply choose Excel from within R/3.
Henkel has been treated very much as a pilot site for R3 in the UK. The
implementation uses a Hewlett-Packard 9890 database server and 9730
computers in a client/server configuration with PCs, and will eventually
support 250 users in the UK alone.
Mr Frank's 'anchor group' has forged a configuration that is likely to be
adopted elsewhere in the Henkel group, in the Asia Pacific operations. The
first part of the project went live in April 1993, after a six-month period
in which SAP provided a full consultancy service. This accounted for around
Pounds 500,000 worth of the Pounds 2.5 project total, with a Pounds 1m
expenditure on software, and Pounds 1m on hardware.
According to Mr Frank it has been a revelation, exciting even, to emerge
from a more limited world into an 'Open' system that can expand with the
company.
'It is not just a matter of turning on the the screen and making a better
decision. We are growing by acquisition at the rate of one a year, and now
we can easily integrate any acquired business on a Unix platform.
'Now, people are all using the same data at different levels of the
hierarchy. Decisions will be made on this data as we build up an executive
information system, which will work at different levels for users in
different areas.'
Software: SAP R/3
Product: R/3 is an integrated suite of client/server-base applications
software that covers the the entire scope of business operations, from
accounting and financial management, to manufacturing, logistics and human
resources management.
Supplier: SAP UK is a wholly owned subsidiary of SAP AG, the world's seventh
largest software company, which is publicly quoted in Germany. SAP was
founded in 1972 in Germany, and SAP UK was established in 1988. Turnover: DM
707.1m 1992, with DM123.3m profit, DM831.2m in 1991, with 127.2m profit. UK
turnover rose from Pounds 3.8m in 1991 to Pounds 6.9m in 1992; the company
has 50 employees in the UK.
Number of users: 1,000 sites worldwide for R/3.
Price: from Pounds 80,000 for a 32-user system for financial accounting.
Sales and support/maintenance is direct and through consultancy partners.
Maintenance charge for R/3 is 15 per cent of the software price. Other
services available: pre- and post-sales support, technical and applications
consultancy, education and training, online help and 'Early Watch' remote
diagnostic service.
Hardware and operating systems: wide range of Open Systems client/server
platforms including Bull, Digital, HP, IBM, SNI, Sun and Sequent.
User views include: 'Easy-to-use, responsive support, 'intuitive' graphical
user interface.' Other view: 'Complex,' (this can be an advantage); highly
priced for top-of-range hardware platforms.'
UK contact: Trevor Saloman, SAP on tel 081 893 2893.
</TEXT>
