<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1994 - Financial Control
Systems (6): European perspective - EIS case study: Electronics supplier /
The size of Philips Consumer Electronics made it difficult to get an
overview that allowed managers to compare and co-ordinate operations, until
an EIS was implemented
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Picking a supplier who would be around in the long term was vital to Philips
Consumer Electronics - and so was international support. As one of Philips'
five leading product divisions with a Pounds 6bn turnover of its own, PCE
needed to overhaul its information systems in line with its European
reporting structure.
The aim was to provide a co-ordinated approach, with some local autonomy.
'The main issue was gathering information across diverse groups and
presenting it to managers so that they can make effective decisions,' says
Royston Morgan, information manager at PCE.
Problems in co-ordination were first pointed out by the colour TV business
group, which wanted to compare factory with factory using the same
yardstick. The ability to analyse differences called for an EIS, and four or
five were assessed. Pilot's Command Centre and Lightship Professional
software satisfied Morgan's demand for a product that would provide
co-ordination across Europe.
'Any application had to fit in with our infrastructure and support our
business aims, allowing us to co-ordinate centrally from the headquarters in
Eindhoven,' he says.
There are now 200 regular users of the system, and 350 or so approved users,
largely in the layers of management below director-level. Mr Morgan sees
direct bottom-line benefits after 18 months, particularly in sales and
marketing areas, but remarks that the main effort has to go into business
thinking, not programming.
'It's not a question of who can program it, but of who can understand the
business, and translate those needs into an application,' he says. 'The
analysts must understand the business in general, and be able to translate
the business needs of others.'
Software details:
Pilot Lightship
This product is a centralised client/server reporting environment. LightShip
Professional is a Windows-based graphical user interface that can access and
present data from multiple sources and formats.
Supplier: Pilot Software was founded in 1984 in the US, founding a UK
operation in 1991. It is a privately held company. Turnover: Dollars 50m in
1992; Pounds 5.1m in UK.
Number of users: 17,000 sites with 50,000 users.
Price: varies according to modules; eg Lightship Professional starts at
Pounds 37,000 for 100 users and three developers. Lightship Lens starts at
10,000 for 100 users, Lightship Link Pounds 6,250 for 25 users. User views:
'Flexibility, quick build of modules, powerful graphics presentation, tools
for projection and forecasting,' but support and documentation 'could be
improved' in some localities.
Contact: David Carey-Jones, Pilot Software, tel 0932 569944
</TEXT>
