<PROFILE>_AN-ECJDQAHFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940310
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1994 - Financial Control
Systems (3): From EIS to OLAP - Buzzwords
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
An EIS, or executive information system, was originally conceived as a
screen-based information service geared specifically to top executives, with
easy-to-use, ready-packaged information which would provide a complete
picture of the organisation. 'Drill down' provides detail on components,
also in graphical form. 'Traffic lighting' is a technique to aid analysis,
particularly of danger-zones or by pre-determined norms or limits for
situations.
Some now interpret the acronym as 'enterprise intelligence service' as EIS
proves useful to managers further down the chain. The system sources include
information drawn from internal computer and paper-based systems. It might
also include external services, such as on-line share prices: this was once
thought of as a primary executive function, but has proved to be a
little-used option for most EIS-users. Increasingly, EIS applications are
merging with their forebears: decision support systems (DSS) and management
information systems (MIS).
The latest buzzword to describe this development is OLAP - on-line
analytical processing. This describes a multi-dimensional approach which
allows the user to draw data together from different sources and view it as
a 'cube,' which can be turned in any direction, to report on any dimension
or set of dimensions such as time periods, sales regions or product.
'Legacy' is the term used to describe inherited, working systems, often
mainframe-based. Although often used in a pejorative sense (because of the
expense of maintainance as systems age), a legacy is often valuable, and can
consist of core applications. It is not always desirable or practical to
upgrade such systems. The alternative is 'downsizing': that is moving the
applications on to a smaller computer, often a 'client-server' system of
workstations capable of working independently, but linked through a central
'server' computer for sharing of applications and data. Where legacy systems
cannot be abandoned, 'interoperability' is an option. This is often used
where there are multiple operating systems in one installation, and is eased
by using software written to be transportable ('ported') between different
operating environments. Where this is not possible, 'feeder' systems can be
especially written to give data a route between, for example, a spreadsheet
and a consolidation system.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P737  Computer and Data Processing Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
