<PROFILE>_AN-ECJDQAHDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940310
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Survey of Software at Work, Spring 1994 - Financial Control
Systems (2): All singing from the same sheet / Business briefing - The
information you need is probably in the computer system somewhere. But how
can you get at it? Claire Gooding looks at some of the ways companies are
bringing information into line for better financial control
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Most computer users know that having too much information is as difficult as
not having enough. The problem is one of delivering it accurately, to the
right person, in a comprehensible format, at the point when and where it is
needed. If the first hour of any meeting is spent arguing about whose
figures are right, you probably have too many systems, and none of them
quite right.
There have been successive waves of software development: accounting
systems, management information systems, executive information systems, all
promising to be the answer to financial control. Nevertheless, companies
still have cash-flow problems, managers still wade through paper-overload,
and still re-key data from paper reports or from one computer to another
'Computer systems, and particularly the financial systems, hold vast amounts
of data. But is seems that the packages currently available make it quite
difficult to interpret and analyse the data for accounting, modelling, cash
flow control,' says John Tate, director of the London-based Tate Bramald
consultancy that researches and tracks financial software.
In 1993, Tate Bramald had more than 1,000 replies to questionnaires sent out
to all members of the Chartered Institute of Certified Accountants, asking
what they would like most to change in existing software. Reporting
facilities came top in the firing line.
Mr Tate adds: 'Typically, a computer system will hold most if not all the
key information a company needs to meet legal requirements for historic
reporting. So it's easy to see what has happened, but it's difficult if in
fact it has failed to help them manage their business today and in the
future.'
He gives cash flow forecasting as an example. Packages contain up-to-date
data on how much customers owe and suppliers are owed. Records show how
promptly they have paid or been paid, but most systems fail to pull this
together.
'An aged debtors report will give you a lovely report on when the the money
is due - theoretically,' says John Tate, 'but it won't tell you about
customers' payment habits, and how likely you are to get that cash on time.
Also, it won't combine it with similar information in the purchase ledger.
It all needs to be brought together to do a useful cash-flow.'
There is evidence to suggest that many failing companies are actually
profitable, or could be, if they had better financial control. In a cautious
recovery from recession, running out of cash through over-trading is a
constant danger. One bankruptcy can bring swathes of others in its wake: the
problems of being a small creditor of a large, slow-paying organisation, are
well-documented.
Trading in the 1990s is made even more difficult by the speed of change.
Speed of response is essential as 'Just-In-Time' manufacturing techniques
push the responsibilities for supply and demand further down the line.
Companies change hands: alliances are made and broken, as illustrated by the
recent takeover of the Rover Group by BMW, and Honda's impending divorce
from Rover.
Changing circumstances can trigger off a need for new views of existing
data. For example, the effect of the Monopolies and Mergers Commission on
the brewing industry has been profound. It brought about a need for all
sorts of information that had never before been required: new information
technology mechanisms had to be swiftly put in place. Similarly, a sudden
change in European Union regulations about importing bananas has brought new
challenges for Geest, the fruit importers, (see case study, page 8).
Increasing 'globalisation' of business means that conducting business across
national borders bring further demands on information delivery. National
accounting regulations are complex enough. International consolidations are
akin to playing three-dimensional chess through a mirror.
All of this takes place at a time when computing has never been more
'personal.' The biggest investment takes place not in hardware or software
but in people and their expertise. Managers who become used to using
particular tools are loth to give them up in favour of anything new, however
'whizz-bang' they appear.
People like what they know. This was one of the constant themes from users
interviewed for this issue of Software At Work. Instead of identifying a
single market sector and looking at a range of similar applications, (such
as computer-aided design or accounting packages for PCs), the broad topic of
financial control called for a different approach.
The aim was to find out what different sorts of software packages are
available, and how adaptable they are in providing financial control.
Interviewees ranged from those concerned with the quality of the 'raw
ingredients' of financial control - such as timesheet and estimating
systems, and even asset management - to those performing international
consolidations. In between came executive information systems, and
accounting systems with EIS-like extensions.
Several of the most common grumbles were familiar IT bugbears. Agreeing on
the accuracy of data is still a problem. So is re-keying of data from one
system to another. Viewing information from different angles is a common
requirement, as is the need to work in multiple dimensions and currencies.
The inflexibility of reporting tools is exactly what has led to the
development of top-level presentation and analysis software known as
'executive information systems.' These combine sophisticated analysis with
intuitive ease of use, with features such as 'drill down,' which allow the
user to track down the sources of a high-level figure.
There is often a time-lag between the introduction of such tools in to a
company, and their actual use. In fact, the main effort in implementing an
EIS can come in the analysis phase beforehand, when people are forced to
look at what information and systems they already have, and how, why, and
where the information flows.
Large organisations with in-house skills are typically turning to management
information (MIS) or EIS systems and developing their own reporting
structures, feeding from disparate databases or spreadsheets. A similar
shift is taking place with accounting systems. Companies such as Great
Plains, Platinum, and Systems Union are opening up file structures, and
making them available to query languages (such as SQL) and reporting
products such as Forest and Trees.
Standard front-ends and complementary coupling with other packages seem to
be the way forward. IMRS' latest release of its Hyperion financial
management software features the Standard Query Language, SQL. Many popular
packages allow users to cling to familiar rafts, such as the spreadsheets
Lotus 1-2-3 and Microsoft Excel. Their great advantage, as users confirm, is
that everyone else uses them: a lingua franca of finance. This is useful in
a world where a company runs a number of operating systems, OS, (Tate
Bramald's survey found only a quarter of installations ran only one OS,
whereas more than 30 per cent ran four or more OSs). Even so, a spreadsheet
has its limitations in two dimensional modelling, and data presentation.
PA Consulting's senior consultant Keith Robertson takes a dim view of
financial managers who are hooked on pretty graphics, and rely on standalone
PC systems to deliver them. But he believes that, while the recession slowed
technology's progress, the surviving products are of improved quality.
This brings its own dangers: business managers who become experts in their
own local software solutions, but lose their focus in their fascination with
information technology - 'conversations in sports clubs these days often
revolve around what facilities particular packages offer,' he adds. 'A
business needs to ensure it pays key staff to provide business skills,
rather than falling into the trap of becoming a workshop where staff
exchange ideas on new IT products and features.
'Nowhere is this more important than in the area of financial control, where
the bottom line has real monetary value, rather than merely being
represented by a series of various-size graphics of Big Ben in different
shades of green.'
For more details: Tate Bramald survey of CICA users, 1993: tel. 081-332 2417
The CMG consultancy recently discovered some scepticism among potential
users of executive information systems, EIS. In a survey undertaken jointly
with the supplier of information systems SAS Institute, CMG interviewed over
240 executives in the mortgage-lending industry. Fewer than 20 per cent of
building societies use EIS, and many had failed in their first attempt. Over
half used internal development tools. According to senior consultant Bob
Frost, 'there are very few true EIS systems around at present. Many which
purport to be EIS are merely graphical presentations of existing
information. Over the next five years we foresee a convergence of an
organisation's information delivery systems.'
Details: CMG EIS Survey; tel 071 976 0066.
</TEXT>
