<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / London Stock Exchange: Bond markets continue to upset share
prices - Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Favourable news on dividends and profits proved insufficient yesterday to
protect the UK stock market against another slide in US and German bond
prices towards the end of the session. With British government stocks also
turning off, the market slipped back sharply in the late afternoon to close
with a fall of 17.7 on the FT-SE 100 Index for a final reading of 3,246.7.
Equities opened firmly, encouraged by the absence of the rights issue
threatened by rumour mongers at the close of the previous session. Several
trading programmes, apparently weighed towards the buy side, also helped to
put 6 points on the Footsie within the first half-hour of official trading.
But then, as so often happens, stock index futures took a hand and London
could make no further headway.
The modest reduction in German money market rates at the Bundesbank repo
tender, while favourable to interest rate hopes, appeared to indicate that
rates in Germany will come down very slowly.
Hopes of a further reduction in UK base rates were fostered by continued
firmness in sterling, although market strategists showed no sign of changing
their view that the next rate cut will be held back until next month, when
UK consumers will be hit by higher tax and social security charges.
The flat rejection of rights issue rumours by BAT Industries was accompanied
by excellent profits and dividend news. The stock market, with interest
excitement now subsiding, is turning its attention to dividend growth
prospects, both in terms of yield comparisons between equities and bonds,
and also as an underpinning of optimism on corporate earnings.
RTZ, the base metals group, also increased the dividend payout, and several
other leading stocks responded to good profits statements. British Land
eased after announcing a Pounds 150m Eurobond issue, helping to take the
steam out of fears that the stock market is threatened by a large
fund-raising from a big name.
Until late afternoon the Footsie held fairly steady, with the loss held to
around 4 points. It was the slip in German bonds, and then in US bonds,
accompanied by a 16-point fall in the Dow Average in early trade in New
York, which proved the undoing of London stocks.
Seaq volume increased to 730.2m shares, from 676.2m on Tuesday when retail
business reached a substantial worth of Pounds 1.69bn. The FT-SE Mid 250
Index dipped by 10.1 to 3,913. But there was no sign of a bearish turn in
the market. Legal &amp; General, one of Britain's leading life and general
insurance groups, disclosed yesterday that it expects the bull market in UK
equities to continue 'well into 1995' and that, given 'the current outlook
of strong earnings growth', it expects to stay overweight in UK stocks for
the medium term.
The FT-SE Actuaries UK Indices Committee yesterday approved the following
constituent changes. In the FT-SE 100 Index: inclusions - De la Rue, Tarmac
and NFC; exclusions - Schroders, Scottish-Hydro Electric and Anglian Water.
In the FT-SE Mid 250 and Actuaries 350: inclusions - Telegraph, Mercury
World Mining, Kleinwort, EP Investment Trust, Flextech, Berisford Int,
Burford Hldgs and AMEC; exclusions - Geest, Ashley (Laura) Hldgs, Amstrad,
Greene King, Henderson Admin Grp, Life Sciences Int and JIB Group.
</TEXT>
