<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The retreat in US and German bonds continued to exact a toll on stock index
futures, leaving the near month contract in the doldrums after early
attempts at a rally, writes Joel Kibazo.
There was a firm start to trading in the March contract on the FT-SE 100
after it opened at 3,255. But having touched 3,262, demand for the contract
petered out.
Independent traders took the lead in selling and the contract surrendered
the early gain, drifting lower over the next few hours in subdued trade.
Dealers kept an eye on bond markets and the first signs of a slide in German
and US bonds brought active selling of March. It ended at 3,237, down 12
from its previous close and about 3 points below its fair value premium of
minus 8. Volume at the official close was 13,328 lots, and good activity in
the June contract brought turnover of 2,818.
In the FT-SE Mid 250 Index on the Liffe, turnover was 351 lots as it closed
at 3,917. On the OMLX, volume in the same contract rose to 60 lots. It ended
at 3,913.
Liffe traded options had a quiet session, with volume falling to 30,633. The
FT-SE 100 option traded 12,964, while Ladbroke was the busiest stock option
with a total of 2,331 deals, followed by Argyll at 1,875 and Land Securities
at 1,818.
</TEXT>
