<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Markets Report: Repo cut boosts D-Mark
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The D-Mark firmed across the board yesterday as the cautious lowering of
German interest rates lent support to the currency, writes Philip Gawith.
The German currency rose because the market had expected a more generous cut
in the repo rate than the three basis points - to 5.94 per cent - that the
Bundesbank allowed.
The rate move, which was followed by a Belgian rate reduction, confirmed the
downward trend of European interest rates, but underlined the cautious
approach being taken by the Bundesbank.
The US Federal Reserve's 'beige book', released yesterday afternoon,
reported little sign of rising prices and had minimal effect on the dollar.
The US currency was stronger against the yen on indications that progress
was being made in the resolution of the trade dispute with Japan.
German call money rates eased slightly after the Bundesbank added a net
DM500m funds at its weekly repo and let interest rates decline again. Call
money was quoted at 5.95/6.10 per cent, from 6.00/6.15 per cent on Tuesday.
The three basis-point cut was slightly below market consensus, but confirmed
that German rates were on a downward path. The Bundesbank allocated DM83bn
of new funds to replace DM82.5bn of pacts expiring.
The D-Mark finished at FFr3.404, from FFr3.397, against the French franc and
L988.6, from L984.3, compared to the Italian lira.
The Belgian central bank followed the German example and cut its key central
bank rate to 6.15 per cent from 6.25 per cent. The Belgian franc held steady
afterwards at BFr20.590/593 per D-Mark, but closed lower at BFr20.60, from
Tuesday's BFr20.58, in line with the general weakness of EMS currencies
against the D-Mark.
Mr Adrian Cunningham, senior currency economist at UBS, said Belgium still
enjoyed a positive interest rate differential compared to the D-Mark bloc
currencies. He cautioned, however, that 'at some point the market is going
to call into question the extent to which Belgium can bring rates into line
given its fiscal difficulties'. He said Belgium was getting into 'marginal
territory' where further rate cuts could cause currency weakness.
The Bundesbank's small move has reduced the prospect of a rate cut when the
monetary council of the Bank of France meets today.
The dollar continued in poor health yesterday, finishing nearly a pfennig
lower in London at DM1.7070 from DM1.7155. It closed weaker in New York at
DM1.6995.
Although the release of the Johnson red book, and a speech by Fed governor
Mr John Laware, emphasising a strong growth outlook, were both
dollar-positive, they were undermined by the German rate cut. Mr Steve
Hannah, head of research at IBJ International, commented: 'News on the US is
being offset by the laggard behaviour of the German monetary authorities.'
The release of the 'beige book' - an economic summary by the 12 Federal
Reserve district banks, covering the period from mid-January to February 28
 -was eagerly awaited by a market nervous about the US inflationary outlook.
In the event, the Fed said: 'Only limited price pressures are reported -
prices of building materials, selected metals and some chemicals are said to
be rising, but prices of manufactured goods and consumer goods generally are
not experiencing upward pressure.' This quashed fears of an imminent
tightening by the Fed.
Attention will now shift to the release next week of CPI and PPI figures.
The dollar enjoyed improved fortunes against the yen, closing at Y105.835,
up from a low of Y104.80 on the day. Analysts said the firmer dollar
reflected positive developments on the trade front with Japan. It finished
in New York at Y105.665.
Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, provided the impetus when he
said progress had been made in the US-Japan cellular telephone dispute. 'I
am not announcing right now we have an agreement. We do not know, but we
have made progress,' Mr Kantor was reported as saying.
There were also reports of progress in the super-conductor sector. But Mr
Cunningham of UBS noted that there was 'still a long way to go'. He said
there were at least five other sectors in which the US could activate trade
sanctions under the Super 301 executive order. 'The market still needs to
see something come out of the Japanese side,' he added.
Conditions in the UK discount market were fairly tight, the overnight rate
rising to 7.5 per cent. The Bank of England provided the market with Pounds
660m of late assistance after earlier putting Pounds 604m into the system.
This compared to a revised shortage of Pounds 1.3bn.
The Bank announced that it will be providing Pounds 4.5bn to the market
today in its new twice-monthly repo. This represents a net inflow of about
Pounds 1.2bn. Analysts said the improved outcome reflected the recent
tightening of two-week rates in the cash market which made resort to the
repo facility attractive.
</TEXT>
