<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: RTZ economist sees metal prices
remaining flat in 1994
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Average base metal prices are unlikely to be much different this year from
1993, Mr Phillip Crowson, chief economist at RTZ, the world's biggest mining
company, forecast yesterday.
In spite of some signs of economic recovery around the world, '1994 will not
be a particularly exciting year for metals demand', he suggested as RTZ
announced its annual results. There would certainly not be enough of an
increase in demand to reverse the flood of excess metal into stocks.
Several wild cards would continue to influence the supply and demand
balance, including net Chinese trade, the behaviour of CIS exports, and
conflicting influences on Western production.
Prices would be liable 'to fluctuate over a fairly wide range before any
clear tends become established'. But they should not drop back to the low
points reached last November.
Since then, prices have risen about 20 per cent. The rise 'was triggered,
and even sustained by investors acting largely on technical analysis of
chart patterns', Mr Crowson said. A substantial volume of funds, mainly US,
had been seeking alternative outlets to equities and bonds.
Many investment funds had a 'heads I win, tails I don't lose' attitude to
the metal markets. If prices rose, they held on in expectation of further
gains, and if they fell back, they considered metals even better bargains,
and bought.
