<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Peru's blossoming desert goes
on the market - Irrigation is filling the only gap in an otherwise perfect
climate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A strange sight greets the visitor to Peru's northern coastal desert. Men
and women trudge along furrows apparently ploughed in the sand. From time to
time they pounce, burrow with their bare hands and come up with a long white
object resembling a stick. They are harvesting white asparagus.
White asparagus, unlike green, must be grown underground to avoid
photosynthesis; and the unpromising-looking desert soil of Peru's desert
coast is an ideal medium - zero precipitation means no diseases and funguses
attack plants. The cold Humboldt Pacific current keeps temperatures
exceptionally stable, ensuring a sort of permanent spring, which is perfect
for cultivation and year-round harvesting of almost any crop known to man.
All the Peruvian desert needs is irrigation, and the capital to install it.
Not surprisingly, the leaders in drip irrigation technology are the Israelis
and the Peruvians are learning fast from them.
'With the climate Peru enjoys, plus water, we have unparalleled comparative
advantages here,' says Mr Alon Lidai, local representative of Netafim, an
Israeli drip irrigation company. On a 11-hectare pilot asparagus farm,
formerly useless desert, Mr Lidai and the Peruvian owner are growing
top-quality asparagus and exporting to Germany.
The ultimate in high-tech irrigation costs Dollars 2,800 a hectare
installed. Annual costs, including water, labour and fertilisers (large
quantities are required on this poor soil) are around Dollars 5,000 leaving
a good Dollars 7,000 a hectare profit - very substantial for a Peruvian
farmer.
Now a first 14,770-hectare lot of newly, irrigated desert land, is coming on
to the commercial market. The Peruvian government, through the national
development institute, Inade, is selling off to private investors the lands
within the initial ambit of the vast Chavimochic irrigation scheme.
'It's the first time in over 25 years - since General Velasco's 'land
reform' - that it's possible to buy large extensions of land,' says Mr
Rodolfo Masuda, Peru's vice-minister for agriculture. 'The intention is to
allow the private sector, national or foreign, to bring about the
agricultural advances we need.'
The Chavimochic project - an 80-year old dream for the people who live in
the Chao, Viru, Moche and Chicama valleys near Trujillo, from which the
scheme takes its name - started to become a reality in 1987. The Santa
River, one of Peru's most bountiful, has been partially diverted, its waters
channeled through 85km of impressive canals and tunnels across the Andean
foothills.
Eventually, the Santa waters will benefit a total of 133,000 hectares
(bringing 59,000 new hectares into production and supplying another 74,000
with permanent water).
Under the philosophy of the Fujimori government - ironically the extreme
opposite of the preceding Garcia regime, which launched Chavimochic and
obtained start-up funding from the Banco do Brasil - the state has no role
in productive activity. It will sell off the modern, unused tomato paste
plant, originally intended to generate foreign exchange earnings to finance
the loan. It will award a concession to a private company to maintain and
operate the infrastructure of headwater intake, canals and so on. And it
will make farmers, for the first time ever, pay the 'real' cost of the
water.
Mr Masuda is relatively optimistic about sale prospects. He hopes some large
food processing consortia will buy the Chavimochic lands (they can acquire
up to 1,000 hectares), install plants and bring new technology.
They will also provide the marketing skills and contacts as yet lacking in
Peru.
The model tomato paste processing plant in the Chao valley is scheduled for
sale in April or May. It comes with 1,000 already-irrigated hectares and has
capacity to produce 21,000 tonnes of paste a year. World prices have
recently surged from around Dollars 650 a tonne to Dollars 800 or so,
raising hopes for a successful sale. Several large Japanese companies are
reported to be interested.
Apart from the area that accompanies the Chao plant, however, the
Chavimochic lands require substantial further investment. Secondary channels
must be built to run water off from the main canal, the land prepared and
high-tech irrigation equipment installed.
Costs could run between Dollars 5,000 and Dollars 6,000 a hectare, on top of
the average Dollars 1,450 base price being asked.
Sceptics say it is possible to acquire irrigated land in other Peruvian
valleys for a third of that price. Prospects for real development at
Chavimochic are likely to hinge on the big investor who has the bucks to
back the vision.
</TEXT>
<XX>
