<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / International Capital Markets: CBoT to reorganise management
system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Chicago Board of Trade, the world's busiest futures exchange, is on the
verge of reorganising its management structure in a move aimed at preserving
its lead in an increasingly competitive industry.
Although the CBoT is enjoying record volume, thanks to volatility in world
interest rate and foreign currency markets, exchange members have complained
of declining profits and a cumbersome committee structure that hampers
innovation and expansion. More agile exchanges like London's Liffe and the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange have surpassed the CBoT in dollar value of
contracts traded, and in the amount of institutional business they attract.
Last year, the exchange asked the consultancy firm of Booz-Allen &amp; Hamilton
to examine its management practices and recommend reforms. On Tuesday, the
CBoT's board of directors agreed to adopt the Booz-Allen recommendations,
subject to an April 14 vote of the full membership.
Booze Allen has suggested that the CBoT cut its deeply imbedded and
politically oriented system of more than 100 committees to just five,
charged with oversight of finance, strategy, audit, management, and
regulation.
It also recommended that CBoT staff be given more powers for day-to-day
management of the exchange, while the chairman and board of directors,
comprised mostly of trader-members, focus on strategy and planning for the
exchange.
Both Mr Patrick Arbor, CBoT's chairman, and Mr Thomas Donovan, its
president, have endorsed the report.
</TEXT>
