<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / International Company News: First-half downturn at ACP
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Australian Consolidated Press Holdings (ACP), the quoted media group in
which Mr Kerry Packer's family company, Consolidated Press, has a 45 per
cent interest, yesterday announced an 8.6 per cent drop in after-tax profits
during the six months to end-December, at ADollars 30.2m (USDollars 21.6m).
Sales revenues dipped from ADollars 212.3m to ADollars 208.5m, while
operating profits, before both interest and tax, fell from ADollars 66.7m to
ADollars 55.8m.
However, ACP said that the comparisons were distorted by some changes to
accounting policies in 1992, which bought a one-off benefit; by the sale of
the Offset Alpine business; and by the impact of start-up costs of three new
titles in Australia during the most recent half year - The New Weekly, SHE
and National Enquirer.
The latest half-year operating profit is after a ADollars 6.4m loss in
respect of these titles and their launch costs. The National Enquirer joint
venture was suspended in December, but ACP said that it was confident that
the investment in the two women's magazine titles would 'add substantial
value . . . over the longer term'.
The company added that circulation revenues in Australia had improved by
around 7 per cent, year-on-year, once the impact of new titles was excluded.
However, it acknowledged that the forecast upturn in national display
advertising had not occurred.
'Advertising revenues were flat compared to the same period of 1992. This
situation appears likely to remain unchanged for the remainder of the
current financial year,' it said. Because of this and the start-up costs,
ACP said it was unlikely it would 'significantly exceed' last year's profits
total this time round.
ACP added that it was in 'final negotiations' with bankers over a
restructuring of debt facilities, which it hopes will cut interest costs.
Year-end borrowings are forecast to be below ADollars 270m.
</TEXT>
