<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / International Company News: Pulp and paper group logs a
privatisation record - The Swedish public is to be offered a further 34% of
AssiDoman over the next 12 days
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sweden's right-centre government yesterday proclaimed a successful start to
its biggest privatisation issue to date, announcing that an offer to Swedish
and foreign institutions of a 15 per cent chunk of the forestry group
AssiDoman had been three times subscribed.
The government used the bids from institutions to set a price of SKr153 per
share for AssiDoman, valuing the company at more than SKr16bn (Dollars 2bn).
A further 34 per cent stake is to be sold to the Swedish public over the
next 12 days at a discounted price of SKr138.
In total the state should raise around SKr8bn from the sale of the 49 per
cent of AssiDoman, by some margin the largest privatisation Prime Minister
Carl Bildt's market-orientated coalition has pulled off since it came to
power in late-1991.
The previous biggest sale was the SKr2.2bn flotation last May of Celsius,
the defence group. Before that, the state sold its stake in SSAB, the steel
group. Next in line is the planned sell-off in June of the state's majority
stake in Pharmacia, the pharmaceuticals group spun off last year from
Procordia under a deal between the government and Volvo, which jointly
controlled Procordia. That should raise about SKr16bn at today's market
prices. The state's one-third stake in the petroleum retailer OK Petroleum
is also to be sold by private placement.
Mr Per Westerberg, the industry minister, says the government will have sold
35 companies by the time the general election comes around in September. 'If
we succeed with AssiDoman and Pharmacia then we will have raised very close
to SKr30bn over the three years. That is in line with our goal of an average
of SKr10bn a year and we would be very satisfied with that.'
Of the AssiDoman sale he said: 'We will have a strong new pulp and paper
group in Sweden with the financial muscle to act in the market. A strictly
commercial company that can look for partners - like Celsius and SSAB -
without political interference.'
The Swedish privatisation path has not all been smooth, however, and big
question marks remain over potential issues still to come. The opposition
Social Democratic party, which is leading in the opinion polls at present,
is firmly opposed to diluting the state's share in companies such as the
telecommunications company Telia and Vattenfall, the state power company,
which are on the coalition's list for some degree of privatisation after the
election.
The Social Democrats, indeed, were opposed to the privatisation of
AssiDoman. The company was formed at the turn of the year from the
state-owned groups Assi and Doman and will soon also take over a third
company, Ncb. This will make it Sweden's fourth largest forestry group, the
country's biggest owner of forests and the biggest producer of sawn timber.
Under the terms of the present sell-off, the state will remain a 51 per cent
stake-holder in AssiDoman. But Mr Westerberg said this was likely eventually
to slip below a majority holding.
This has angered the Social Democrats who oppose the loss of state control
over companies which they identify as being of vital interest in the control
of infrastructure and natural resources. Mr Anders Sundstrom, the Social
Democratic spokesman on industry, said yesterday his party would block any
further dilution of the state's holding in AssiDoman if it gets back into
power in September.
Mr Westerberg also came under fire over the Celsius issue which was 17 times
oversubscribed - leading to claims that the state 'lost' up to SKr2bn by
under-pricing the shares. It was partly for that reason that he opted for
the pre-bidding method to set a price for AssiDoman.
He should not run into such problems with Pharmacia, which is already listed
on the stock exchange and the privatisation of which is not opposed by the
Social Democrats. Mr Sundstrom also supports the eventual re-sale to the
private sector of Nordbanken, the biggest victim of the Swedish banking
crisis which is not now expected to be ready for privatisation until 1995.
But Mr Westerberg's intention in due course to put the two giants
Vattenfall, Europe's sixth largest electricity producer, and Telia on the
privatisation block will clearly depend on the outcome of the election. 'We
don't want to privatise Telia, Vattenfall or the forests - not even a
minority share,' said Mr Sundstrom.
</TEXT>
<XX>
