<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / International Company News: Sharp third-quarter fall for
Heinz
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in HJ Heinz, the US food company headed by Mr Tony O'Reilly, the
Irish businessman, sank to a 12-month low yesterday as the company reported
a sharp decline in third-quarter profits.
Net income fell by 21 per cent to Dollars 128.6m in the quarter ended
January 26, on turnover down from Dollars 1.77bn to Dollars 1.71bn. The
shares fell Dollars  1/2 to close at Dollars 31.
One reason for the downturn in net profits was an increase in the effective
tax rate for the quarter from 34.4 per cent to 40.3 per cent. But pre-tax
profits were also badly down, by almost 13 per cent.
Heinz said a number of factors were to blame. Two profit-making companies -
the confectionery business of Heinz Italy and the Near East specialty rice
business - had been sold during the year, and the group's marketing expenses
were 19 per cent higher than in the comparable quarter.
But the biggest factor was the poor performance of the Weight Watchers
business, which draws half its revenues from diet classes and half from diet
foods. This suffered from unusually severe winter conditions in the US and
from disruption caused by the Los Angeles earthquake, both of which kept
dieters at home.
Longer-term, Weight Watchers has also been suffering from a decline in the
obsession with personal fitness that characterised the 1980s and from a
tendency among remaining weight watchers to save money in less prosperous
times by making up their own diets.
On the positive side, Heinz saw volume gains in beans, ketchup, pet foods
and food service products (bulk foods for the catering industry), but these
were partially offset by volume declines in the Weight Watchers businesses
(meetings and foods) and StarKist tuna.
Earnings per share in the third quarter fell from 62 cents to 50 cents. For
the nine months to January, turnover was up from Dollars 5.07bn to Dollars
5.1bn, net income rose from Dollars 326.6m to Dollars 473.9m, and earnings
per share rose from Dollars 1.77 to Dollars 1.84 excluding accounting
changes - though this included a gain of 24 cents a share on the sale of the
two businesses.
</TEXT>
