FT  10 MAR 94 / International Company News: Kone to sell cranes business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Kone, the Finnish elevators group, is to sell its cranes unit to Industri
Kapital, a Scandinavian industrial investment fund, for more than FM600m
(Dollars 108.3m).
The sale is part of the group's continuing focus on core business, and
follows last year's disposal of MacGregor-Navire, the world's leading
supplier of shipboard cargo handling equipment. The deal will increase
Kone's equity-to-assets ratio to around 40 per cent
Kone Cranes is a world leader in industrial and ship-to-shore cranes, and
has 40 companies in 20 countries. It had sales of FM1.93bn in 1993, up 26
per cent, and its order book rose 12 per cent to FM1.01bn.
Industri Kapital is backed by a group of Scandinavian banks, insurance
companies and funds, and is already a significant shareholder in a number of
Nordic industrial and service companies.
Mr Bjorn Saven, Industri Kapital managing director, said Kone Cranes had 'a
leading market position in an attractive market niche where we see good
potential for further development'. He said the aim was to seek a stock
market listing for the unit.
Exact terms of the sale will be based on asset values within Kone Cranes
when the deal is finalised over the next few weeks.
</TEXT>
