<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Portals beats expectations with 22% advance
to Pounds 31m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Strong overseas demand for banknote paper and a growing appetite for round
teabags helped Portals Group report a stronger than expected advance in
1993.
Pre-tax profits of the security and specialist papermaker and environmental
protection and control products group rose by 22 per cent to Pounds 31m in
the year to end-December.
That compared with profits of Pounds 25.5m in 1992, when the outcome was
depressed by net provisions totalling Pounds 1.84m. Interest costs for 1993
fell to Pounds 91,000 (Pounds 617,000) and the group recorded a Pounds
304,000 (Pounds 127,000) profit on the sale of properties.
Turnover from continuing operations grew by 11 per cent to Pounds 197.9m
(Pounds 178.3m) led by the security and specialist papermaking division
which lifted its turnover by 15.2 per cent to Pounds 116m (Pounds 100.7m.)
Earnings per share were up 27.6 per cent to 34.55p (27.08p) and a final
dividend of 10.75p (9.5p) is recommended making a total for the year of 16p
(14.5p.)
Buoyed by the higher than expected profits and an upbeat market assessment
from Mr John Lloyd, Portals' managing director, the group's shares closed up
29p at 608p.
Mr Lloyd said that as a result of increasing demand for Portals' banknote
paper, particularly from developing nations and eastern Europe, the group
had decided to install a new 4,000 tonne banknote paper machine costing
Pounds 19m at its Overton mill, which will come on stream in 1996.
Operating profits from continuing operations increased by 8 per cent to
Pounds 30.8m (Pounds 28.5m). In the security and specialist papermaking
division
the increasing demand for round teabags - which now claim two thirds of the
marketplace - helped JR Crompton lift output to record levels.
After a strong performance in 1992 the protection and control division
recorded flat operating profits from continuing operations of Pounds 8.56m
(Pounds 8.43m) on turnover up by 5.5 per cent to Pounds 81.9m (Pounds
77.7m.)
The group ended the year with Pounds 16m of net cash compared with net
borrowings of Pounds 2.75m a year earlier.
COMMENT
Portals' specialist papermaking business used to be viewed as dependable but
boring, but this is changing. The market, which historically has grown at a
real rate of between 2 and 3 per cent a year, is now growing at between 4
and 5 per cent a year. The banknote market has expanded because of the
break-up of the Soviet empire and growth in emerging markets like south-east
Asia, and demand for high security paper is growing as governments try to
keep one step ahead of the counterfeiters. Pre-tax profits could reach
Pounds 34.5m this year producing 39p of earnings and a prospective p/e of
15.6. Buy this stock.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Portals Group.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
