<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Ind Newspapers rises to IPounds 29m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Independent Newspapers, the Irish newspaper group controlled by Mr Tony
O'Reilly, has achieved an 81 per cent increase in 1993 pre-tax profits from
IPounds 16m to IPounds 29m (Pounds 27.9m) on turnover of IPounds 173.5m.
Some IPounds 7.3m of the profit increase was due to lower interest charges
resulting from the conversion last April of the group's IPounds 30m
convertible capital bond issue.
This included the reincorporation of an interest credit of IPounds 2.5m in
accrued interest on the bonds. Net debt at year-end fell to IPounds 11m
(IPounds 48m), giving gearing of 6 per cent. Recent acquisitions in South
Africa and the UK have since increased borrowings to IPounds 30m.
Operating profits for 1993 rose to IPounds 27.1m (IPounds 22.2m). An
exceptional charge of IPounds 3m as a provision against the investment in
the loss-making Tribune newspaper, was offset by an IPounds 3.8m gain on the
disposal of its Mirror Group stake .
The profit contribution from the Australian interests in the APN newspaper
group and Buspak advertising doubled to IPounds 9m, and its UK subsidiaries
returned to profit with a contribution of IPounds 0.5m.
The input from the core Irish newspaper business grew by 6 per cent to
IPounds 18.4m.
Princes Holdings, the 50 per cent-owned cable TV subsidiary in Ireland, did
not contribute any profits, but increased its subscriber base by 57 per cent
to 103,000 customers through a deliberate loss-leading marketing campaign.
Mr Liam Healey, group chief executive, said the subsidiary would begin to
show profits this year. A subscriber base of some 250,000 customers was
targetted for 1997.
Last month the group spent IPounds 22m on a 29.99 per cent stake in
Newspaper Publishing, publisher of the UK Independent and Independent on
Sunday.
It has also taken a 31 per cent stake in the South African Argus newspaper
group through a share-swap deal which will give Argus shareholders a 5 per
cent holding in Independent Newspapers.
Earnings per share came through at 30.54p (19.44p) basic and 24.93p (19.6p)
fully diluted.
A final dividend of 7p is recommended, for a total of 11p (9.3p adjusted).
COMMENT
Independent Newspapers is a big fish in the cramped pond of the Irish
newspaper market, and growing contributions from overseas acquisitions like
APN will be vital to sustain the impressive level of growth achieved
hitherto. Barring civil war in South Africa, the Argus move appears a good
one. But the taking of a minority stake in the loss-making Newspaper
Publishing group in the UK without being able to bring Independent's proven
management skills to bear at board level, could misfire. Earnings per share
of 28p look achievable in 1994, giving a prospective p/e multiple of 17.7,
which makes it pricey in the confines of the Irish market but cheap against
its international peers.
</TEXT>
