<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Making money out of the wrong terms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Greg Dyke, chief executive of London Weekend Television, lost his job
yesterday - and made some more money.
However it was not just the resignation settlement reached after he failed
to negotiate acceptable terms to stay on with Granada, the new owners of
LWT, that added to his riches.
He made another Pounds 46,000 when the market digested the news of his
resignation and marked Granada's shares up by 4p, presumably in the
expectation that the new LWT chief executive, Mr Charles Allen of Granada,
may cut costs more enthusiastically than Mr Dyke.
'We would have liked to have kept Greg Dyke on, but it had to be on the
right terms,' said Mr Allen, who has set up shop in the spartan Waterloo
room at LWT's Southbank headquarters until the chief executive's office
becomes free at the end of this month.
The right terms for Mr Dyke, one of the more charismatic executives in
commercial television, famous for turning round the fortunes of TV-am, the
breakfast broadcaster, by giving greater prominence to a glove puppet called
Roland Rat, were essentially that he remained as the LWT chief executive.
As the man running a subsidiary of Granada he would have reported to Mr
Allen as head of Granada's television and leisure businesses.
Mr Dyke, whose jobs have included local newspaper reporter and trainee Marks
and Spencer manager, would have stayed if he had been offered oversight of
Granada Television as well as LWT and a seat on the main Granada board.
Mr Dyke may have lost his job, but even before the effects of the 4p rise in
the Granada share price, his stake in the company was worth about Pounds
8.2m.
As a result of the successful Granada takeover, one of the oddest but most
effective management duos in commercial television is leaving LWT.
The 'toff', Sir Christopher Bland, former Guards officer and LWT chairman,
will leave at the end of next week some Pounds 14m richer, soon to be
followed by Mr Dyke, who has always played up his proletarian origins.
Mr Gerry Robinson, Granada's chief executive, will take over as chairman of
LWT.
Mr Dyke has always insisted that the two were much more similar than
appearances suggested.
'We both swear like troopers, have the attention span of a peanut, and like
to win,' he said, before it became totally clear that they had lost.
The scale of the loss became clear on Friday February 25, the final deadline
for the Granada bid. At the 11th hour Sir Christopher and Mr Dyke were
offered 4m shares by arbitrageurs at Pounds 8 each, the sort of price they
had been arguing the company was worth.
After a half-hearted attempt to finance the share purchase they decided to
bow to the inevitable, partly because the deal might have cost them several
million pounds.
In the Waterloo room yesterday Mr Allen was relaxed and conciliatory after a
holiday. When he was appointed chief executive of Granada Television 18
months ago after a career in accountancy and general management, it was
portrayed as something close to the end of civilisation.
He believes he has proved his point that 'the bottom line' and producing an
increased stream of quality television are not mutually inconsistent.
As with the first months at Granada Television, Mr Allen will spent the next
three to six months as hands on chief executive, encouraging staff to come
up with a plan for the future and then sticking to it.
An unspecified number of jobs will go where there is duplication and overlap
between Granada and LWT, but Mr Allen is thinking more in terms of growth
and making more programmes than in cutting back.
By next year he is thinking of developing an international satellite channel
with partners, but calling on the programme strengths and libraries of
Granada Television and LWT.
By then, Mr Dyke might have a clear idea what he wants to do next. At the
moment the speculation runs from chief executive of a bid for a new Channel
5 franchise through managing director of BBC Television (fully occupied at
present) to buying Brentford, the football team he supports.
More plausibly, some of the City investors who supported Granada in the
hostile bid against LWT are now interested in supporting financially
whatever Sir Christopher Bland and Mr Greg Dyke decide to do next in the
media.
</TEXT>
