<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / UK Company News: BICC profit of Pounds 104m fails to cover
pay-out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The absence of exceptional items helped BICC, the cables and construction
group, post significantly higher pre-tax profits last year. However the
profits were again insufficient to cover the group's maintained dividend.
Pre-tax profits increased to Pounds 104m from a restated Pounds 63m the
previous year when profits were reduced by property and Channel Tunnel
provisions totalling Pounds 39m. Group turnover increased by 7.4 per cent to
Pounds 3.92bn (Pounds 3.65bn.)
Operating profits were flat at Pounds 135m, excluding a Pounds 2m
acquisition contribution last year and the substantial property and Channel
Tunnel charges in 1992.
Earnings per share were 15.4p, just ahead of the 1992's restated
pre-execeptional level of 14.7p. Sir Robin Biggam, chairman, said the group
had again been successful in generating cash from its operations and this,
taken in conjunction with signs of improvement in some of the group's
markets, had led the board to recommend a maintained final dividend of
13.25p making a full-year total unchanged at 19.25p.
The shares fell 16p to close at 438p.
He said the results, 'continued to reflect the exceptionally difficult
trading environment which we have experienced over the last three years'.
'We now have two very strong and competitive businesses, which are in
excellent positions to benefit from improving market conditions. recently we
have seen some signs of improvement in Australia, North America and the UK,
and other European markets are likely to stabilise in the current year.
Accordingly, we expect to see our performance improving in 1994.'
In construction Balfour Beatty posted operating profits of Pounds 40m, up
Pounds 3m on the previous year on turnover that slipped to Pounds 1.83bn
(Pounds 1.85bn.) Over the past five years Balfour Beatty has generated
Pounds 150m of profits.
The group's other core business, cables, was affected by continuing market
weakness. BICC Cables, which mainly operates in Europe, saw profits fall by
14 per cent to Pounds 67m from Pounds 78m the previous year on turnover that
increased to Pounds 1.05bn (Pounds 946m.) Profits in the UK, however, held
up well.
Sir Robin said the decline was largely attributable to losses incurred in
power cables in Spain. There was also a softening of demand for cable in the
Italian, German and Portuguese markets.
COMMENT
BICC has been forced to dip into reserves again to maintain the dividend.
With its main markets around the world showing signs of improvement, a
similar move should not be required again this year. The group has a clear
strategy, the balance sheet is strong and its businesses have been
rationalised. Pre-tax profit of about Pounds 140m are expected this year
producing earnings of about 20.2. With a lofty prospective p/e of 21.7, the
stock is supported only by its generous yield.
</TEXT>
