<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Fokker drops deeper in the red as market demand falls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Fokker, the Dutch aircraft maker, has ploughed heavily into the red for 1993
after slack market conditions forced it to cut prices to attract customers.
The company, which came under control of Daimler-Benz of Germany last year,
said net losses totalled Fl 460m (Pounds 164m). This is more than three
times higher than its previous predictions of a Fl 150m loss. Fokker posted
a net profit of Fl 19.8m for 1992.
The shares closed down nearly 12.5 per cent at Fl 18.30 from Fl 20.90 on
Tuesday.
Fokker blamed the unexpectedly large losses on a provision of Fl 275m to
cover the cost of cutting prices to customers. Group turnover fell nearly 10
per cent to Fl 3.7bn from Fl 4.1bn.
The price discounting has allowed the company to reduce its unsold stock to
just six aircraft in March 1994 from 32 at the start of 1993.
Like other aircraft manufacturers, Fokker has been hit by the financial
difficulties of the world's airlines.
The 1993 figures also include a separate charge of Fl 90m to finance
redundancies in the first half. Last month, Fokker said 1,900 further jobs
would have to be eliminated this year, representing the third large
restructuring in three years, as part of wider efforts to reduce output to
meet lower market demand. 'The company cannot afford to continue building
more aircraft than the market demands,' it said.
Interest charges rose to Fl 181m from Fl 126m, reflecting Fokker's increased
involvement in sales financing, mainly leasing, as a way of finding
customers.
The company also announced that Mr Ben van Schaik is to become its
management board chairman on April 1, succeeding Mr Erik Jan Nederkoorn who
resigned last month after a boardroom row.
Mr van Schaik, a Dutchman, is the head of European sales at Mercedes-Benz
Commercial Vehicles in Stuttgart, Germany.
The appointment ends speculation that Fokker's majority shareholder would
put a German or a non-Dutch national at the head of the company.
</TEXT>
