<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / RTZ remains steady and completes move into mining
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RTZ, the world's biggest mining company, demonstrated its resilience to low
commodity prices with a steady performance in 1993 when its plans to focus
the group wholly on mining were completed. Mr Robert Wilson described the
year as a landmark for the company, concluding the restructuring started in
1988. Since then, average dollar non-ferrous metal prices fell 44 per cent,
with a 15 per cent decline last year.
In total 'the dismally low prices for many of our products', including coal
and iron ore, reduced 1993 earnings by Pounds 122m, said Mr Wilson. However
this was more than offset by a Pounds 78m contribution from volume growth
and a Pounds 103m gain from exchange rate movements.
Pre-tax profits fell from Pounds 521m to Pounds 435m. But the figure
contains Pounds 217m of exceptional items, including Pounds 165m related to
the disposal of its Pillar industrial division. Group turnover increased
from Pounds 4.6bn to Pounds 4.8bn.
Net attributable earnings were up 20 per cent to Pounds 287m.
Earnings per share rose from 22.5p to 27p. However, adjusted earnings, which
reflect the underlying performance by excluding exceptional items, rose by a
more modest 10 per cent, from Pounds 338m to Pounds 373m.
Sir Derek Birkin, presenting his last results as executive chairman, said
the prices of most metals appeared to have stopped falling. 'However, they
are likely to be volatile for some time because of a combination of renewed
investor interest, possibly erratic supplies, and high inventories.'
A final dividend of 7p is proposed, bringing the total to 20.5p compared
with 19.5p. Sir Derek said the increase 'should be taken as an indicator not
of the outlook for 1994 but of our confidence in the company's potential
once recovery is soundly established'.
During the year the group moved into the US coal industry for a total outlay
of Pounds 320m, and disposed of Pillar, which should realise Pounds 900m.
The sale helped to cut net debt from Pounds 1bn to Pounds 384m, reducing
gearing from 36 per cent to 12 per cent. Mr Christopher Bull, finance
director, said it was 'not a bad time to have a very strong balance sheet'
as the company expected to double capital expenditure this year from 1993's
Pounds 265m.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
