<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Norway's Uni Storebrand pulls out of international
reinsurance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Uni Storebrand, Norway's biggest insurer, yesterday reported record 1993
results but announced that it was withdrawing from the international
re-insurance business following a succession of losses.
'Negative results over several years plus a weak capital base are the main
reasons why Uni Storebrand International is being wound down,' the group
said. It is charging NKr450m (Pounds 408m) against the 1993 accounts to
cover expenses during the run-off period.
Uni has also written down the value of its shares in Uni International,
which made an operating loss of NKr357m last year, by NKr694m. In 1993 the
international business represented 20 per cent of group premiums.
Uni said its international reinsurance operations were unlikely to generate
an acceptable rate of return for the foreseeable future, and capital could
be deployed more profitably on core domestic businesses.
Uni is to continue to undertake insurance business internationally in
sectors such as marine, oil and satellite within its non-life unit. But the
Singapore office is to be closed while Uni Storebrand UK has been supplied
with a liquidity support guarantee of up to Pounds 20m to continue
operations. The UK business is to be put up for sale.
In the US, Uni last year failed to succeed with an initial public offering
for Christiania Re, but said that operations would continue until the unit
was sold.
Uni is not the only Scandinavian insurer to withdraw from international
reinsurance. Last year, Swedish rivals Skandia and Trygg-Hansa cut their
reinsurance business.
For 1993 the group achieved a net profit of NKr1.02bn against a loss of
NKr3.54bn in 1992. The result was helped by NKr3.4bn in realised gains on
securities and bonds against losses of NKr800m in 1992.
Group net operating income rose last year to NKr23.6bn from NKr20.6bn.
Premium income fell to NKr13.7bn from NKr14.3bn. Uni plans to pay a dividend
of NKr1.10 per preference share and NKr0.20 per ordinary share.
Skandia rights issue, Page 29
