<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / T&amp;N raises asbestos lawsuits provision to Pounds 21m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT and RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
T&amp;N, the British engineering and motor components group, said yesterday it
had increased its liability provision for asbestos-linked legal action by 27
per cent after a flood of new compensation claims in the US.
The Manchester-based group, formerly one of Britain's largest manufacturers
of asbestos-based products, has set aside Pounds 21.1m to cover legal and
settlement costs arising out of the claims, compared with a Pounds 16.6m
provision in 1992.
In spite of the increased provisions, T&amp;N said it expected its liabilities
to decline. The issue has cast a shadow over the group's prospects for more
than a decade.
Claims, mainly in the US, from victims of asbestos-related diseases have
left insurance companies - and the troubled Lloyd's market in London - with
billions of pounds of losses and have forced some of the world's leading
asbestos producers into bankruptcy proceedings.
T&amp;N - formerly Turner &amp; Newall - said a class action under way in New York
might significantly reduce legal claims. Mr Colin Hope, chairman and chief
executive, said T&amp;N had joined forces with 20 companies and their insurers
to pursue the action, which is being overseen by the US Centre for Claims
Resolution, a body that seeks to arbitrate legal actions.
'This is a watershed ruling. It would significantly limit our liability and
progressively reduce our costs to zero over the next 10 years,' Mr Hope
added. According to T&amp;N, the preliminary plan has been approved by a federal
court judge and a final ruling is expected in the next two weeks.
The action aims to alter US law so that future asbestos claimants would have
to submit to medical tests and settle for fixed compensation payments linked
to their level of disability or illness. Companies taking part in the action
would settle claims more rapidly.
Aware that such a class action is likely to succeed, US law firms are
understood to have sharply increased the number of cases filed against such
companies, attempting to extract settlements before the new system comes
into effect.
T&amp;N claimed the number of cases filed in New York against asbestos producers
and their insurers was running at about 3,000 a month. In the past decade,
T&amp;N has spent more than Pounds 130m on asbestos legal costs and settlements.
Mr Hope said the company had also built up a balance sheet provision of
Pounds 38.4m to cover longer-term legal costs. Those potential costs include
13 outstanding actions against asbestos products from buildings.
T&amp;N ahead, Page 27
</TEXT>
<XX>
