<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Kohl issues plea to UK and Spain over EU enlargement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany issued an extraordinary personal appeal to
Britain and Spain yesterday to drop their objections to the compromise for
enlargement of the European Union.
He pinned the blame for the failure of the latest round of negotiations
firmly on those two countries, and said if no agreement was reached by next
week, it would be impossible to admit Austria, Finland, Norway and Sweden by
January 1 1995.
'Given the overriding political importance of this enlargement for Europe,
it is completely impossible both for the (German) government, and for me in
particular, to understand how some member states have not yet endorsed the
consensus,' he said in an official statement.
Mr Kohl said a fishing rights package put on the table on Tuesday protected
the interests of all member states of the community, in particular Spain,
while taking into account the particular importance of the industry for the
Norwegian population.
As for the British objection to any change in the number of votes needed for
a 'blocking minority' in the Council of Ministers, he said the Greek
presidency had put forward 'a sensible proposal' building on suggestions
made by Germany. The German concern is that if the whole package is not tied
up by next week at the latest, there will not be enough time for the
European parliament and all member states, as well as applicants, to approve
it before the end of the year.
Officials fear if that deadline is missed, the enlargement process could be
delayed for months.
The German government is particularly baffled by the British attitude over
the voting question.
In Strasbourg, the European Parliament warned the UK and Spain it would not
support the EU's planned move from 12 to 16 members without a change in
voting rights to reflect an expanded Europe.
But while the Norwegian government appeared sanguine yesterday about
prospects for a final resolution of its fishing rights conflict with Spain,
Madrid said proposals it had been presented with in Brussels late on Tuesday
were 'a joke'.
Government officials in Madrid dug their heels in after Germany's public
criticism. Responding to a charge by Mr Klaus Kinkel, the German foreign
minister, that Spain 'has to move', they said it was up to Norway to move by
making a more serious offer.
London, though, was trying to ignore the German appeal. No 10 Downing Street
said that Mr John Major, the prime minister, remained 'determined to protect
our interests in an enlarged community'.
Officials said the government was committed to retaining the existing
23-vote blocking minority.
Reporting by Quentin Peel in Bonn, Lionel Barber in Brussels, David White in
Madrid and Kevin Brown in London
</TEXT>
