<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / The Lex Column: RTZ
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It is a measure of RTZ's quality that earnings and the dividend have been
edged higher despite the cyclical trough in metals prices. If the company
looked hemmed in following the acquisition of Nerco's US coal assets a year
ago, the sale of Pillar has restored its room for manoeuvre. Year end
gearing of 12 per cent - rising to perhaps 20 per cent as higher capital
expenditure starts to bite - leaves plenty of scope for deal-making. Another
step in US coal would make good sense.
Not that RTZ needs a deal to deliver earnings growth. Capital expenditure of
Pounds 500m this year points to no lack of investment opportunity within the
existing business. Big gains should come from the cyclical upswing in metals
prices. True, RTZ's heady cocktail of currency and commodity exposures makes
the pace of profits growth unusually difficult to judge. On the company's
own view that average metals prices this year will be little different from
last, the immediate outlook is far from sparkling.
But if metals prices peak towards the end of the decade at levels which are
in real terms similar to the late 1980s, RTZ might squeeze up to Pounds 1 a
share of earnings from its existing assets. On that basis the shares -
having risen by 30 per cent since November - stand on a peak earnings
multiple of nearly 9 times. While investors are prepared to take an
optimistic view of metals prices, that rating seems fair enough. It will
take another well-judged deal to move the shares much higher.
</TEXT>
