<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / The Lex Column: Standard Chartered
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
While HSBC has been diversifying out of Asia with its purchase of Midland,
Standard Chartered seems to be moving in the other direction. Not only did
three quarters of last year's operating profits originate in the Far East;
the bank is talking about disposing of activities in the industrial world
that do not fit in with its particular focus. All that makes its shares
attractive to investors looking for emerging market exposure. But it also
makes the business more risky, especially given Standard's abnormally low
regional bad debt provisions. That in turn requires a high return.
Yesterday's 4 per cent fall in the share price suggests Standard's net
return on shareholders' funds of 20.8 per cent is not yet quite high enough,
even though it is roughly similar to that of HSBC. A high return is all the
more necessary since the bank is still highly leveraged, especially in Hong
Kong, where net assets of only Pounds 307m support a balance sheet of Pounds
11.5bn.
Standard now has some healthy earnings to retain, but its tier one capital
ratio was bolstered last year by an issue of preference capital and a
reduction in risk-weighted assets. A test for the new management is to
exploit its Asian franchise to improve returns. This year it will be helped
by falling UK provisions and a lower tax charge. Standard should earn enough
to permit another large dividend increase. That could underpin the share
price but it would take evidence of more fundamental improvement to drive it
forward again.
</TEXT>
