<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / The Lex Column: BAT smokes without fire
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BAT's smoking cash flow machine coughed slightly in 1993. The dust-up
started by the Marlboro men in the US has certainly bruised Brown and
Williamson. Its position as number three in the US market means it must
continue to follow rather than lead the battle over margins. That struggle
may abate now that Marlboro is regaining ground, but there remains a threat
of higher tobacco taxes - and thus renewed pressure on gross margins - later
this year.
From a profits' perspective, the disappointment in tobacco was offset by
growth in financial services. Gearing also fell, though significantly most
of the improvement came from paying last year's dividend in shares rather
than cash. The crimp in underlying cash flow may still be a medium term
barrier to the company's expansionist ambitions in continental Europe. BAT's
aim of increasing both its dividend payout and its cover is another
inhibition on large acquisitions. The company argues that prudence dictates
it will not pay the kind of fancy prices currently being demanded by
Parisian sellers of insurance companies. In truth, constraints elsewhere
within the business must also have played their part.
For the time being BAT is probably stuck with growing its own greenfield
life business on the continent and chiselling more from the existing
insurance operations. The problem of valuing a combination of tobacco and
insurance earnings also remains. Potential for dividend growth underpins
BAT's yield. But in the absence of anything more dramatic, the shares are
unlikely to catch fire.
</TEXT>
