<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Leading Article: Jail madness
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
England's prison population is rising sharply. Since the beginning of last
year, the numbers have increased from 41,000 to 48,000 and are still going
up. Over the past six weeks, jails have become so overcrowded in some parts
of the country that prisoners have had to be kept in police cells. At nearly
one prisoner for every 1,000 people in the country, the UK in 1991 had a
higher proportion of its population in jail than every Council of Europe
nation apart from Hungary.
The rise in prison numbers stems from a hardening in public attitudes to
crime. The idea that society was being too soft on criminals has been picked
up by judges and reflected in their sentencing policies.
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, has also seen the opportunity to play
to the public mood by promising a crack-down on crime. He has instituted
policies designed to send more offenders to jail and make prison life more
austere. This is a marked u-turn from the policy of reducing the prison
population pursued by previous Conservative home secretaries.
One fear is that the mounting jail population will lead to such overcrowding
that there will be another round of prison riots like that at Strangeways in
1990. This fear was voiced by prison governors in their annual conference
yesterday.
Mr Derek Lewis, the prison service's director-general, says it is wrong to
talk about a crisis. But he admits that the situation is difficult. The
growth in the prison population has delayed reforms to end overcrowding and
'slopping out', where prisoners do not have toilets in their cells. While
prison capacity is being expanded to cope with the increased numbers, army
camps and other contingency arrangements may have to be deployed to house
prisoners if numbers rise faster than expected. All this carries a greater
risk of rioting, Mr Lewis acknowledges.
Even if the risks of riots are exaggerated, the overall policy of increasing
prison numbers is madness. Violent criminals must be jailed so long as they
are a danger to the public. But there is no sense in putting non-violent
criminals for long periods behind bars.
Not only does it cost the taxpayer about 10 times as much to keep a prisoner
in jail as to monitor a community service order. There is little evidence
that prison helps rehabilitation. Mr Douglas Hurd, when home secretary, used
to say that jail was an expensive way of making bad men worse. It is time Mr
Howard abandoned his demagogic policies and imbibed the wisdom of his
predecessors.
</TEXT>
<XX>
