<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Letters to the Editor: Folly in a privatised railway
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr OWEN SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Charles Batchelor's article 'Obstacles on the mainline' (March 7) on
BR's privatisation is timely in illuminating the intrinsic difficulties
associated with this nonsensical policy. It is difficult to see how an
adequately capitalised railway can emerge from the application of the
framework laid down in the Railways Act 1993 without changes which will be
massively detrimental to the travelling public.
Recent reports in your newspaper have indicated that annual rates of return
on their equity investments of up to 20 per cent are sought by capital
markets in the UK. These are significantly above the low rates of return
which those profitable parts of the rail business generate now (in 1992
InterCity was calculated as making a return of only 1 per cent on its
capital assets).
BR operates one of the leanest railways in Europe and scope for internal
efficiency savings is small. Returns on capital investment will therefore
likely be increased by cutting services, closing lines and increasing fares
leading to big falls in usage.
The same has occurred with bus deregulation and privatisation since 1985,
where ministers have acknowledged the follies of the policy by backtracking
on their manifesto commitment to deregulate bus provision in London. It is
hoped BR privatisation will be similarly reconsidered before irreparable
damage is inflicted on the national railways.
Owen Simon,
106 Elborough Street,
London SW18 5DL
</TEXT>
