<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Economic Viewpoint: What's wrong with economics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SAMUEL BRITTAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Death of Economics is the misleading title of a hyped-up book by Paul
Ormerod out on March 21. Careful reading shows that the author does not want
to bury but to reconstruct economics. Having become chief forecaster for the
National Institute of Economic and Social Research at a precocious age,
Ormerod should have both the team leadership and the computational skills to
make a serious effort to do so later; but this book is not it.
It is easy for Ormerod to score some good hits. While the book was being
written, forecasters failed to predict the Japanese recession, the strength
of the US recovery or the depth of the collapse in the German economy. And
Ormerod is right to condemn the way in which too many economists will
describe someone as a 'sociologist' as a superior form of putdown.
He wrongly assumes, however, that the only opposition to economic
scholasticism comes from the left of the political spectrum, at points
between Marx and Galbraith. He seems not to know the equally trenchant
criticisms from, for instance, the 'Austrian' school - not merely the
card-carrying members but others, such as the more empirical Schumpeter, who
concentrated on entrepreneurial initiative and poured scorn on 'perfect
competition'.
For a while I thought that his book was going to be merely another attack on
Thatcherism and Reaganism disguised as an attack on economics. Fortunately
there is more to the book than that. But Ormerod repeats like a mantra Lady
Thatcher's remark, 'There is no such thing as society', as if merely citing
it were a knock-out blow. For a demonstration that this saying can bear a
civilised and sensible interpretation, I must modestly refer readers to a
publication of my own in the accompanying list.
Ormerod seems half to believe that Thatcher-Reagan economic policies are
based on esoteric, modern General Equilibrium Theory or its close relation,
the New Classical Macroeconomics. Indeed, he accuses Conservative ministers,
as others have done, of not appreciating the extremely unlikely conditions
required for free competition between numerous agents to promote a perfect
allocation of resources.
In fact, neither political leader has been influenced by the New Classicals
or even been much aware of them. The economist who influenced Thatcher in
her formative period was Hayek, who was of course light years from current
New Classical orthodoxy both in style and in substance. He saw markets as
'discovery procedures' which are never in equilibrium and never produce an
optimum, but are the least bad method we know of co-ordinating the
activities of millions of human beings without having to make excessive
demands on their mutual knowledge and love. Thatcher was also influenced by
Hayek's assertion of a relation between a free society and market capitalism
 -topics dismissed by the New Classicals as 'not economics'.
Nearer to his home ground, Ormerod's attempt to attribute ultra free market
policies to mainstream economists flies in the face of all empirical
evidence. The Thatcher era began with the famous letter by 364 economists
denouncing the 1981 Budget - which was much like the last Budget under a
prime minister and chancellor from a very different wing of the Conservative
party. At the end, the Institute of Economic Affairs was discomfited to find
that the majority of the economists it polled deliberately distanced
themselves from government policies, above all the attempts to curb public
spending.
A less pretentious but better-focused critique of current academic economics
appeared last year by the German-American monetary economist, Thomas Mayer,
entitled Truth versus Precision. Mayer admits to favouring competitive
capitalism but to having an interest in income redistribution - for instance
via a negative income tax. He was, also, ejected from the hardline
monetarist Shadow Open Market Committee for deviationism - all of which
biases me in his favour.
Yet his book contains many passages which could equally occur in the
supposedly unique Ormerod book. He reports cynicism among younger, ambitious
academics, who follow practices such as 'sticking in the maths' so that
their articles can be published and they can obtain tenure. Another example
of the folklore of the profession is remarks by graduate students that
'policy is for simpletons'.
Mayer focuses on the practices of economists in the most prestigious
American universities. He complains that precision and mathematical
elegance, which have a legitimate place, have come to play a dominating role
in economics which they do not have even in the natural sciences. Like
Ormerod, Mayer regards what is called the New Classical Economics as, on
balance, a retrograde influence. The main propositions of this school are:
that economic agents behave as if they know the correct model; that markets
normally clear without surpluses or shortages.
The New Classicals are probably best known to practitioners in the financial
markets through the more extreme form of the 'efficient markets' hypothesis
 -which is difficult to reconcile with the recent shake-out in the bond
market, let alone the equity crashes of 1929 or 1987.
Beneath the surface populism, it is Ormerod, not Mayer, who emphasises the
mathematical side of economics. His real crusade is against what he calls
the linear view of mainstream economics. The issue can be safely left to the
modern economics industry with its heavy mathematical bent. Indeed, it is
beginning to use non-linear relationships, for instance by introducing chaos
theory. I wish I could be so confident of its ability to handle policy
problems.
Ormerod's own practical contribution is to point out that the Phillips curve
linking unemployment to inflation is liable to shift its position quite
suddenly. But during any one period, unemployment circles around a
surprisingly stable rate, and normal economic policies seem powerless to
shift the position of that 'attractor point'. This point bears a suspicious
relation to our old friend the non-accelerating inflation rate of
unemployment (or NAIRU), which Ormerod has spent several chapters trying to
kill.
Ormerod rightly complains that forecasting models downplay the role of
profits, which appears as a residual. He himself has a medium-term model
which relates economic growth to the profit share. But he has, as far as I
can tell, no better explanation than anyone else of why the underlying
unemployment rate has moved so adversely (outside the US) in recent decades;
and in his policy recommendations he falls back on work-sharing, which is
for an economist the equivalent of showing the white flag.
What has gone wrong with economics is not that mysterious. It has been the
over-emphasis on economic technique as opposed to underlying ideas. Both the
Keynesian revolution and the monetarist counter-revolution arose from
problems thrown up by real events, while the New Classical school was a
development internal to academic economics. The result, as Mayer points out
more clearly than Ormerod, is that people interested in policy are turning
more and more to schools of government or management consultants, a process
which has its costs, as we see with Clinton's trade policies. But in the end
the academic market, like others, will have to correct itself.
Books cited
Paul Ormerod, The Death of Economics, Faber, Pounds 14.99 (to be published
March 21).
Thomas Mayer, Truth versus Precision in Economics, Edward Elgar.
Thomas Mayer, Monetarism and Macroeconomic Policy, Edward Elgar.
Samuel Brittan, There is no such thing as Society, Social Market Foundation,
20, Queen Anne's Gate, London SW1H 9 AA.
Numbers Guide, Economist Business Books.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
