<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Arts: Monteverdi's 'Venetian Vespers'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD FAIRMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Trying to recreate the golden period of St Mark's, Venice is not easy more
than three centuries later. In the 30 years Monteverdi spent there both he
and the other composers wrote any amount of fine music that has come down to
us, but the atmosphere of that thriving period is inevitably lost.
As research delves ever deeper, so the desire increases to hear the sacred
music performed within the context for which it was intended. Andrew Parrott
and his Tavener Consort have been at the forefront of this movement. On
Tuesday, at St John's, Smith Square, they gave what they claimed to be the
first performance in modern times of the 'Venetian Vespers' set within a
reconstruction of a religious service, as it might have been heard.
This is not the famous Vespers of 1610, written for Mantua. Two collections
were published of the church music that Monteverdi subsequently wrote in
Venice, the latter in 1650 after his death. Parrott has turned to that
posthumous publication and sought to fill it out with additional music to
form a full Vespers service. The extra pieces include instrumental works by
Cavalli, Fontana and Uccellini, and three diverse Monteverdi motets.
A degree of informed guesswork is necessary to put all this in place.
Suffice to say that the result is more varied than simply performing the
1650 Messa et Salmi as it stands. The concentrated thinking of the
Monteverdi psalms is dispersed by light and flamboyant violin sonatas and
the measured, restful sections of plainchant.
Ever since the Tavener Consort's memorable recording of Bach's B Minor Mass
one-to-a-part, it has been clear that Parrott favours private communing, not
public celebration in the performance of religious music. His Monteverdi is
naturally on the same lines (the music for Venice was written with small
instrumental forces in mind).
The solo singing among the Tavener Consort was modest; British singers often
fail to respond to Latin languages and barely a word of the solo 'O quam
pulchra es', for example, was intelligible. It is a shame that Italian
musicians have played so little part in the revival of their great music. St
Mark's is there, awaiting its own musical renaissance.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
