<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Arts: An efficient Swiss pianist - Recital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A year ago, the young Swiss pianist Andreas Haefliger made his Wigmore Hall
debut to great acclaim. When he etched a treble line, one remembered that
his father Ernst has been a Bach tenor of fine, selflessly impassioned
finesse; but Haefliger fils has genial virtues of his own - above all, a
toughly refined lust for what his chosen instrument can be made to do, to
express.
On Tuesday his second Wigmore appearance confirmed all that, but without
striking any new sparks. It was less exciting than his first time round. His
best came at opposite ends of the evening. First, in Beethoven's A-flat
Sonata op. 26 he pursued long, lyrical sense high and low, whilst doing full
honour to the big contrasts between movements. That was a performance of
lovely, controlled warmth. At the end Haefliger flung several Rakhmaninov
preludes and etudes-tableaux at us with terrific energy and flair.
That last splash made up for some faceless playing in mid-programme. Last
year, this pianist expounded Schumann's Davidsbundlertanze with a rare,
judicious boldness, turning boudoir subtleties into more vital stuff. This
time the same composer's Kreisleriana fared less well. Though Haefliger
delivered its almost incessant etude-figurations in great sweeps, a heart
more candidly on the sleeve would have been welcome. Too much of the
sequence sounded of a smooth, efficient muchness. As a whole Kreisleriana is
super-charged, intricate and harried; we need warmer idylls when Schumann
can suspend his virtuoso machinery in favour of lean, poignant effusions.
It may be that Haefliger's cool-ish Kreisleriana, and his un-visionary Sixth
Sonata of Skryabin - expert and tremulously decadent though it was - lost
out simply through imperfect rapport with the instrument, or with the
Wigmore acoustic. One felt him loyally suppressing his own
piano-personality, when we would have liked to hear it plain.
At least his Rakhmaninov group was extrovert and exhilarating, with
rapid-fire chord-showers. Just before it, every one of Sofia Gubaidulina's 9
Pieces from 'Musical Toys' enjoyed an original half-jokey resonance of its
own. A cartoon-picturesque episode here, a laconic moral there, a touch of
grace somewhere else: genuinely creative, appealing fun, and not trivial at
all.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
