<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Technology: Patent benefit on-line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM CLAYTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
From this month , it will be much easier to find patents held at the British
Library in central London. The increasing use of CD-Rom is helping to
control the largest collection in the world, with material from Europe, the
US and Japan.
The library contains 34m patents, increasing by about 1m a year. To cope
with this volume of material, plus a year's worth of scientific books and
periodicals also housed at the library, requires almost 2km of extra shelf
space each year.
Many people come in person to search the collection; more use the library's
Patent Express service which sends copies by post, courier and fax.
People search the collections for various reasons. Inventors need to be sure
their brainchild is original. Companies use searches to watch competitors or
guard against wasteful research and development.
Recently, the process of applying for a patent has become much easier. Under
the European Patent Convention only a single application is needed for a
patent to be granted in up to 14 countries. In addition, the Patent
Co-operation Treaty provides the basis for a single international
application.
Eighteen months after a successful application, a patent is published by the
Patent Office and can be anything from two or three pages in length to
several hundred, the average being 10 to 12. As well as being printed
conventionally, a copy is scanned and put on to a CD-Rom which can hold
about 1,000.
An exchange network has been set up between patent libraries around the
world which swap CD-Roms.
The development is also bringing significant benefits for both storage and
searching. Looking through an on-line database is obviously quicker than
consulting bound volumes on the shelves and makes it possible to carry out
complicated searches.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3572 Computer Storage Devices.
    P7375 Information Retrieval Services.
    P6794 Patent Owners and Lessors.
</IN>
