<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Technology: A good read on screen - Digitalisation and
CD-Rom are shaking up the publishing industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTORIA GRIFFITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Books have changed surprisingly little since the printing press was invented
400 years ago, but a metamorphosis may soon set in. Digitalisation and
CD-Rom technology, which allow vast amounts of information to be stored on a
compact disc, are shaking up the staid publishing sector.
'A book today looks pretty much like it did a century or two ago,' says
Valerie Hyman, a member of the faculty at the Poynter Institute media
think-tank in Florida. 'But technological changes will profoundly affect
this industry over the next two decades.'
Known as electronic publishing or computerised publishing, these changes are
already calling into question the very concept of a book. One company,
Voyager, is already printing books on CD-Rom for reading on a computer
screen. Other companies are exploring book-on-demand printing, which offers
custom-designed texts.
'Publishing in the future will look more like a computer database,' says
Joseph Dionne, chairman and chief executive officer of McGraw-Hill, which is
becoming increasingly involved in electronic publishing. 'The idea is to be
able to mix up the information and give to customers exactly what they want
when they want it.'
Primis, a subsidiary of McGraw-Hill which was developed with technology from
Eastman Kodak and RR Donnelly, has put a new slant on the textbook market by
allowing for customised printing at the bookstore. A professor 'designs' a
textbook by selecting chapters, passages and other information from a
selection of materials.
The data are then digitalised and stored in Primis' computer. A student who
needs the textbook can walk into a bookstore, place an order and receive the
book through a computer link-up in a matter of minutes. (Primis' printers
put out 90 pages a minute.) So far, only a small number of bookstores have
this capability, but Primis expects the market to grow.
The computerised method offers a number of advantages. 'The professor gets a
textbook that exactly fits the course material,' says Suzanne Bedell,
publisher at Primis. 'And the students don't have to spend money for
extraneous materials.' The textbooks can also be updated easily from
semester to semester, particularly important for courses in the sciences and
politics.
Xerox also wants to enter on-demand publishing. The company introduced
high-speed Docu-Tech printers into the market four years ago and has been
building up a database. Xerox is operating on-demand printing in about 30
test sites and plans to launch the product in the general market later this
year.
'One problem for us has been binding the book on-site,' says Peter Galton,
marketing manager for Docu-Tech. 'But this year, we'll be introducing the
capability to create covers on the spot. We can do either case-bound
hardbacks or perfect-bound paperbacks.' Xerox says it will also be able to
print colour illustrations and graphics in the Docu-Tech products. 'Once you
capture the information digitally, you can print almost anything,' says
Galton.
With the move to digitalisation, the lines between fiction, film, education,
books, research and entertainment will become increasingly fuzzy. Primis
already has plans to include videos of professors' lectures with some of its
products.
Voyager has gone a step further by trying to change not only the way books
are put together but also the way they are read. It is marketing books on
CD-Rom which are meant to be read on the computer. The company's version of
Macbeth, for instance, features Shakespeare's original text, additional
annotations, and a computer-screen video of a performance of the play by the
Royal Shakespeare Company.
If a reader does not understand a word, explanations and definitions can be
revealed by putting the indicator on a word, and pressing a key. Other
annotations can be obtained in a similar way. At any point in the text, the
reader can also activate the video; this appears in the corner of the
computer screen and the pages of the text automatically turn as the play
progresses.
'As CD-Rom technology progresses to include more memory, we hope to expand
the video part of the screen and diminish the text,' says Michael Cohen,
producer/editor at Voyager.
Electronic publishing is bound to trigger profound changes in the industry.
The concept of bookshops and libraries may change completely. 'The bookstore
and library of the future will hold no inventory, just databases,' says
Dionne. The idea is that customers will make their selections from the
computer, and leave with their computer disc or on-demand book in hand.
By reducing up-front costs for the publisher, the technology may help new
authors. 'Because the publisher doesn't have to invest in printing hundreds
or thousands of books that might not be sold, this lowers the risk to
publishers,' says Paul Aiken, attorney for the Authors' Guild. 'That means
they should be more willing to take a chance on new authors, and this should
allow more titles to become available on the market.'
However, the guild is concerned about how the technology will keep track of
copyright. 'If just a chapter of someone's book is being used, how will the
payment be accounted for?' Aiken asks. 'And what if the author doesn't want
the work taken out of context like that? These are complex issues that must
be addressed.'
Another uncertainty is the extent to which the reading of books on the
computer will take the place of reading a printed book. 'I think there's
room for both,' says Galton. 'Computer screen books may be appealing in some
instances, but there's something aesthetic about a bound book, and something
comforting about curling up in bed with a book.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
