<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / People: Clinch goes full blast into ICI in UK
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Australian Peter Clinch, 53, has been given the job of putting a bit more
bang behind ICI Explosives, the world's biggest supplier of commercial
explosives and blasting technology. He replaces Bob Clark, 57, as chief
executive of ICI Explosives, on April 1.
Clinch, an executive director of ICI Australia, takes charge of a company
which can trace its origins back to Alfred Nobel, who invented dynamite in
1867. Nobel Industries was one of the four companies which merged to form
ICI in 1926.
ICI Explosives, which recently moved its headquarters back to Britain from
Canada, is one of ICI's five core businesses. In terms of turnover of Pounds
643m it is ICI's smallest business but last year its trading profits of
Pounds 52m accounted for nearly a fifth of the total.
Clinch, who has a civil engineering degree from Sydney University, joined
ICI in 1965 as a works study engineer at the group's plastics factory in
Botany Bay. Bob Clark, who has headed ICI Explosives since 1988, retires in
June after 33 years with the group.
</TEXT>
