<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / People: Maxwell: new man for the Pru
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
John Maxwell, ousted from his job as chief executive of plasterboard
manufacturer BPB Industries after only nine months, has turned up in the
position of corporate development director for the Prudential, Britain's
largest insurer.
Chief executive Mick Newmarch says he is very pleased to have Maxwell
aboard, and that his new recruit turned down at least two other 'very
senior' jobs in favour of the Pru. Maxwell was reckoned to have done a good
job as finance director of BPB, but to have found the transition to chief
executive difficult in an industry he previously knew nothing about. He was
also criticised for spending too much time talking to the City. Between 1986
and 1992, however, he had run the Provincial Group, the UK's largest
privately-owned financial services company, and had also previously had
experience at Grand Metropolitan and Rank Xerox.
Two years ago, Newmarch brought in Laurel Powers-Freeling as head of group
strategy, but, unlike Maxwell, not on to the main board. She has, according
to her wish, recently transferred to line management, supervising the Pru's
attempts to reach higher networth, more financially aware customers, says
Newmarch. Now that the overall strategy has been enunciated, it is Maxwell's
job to monitor its implementation.
At the same time, Sir Martin Jacomb, 63, becomes a non-executive director.
Jacomb has recently stepped down from the deputy chairmanships of Barclays
Bank and Commercial Union.
A former deputy chairman of the Securities &amp; Investments Board, he was a
central architect of the City's self-regulatory structure, whereas Newmarch
is a vociferous advocate of a single tier of statutory regulation for retail
financial services. 'I concede I honestly hadn't contemplated that,' says
Newmarch, who points out that his own concerns about self-regulation pertain
to retail rather than institutional business. 'We have had a series of
conversations, but we haven't discussed that. No doubt he'll offer his
opinion, but he'll also listen to ours.'
Jim Sutcliffe, deputy md of the home service division, also joins the main
board.
</TEXT>
<XX>
