<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / People: Brady lends weight to UK funds
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Nicholas Brady, the former US treasury secretary and designer of the Latin
American debt reduction process, is lending his weight to two UK funds
investing heavily in the region. He is to become non-executive chairman of
both Templeton Emerging Markets investment trust, which has large holdings
in Latin America, and the newly-launched Templeton Latin American investment
trust.
Brady was appointed to the US treasury by Ronald Reagan, and continued to
serve under George Bush. His name became linked to Latin America when he
came up with a mechanism for lifting the region's burden of debt by
exchanging reduced debt for bonds. Before joining the treasury, Brady's
career was in investment banking, with Dillon, Read &amp; Co. He left office in
January 1993 when Clinton took over.
Brady recently became head of Darby Overseas Investments, a Washington-based
company also investing in Latin America. Daniel Marx, the managing director
of Darby, is to become a non-executive director of Templeton's Latin
American trust. Marx was formerly a debt negotiator for Argentina, and until
recently the under-secretary of finance there. He has taken an active role
in the Argentinian privatisation process; about 20 companies are due to be
privatised within two years.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Templeton Emerging Markets Investment Trust.
    Templeton Latin American Investment Trust.
</CO>
