<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 94 / Accountancy Column: Transformation of practice not always as
easy as ABC - A look at the challenges facing management accounting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL BROMWICH and ALNOOR BHIMANI
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Since the late 1980s, management accounting has faced the strongest and most
vociferous challenges ever for its transformation. The profession needs to
embrace new initiatives without throwing out all the experience of the past.
New forms of technology, 'leaner' production and organisational processes,
and demands for product quality and diversity at the lowest cost have all
encouraged more receptive attitudes to new management ideas. There has been
a greater willingness to question existing long established practices, and
to borrow ideas from other countries.
Advocates of the transformation of management accounting have urged the use
of a rich portfolio of new techniques and processes including activity-based
costing (ABC) - which allocates overheads between the different components
of the production process - and its more advanced variants, such as
activity-based budgeting and activity-based cost management.
Our new book* that coincides with the 75th anniversary of the Chartered
Institute of Management Accountants proposes various immediate needs for
change. It also warns of the pitfalls of jettisoning management accounting
approaches which have stood the test of time in favour of unthinkingly
deploying a variety of emerging accounting techniques which are not proven
to be superior.
First, it is essential to recognise that the management accountant has a
duty to go beyond fulfilling a watchdog function and needs positively to
develop mechanisms of significant use to managers.
One area of great promise is a much greater use of non-financial
information, reflecting the enormous explosion of - often real time -
information available from production processes. At present, there is a lack
of research and documented practical experience of the changes needed in
management accounting in globalised businesses.
The current fast pace of developments has created an environment generally
conducive to reform, making it far easier for the accountant to act as an
agent of change than ever before. This is especially true when working in
cross-functional managerial teams operating near to the market. Management
accountants can help mobilise managers in ways which would otherwise be
neglected.
Accounting mechanisms do not operate in isolation from organisational or
managerial factors. In exploring the potential of novel techniques in
management accounting, attention must be paid to inter-relationships between
accounting activities and other business processes. Accounting must be
grounded far more fully in the technology of the enterprises than
previously.
Many companies are experimenting with new accounting approaches, and others
have gone further. Novelty has become convention in many cases and the
change is irreversible.
However, even a combination of new techniques can neither shore up a poorly
managed organisation nor convert badly managed businesses into those on the
leading edge. Such typical problems need far more than a change in
accounting techniques.
Accounting's role often expands as enterprise activities grow. For example,
manufacturer-supplier relationships are in many industries becoming much
more partnership oriented, allowing greater contact between purchasers and
suppliers. This requires an expansion of the role of accounting in
channelling information effectively and in helping to improve the joint
efficiency of such partnerships.
It seems to be difficult to make significant changes to accounting systems,
perhaps because they reflect both informal and formal organisational
structures and may help to sustain the organisation's power structure.
For whatever reason, it can be reasonably said that only about 10 per cent
of large companies are using activity-based costing in a substantial way.
Many others are still thinking about it or are involved in fairly minor
experiments.
There is no doubt that activity-based costing is better than using simply
the volume of production units when trying to understand overheads that vary
directly as a result of clear and unique factors.
However, the conditions required to legitimately apply these approaches are
more restrictive than has been recognised. The use of ABC works best where
factors that affect costs can be identified and where each activity can be
demonstrated or assumed to be relatively unaffected by the level of the
company's other activities.
Its use in suitable circumstances helps to make understandable the behaviour
of some costs which are presently lumped together as overheads and then
allocated. It also helps to make the behaviour of some costs far more
visible, especially those which yield benefits to the consumer. These
include quality and warranty, and those associated with manufacturing
flexibility, which are more controllable and more susceptible to cost
management. By contrast, traditional management accounting methods submerge
these costs as general overheads.
A significant contribution of ABC is the strategic and management questions
it poses, making the technique a general decision-making tool rather than
purely an accounting technique.
Accounting control measures can be used in a way that sometimes induces
short termism by managers. The concern with monthly variances, many of which
are beyond the control of managers, provides one example. In many instances,
planning and monitoring performance may be improved if the emphasis is
shifted away from the specific responsibility for mistakes to using the
information for re-planning and development.
There is a strong argument for companies to introduce a strategic dimension
to accounting. They should determine the costs associated with strategies
employed by the business and monitor the cost structure of competitors.
Strategic management accounting (SMA) seeks to make such costs visible to
management and allows strategy to be forced down the organisation. A major
difficulty possibly inhibiting the use of SMA is the perception that it
makes impossible information demands. However, much of the information
needed for strategic management accounting is already collected by 'well
managed' companies.
The Japanese practice of 'target costing' has a role to play here. Target
costing takes the price of a product or service from the market, thereby
determining the maximum production cost required to support this price, and
seeks in planning to reduce existing costs to such a level.
It is not suggested that this and other Japanese techniques should be
unthinkingly introduced. But their emphasis on using accounting for
continuous cost reduction, such as 'taxing' expensive uses of components or
labour, should be considered.
Leading edge management accounting in both theory and practice is addressing
relevant modern problems tied to the search for world class competitiveness,
customer orientation and dynamic entrepreneurialism.
A major aim must be to position the management accountant to play a full
role in both the increasing number of more informally managed and
cross-functional organisations and in the full set of relationships
encountered in modern organisations.
These are key ingredients of growth, not just for the profession but for
industrial concerns and the national economy as a whole.
Michael Bromwich is CIMA professor and Alnoor Bhimani is lecturer of
accounting at the London School of Economics.
*Management Accounting: Pathways to Progress. Publishing Department, CIMA,
63 Portland Place, London WIN 4AB. Pounds 12.95
</TEXT>
